[
  {
    "daf": 2,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What is the earliest time to recite Keri'as Sh'ma shel Arvis?\n(b) Rebbi Eliezer gives the final time to recite it as the end of the first night watch (of angels), which is equivalent to the end of the fourth hour (i.e. one third of the night). What do ...\n1. ... the Chachamim and ...\n2. ... Raban Gamliel, respectively say?\n(c) So why did the custom evolve to recite the Sh'ma before nightfall, and what are one's obligations as regards reciting it again after nightfall?\n(d) Why did Chazal decree that the Mitzvos whose prescribed time is until morning, should be performed before midnight?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What is the 'Hekter Chalavim ve'Eivarim' discussed by the Mishnah?\n(b) What is the difference between the Chalavim and the Eivarim?\n(c) Until when must it be performed?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) The Tana takes the Mitzvah of K'ri'as Sh'ma for granted.   From which Pasuk in Va'eschanan do we learn it?\n(b) Which other Kashya do we answer with the same Pasuk?\n(c) From which Pasuk in Bereishis might the Tana also have taken his cue?\n(d) Why does the Tana not conclude the discussion of K'ri'as Sh'ma shel Arvis immediately? Why did he continue only later in the Perek?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) Considering that the Kohanim eat their T'rumah at nightfall, why did the Tana not simply write that the time for reciting the Sh'ma shel Arvis is nightfall?\n(b) In that case, how must we interpret \"u'Va ha'Shemesh\" and  \"Vetaher\"?\n(c) What else could the phrase mean?\n(d) On what grounds does Rabah bar Rav Shiloh reject that interpretation?\n(e) Which Beraisa did the Chachamim of Eretz Yisrael cite which brought them to the same conclusion?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) According to the Beraisa, the earliest time to recite the Sh'ma is when an Ani (a poor man) comes in from work to eat his bread dipped in salt, and the final time (for everyone) is when he gets up from his meal. The Seifa is definitely stating a new (fourth) opinion, over and above the three stated in our Mishnah.   How do we initially reconcile the Reisha with our Mishnah?\n(b) We query this from yet another Beraisa, where Rebbi Meir gives the earliest time to read the Sh'ma as 'when people come in to eat their bread on Friday night'.  What do the Chachamim say?\n(c) What Siman do they give to mark their opinion?\n(d) And they even cite a Pasuk in Nechemyah describing how some of the people used to work, what did the others used to do?\n(e) From when till when does the Pasuk present in describing this?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) The Tana then cites another Pasuk there which writes that the night was for work, and the day for guarding. Why is the first Pasuk alone not sufficient proof that night is gauged from when the stars come out? How is the proof strengthened by the second Pasuk?\n(b) We now think that 'Ani' and 'people' are one and the same.   What problem does this create, if, as we learned earlier 'Ani' and 'Kohen' are also one and the same?\n(c) How do we counter the suggestion that Ani and Kohen cannot therefore be the same Shi'ur?\n(d) We conclude however, that the reverse is true from yet another Beraisa, which we will now discuss. Rebbi Eliezer gives the time to recite K'ri'as Sh'ma as from when Shabbos comes in.   When exactly is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yehoshua mean when he says from the time that the Kohanim become Tahor to eat T'rumah?\n(b) What similar Shi'ur does Rebbi Meir give?\n(c) On what basis does Rebbi Yehudah disagree with Rebbi Meir?\n(d) What did he say in Bameh Madlikin that serves as the basis for his objection?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Chanina gives the Shi'ur of Ani (that we discussed earlier). What final Shi'ur does Rav Acha (or Rav Acha'i) give?\n(b) How do we now prove once and for all that the Shi'ur of 'Ani' and that of 'Kohen' cannot be one and the same (in which case, that of 'Ani' and 'people' in the Beraisa above, can and are one and the same)?\n(c) Who is the author of our Mishnah, which gives the Shi'ur as 'Kohen'?\n(d) Rebbi Chanina gives the Shi'ur of 'Ani'. Based on the fact that Rebbi Eliezer gives the Shi'ur as 'when Shabbos comes in', how do we know that the Shi'ur of 'Ani' is later than that of 'Kohen'?\n(e) What is therefore the correct sequence of these three Shi'urim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) We already cited Rebbi Yehudah's Kashya on Rebbi Meir ('when the Kohanim Tovel') that the Kohanim Tovel before Bein-ha'Shemashos, and this does not conform with the Pasuk \"be'Shochb'cha\".   How does Rebbi Meir counter Rebbi Yehudah's Kashya?\n(b) How do we reconcile Rebbi Meir in one Beraisa (from the time that people come in to eat on Erev Shabbos) with what he says in the other Beraisa (Kohanim), which is earlier?\n(c) What is the problem with Rebbi Eliezer in the Beraisa, who gives the earliest time for reciting the Sh'ma as when Shabbos comes in?\n(d) One answer is that Rebbi Eliezer's opinion, like that of Rebbi Meir, is a Machlokes Tana'im.   What is the alternative answer?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 3,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Some hold that there are three Mishmaros of angels every night.   What do others say?\n(b) What problem do we now have with Rebbi Eliezer in our Mishnah, who gives the final time for the Sh'ma as 'until the end of the first watch'? What ought he to have said?\n(c) We answer that he holds that there are three Mashmaros.  Why did he then refer to the end of the first watch, and not state specifically 'until four hours'?\n(d) What is therefore the significance of the Pasuk in Yirmiyah \"Hash-m mi'Marom Yish'ag\", when does it occur?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) If one can recognize the first watch by the donkeys braying the dogs barking (respectively), what happens at the third watch?\n(b) The beginning of the first watch is the advent of night and the end of the third, the advent of day (neither of which require a sign). Why then, does Rebbi Eliezer see fit to give a sign?\n(c) Alternatively, he is referring to the end of the watches.   Why then does he need to give a sign at the end of the third watch?\n(d) What does Hash-m say by each Mishmar?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yossi once entered one of the ruins of Yerushalayim to Daven, and Eliyahu waited for him at the entrance until he concluded his Tefilah.   What did Rebbi Yossi reply when Eliyahu greeted him with the words 'Shalom alecha, Rebbi'?\n(b) What did ...\n1. ... Eliyahu remark in connection with the fact that Rebbi Yossi had Davened in a ruin?\n2. ... Rebbi Yossi reply?\n(c) How did Eliyahu counter that?\n(d) Which three things did Rebbi Yossi learn from this episode?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) In answer to Eliyahu's query, Rebbi Yossi informed him that he heard a Bas Kol (a Heavenly Voice) cooing like a dove.   What did the Bas Kol declare)?\n(b) What did Eliyahu comment on that? How often does the Bas Kol make this declaration?\n(c) And what did he tell him about Hash-m's reaction when Yisrael enter the Batei Keneisi'os and the Batei Medrashos, and loudly proclaim \"Amein, Yehei Shemei ha'Gadol Mevorach ... \"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) Two of the three reasons given by the Beraisa why one should  enter a ruin are because of suspicion and because of danger.   What is the third?\n(b) What does the Tana mean by ...\n1. ... suspicion?\n2. ... danger?\n(c) Seeing as there is the reason of danger, why does the Tana need to add the reason of suspicion?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) How do we answer the Kashya why we need the reason of suspicion, since we have the reason of demons?\n(b) How do we counter the Kashya that if that is so, the reason of suspicion does not apply either?\n(c) In the same vein, why do we need the reason of ...\n1. ... collapse? Why will the reasons of suspicion and demons not suffice?\n2. ... demons, when we have the reasons of suspicion and collapse?\n(d) How might we answer the last Kashya even when there is only one person?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi in a Beraisa, the night comprises four Mishmaros.   What does Rebbi Nasan say?\n(b) How does Rebbi Nasan learn this from the Pasuk in Shoftim, which, in connection with the story of Gideon, refers to 'the middle watch'?\n(c) How does ...\n1. ... Rebbi counter this?\n2. ... Rebbi Nasan refute Rebbi's answer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rebbi now prove that there are four Mishmaros based on the two Pesukim in Tehilim \"Chatzos Laylah Akum ... \" . and \"Kidmu Eynai Ashmuros\"?\n(b) How does Rebbi Nasan initially explain those Pesukim, based on Rebbi Yehoshua in the Mishnah later, who explains that it was the way of kings to arise in three hours?\n(c) Rav Ashi answers 'Mashmarah u'Palga Nami Mishmaros Kari l'hu'.   What does he mean by that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Z'rika ... Amar Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi permit one to say in front of a dead person?\n(b) According to one Lashon, Rebbi Aba bar Kahana explains that this is only meant to exclude Divrei Torah.   Why may one not say Divrei Torah in front of a Meis?\n(c) What do others quoting Rebbi Aba bar Kahana say?\n(d) Why is this statement, which has no direct connection to the Sugya, cited here?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) We query the earlier statement that David used to rise at midnight from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Kidamti ba'Neshef Va'ashave'ah\".   Based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"be'Neshef be'Erev Yom... \", when did he used to get up?\n(b) To answer the Kashya, how does Rav Oshaya Amar Rav Acha interpret \"Chatzos Laylah Akum ... \" by combining it with \"Kidamti ba'Neshef\"?\n(c) According to Rebbi Zeira, David would doze like a horse till midnight and strengthen himself like a lion from midnight and onwards.   How does Rav Ashi answer the Kashya by dividing the night into two parts? What did he do before midnight and what did he do afterwards?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) We also query the earlier translation of Neshef as nighttime from the Pasuk in Shmuel \"Vayakem David me'ha'Neshef ad ha'Erev\".   How do we initially translate that Pasuk?\n(b) If, as we suggest \"Neshef\" in the latter Pasuk also means nighttime, Why does the Pasuk say \"me'ha'Neshef ad ha'Erev le'Macharasam\", and not \"me'ha'Neshef ad ha'Neshef\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) We ask that, if Moshe could not discern the exact moment when midnight was, how could David ha'Melech have known it?   Based on the premise that \"ka'Chatzos\" means 'at around midnight', what makes us think that ...\n1. ... Hash-m could not possibly have told Moshe 'ka'Chatzos'?\n2. ... Moshe did not know when midnight was?\n(b) We initially answer Chasida that David ha'Melech, like Moshe Rabeinu, could not possibly have known on his own the exact moment of midnight. And that his knowledge was based on a statement of Rav Chana bar Bizna Amar Rebbi Shimon Chasida Which statement?\n(c) At dawn-break, the Chachamim would enter and inform David that the people needed Parnasah.   What would David reply?\n(d) The Chachamim would respond with 'Ein ha'Komeitz Masbi'a es ha'Ari'.   What was the second half of their statement?\n(e) What does the statement mean?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What would David then instruct them to do?\n(b) There followed four stages, all contained in the Pasuk in Divrei ha'Yamim \"ve'Acharei Achitofel, Benayahu ben Yehoyada, ve'Evyasar, ve'Sar Tzeva la'Melech Yo'av\".   If, as Rav Yosef explains, Achitofel represented the war-ministry, and Benayahu ben Yehoyada, the Sanhedrin, what was the significance of Evyasar and Yo'av?\n(c) Why were the 'Urim ve'Tumim' also called the 'K'reisi u'Peleisi'?\n(d) From which Pasuk in Tehilim does Rebbi Yitzchak bar Ada (or ... b'reih de'Rav Idi) learn about David's harp?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 4,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Zeira explains that Moshe Rabeinu and David ha'Melech both knew exactly when midnight was.   Why then, did David require a harp?\n(b) Why did Moshe change the words of Hash-m from \"ba'Chatzos Laylah\" to \"ka'Chatzos Laylah\"?\n(c) Rav Ashi answers that \"ka'Chatzos\" is not a noun, meaning 'at around midnight', but a verb, which means 'when the night is split'.  When was Moshe speaking to Yisrael and what exactly did he tell them?\n(d) The first reason is based on a statement of Mar.   What did Mar say about training oneself to say 'I don't know'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the Pasuk \"le'David, Shamrah Nafshi ki Chasid Ani\", Levi and Rebbi Yitzchak argue over why David referred to himself as a Chasid. One explained that it was because he used to arise at midnight to praise Hash-m, in spite of the prevalent custom of other Kings of that time to get up only in the third hour of the morning.   What did the other one say?\n(b) What was the name of David's Rebbe?\n(c) What did he (David) used to say to him?\n(d) In fact, his real name was Ishboshes (or Eshba'al).   Then why was he called 'Mefivoshes'? What is Mefivoshes the acronym of?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) As a reward, David fathered a son called Kil'av, whose name, Rebbi Yochanan teaches us, was Daniel.   Then why was he called 'Kil'av'? What is Kil'av the acronym of?\n(b) We cite two Pesukim in Tehilim which describe David's joy at having such a son.   What is the significance of the final words of the latter Pasuk \"Ve'ashivah Chorfi Davar\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) We query the fact that David referred to himself as a Chasid from the dots on the word \"Lulei\" in the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Lulei He'emanti Lir'os be'Tuv Hash-m be'Eretz Chayim\".   Based on those dots, what does Rebbi Yossi in a Beraisa quote David ha'Melech as having said to Hash-m?\n(b) How do we explain the fact that one moment David refers to himself as a Chasid and the next, he is not even sure that he will go to Olam ha'Ba?\n(c) And we support this answer with a statement by Rav Ya'akov bar Idi, to reconcile the Pasuk in Vayeitzei \"ve'Hinei Anochi Imach u'Shemarticha ... \" with the Pasuk in Vayishlach \"Vayira Ya'akov Me'od Vayeitzer lo\".   What is the problem?\n(d) How did Rav Ya'akov bar Idi solve the problem?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) (e) A practical application of Rav Ya'akov bar Idi's answer occurred in connection with the Pasuk in the Shirah \"... ad Ya'avor Amcha Hash-m, ad Ya'avor Am Zu Kanisa\".   What are the two 'ad Ya'avors' referring to?\n(b) Based on the repetition of exactly the same words, what ought to have happened?\n(c) What prevented it from actually taking place?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) The Rabbanan hold that one must read the Sh'ma by midnight.   Do they hold in principle, like Rebbi Eliezer (the end of the first watch) or like Rabbanan Gamliel (the whole night) in the previous Mishnah)?\n(b) Why is that?\n(c) Then in which point do they argue with him?\n(d) What were they afraid a personmight do?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) How did they therefore present a worker's order of priorities when he arrives home in the evening after work?\n(b) One of the reasons that Chazal said specifically here, that someone who transgresses the words of the Chachamim, is Chayav Misah,is because of the strong likelihood of one's falling asleep (as we explained).   What is the other reason?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa we just quoted said 'Korei K'ri'as Sh'ma u'Mispalel' serves as a support for the of pinion of Rebbi Yochanan.   What did Rebbi Yochanan say about juxtaposing Ge'ulah next to Tefilah?\n(b) What does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi hold in this matter?\n(c) What is the basis of their Machlokes if it is based ...\n1. ... on logic?\n2. ... on the Hekesh of \"u've'Shochbecha\" to \"u've'Kumecha\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Mar b'rei de'Ravina queries Rebbi Yochanan from the Mishnah 'ba'Erev Mevarech Sh'tayim ... le'Acharehah'.   What is the Kashya?\n(b) What do we answer? Why is 'Hashkiveinu' not an interruption between Ge'ulah and Tefilah?\n(c) How do we prove this from Shachris, where a similar concept applies?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Elazar bar Avina say about anybody who recites 'Tehilah le'David' (Ashrei) three times each day?\n(b) We initially refute the suggestion that this is because ...\n1. ... its Pesukim follow the 'Alef-Beis', because in that case, we ought to say the chapter in Tehilim \"Ashrei Temimei Derech\".   What advantage does that chapter have over \"Tehilah le'David\"?\n2. ... of the importance of the Pasuk \"Pose'ach es Yadecha ... \", because in that case, we might just as well recite Hallel ha'Gadol.   What is 'Hallel ha'Gadol'?\n(c) Which similar Pasuk does Hallel ha'Gadol contain?\n(d) Why then, do we say specifically \"Tehilah le'David\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yochanan asked why the 'Nun' missing from the opening letters of the Pesukim of \"Tehilah le'David\".   What did he answer?\n(b) Which Pasuk in Amos is the source for this concept?\n(c) How did the B'nei Eretz Yisrael read the Pasuk in Amos to soften its meaning?\n(d) And what does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak say to explain how David ha'Melech nevertheless subtly inserted the 'Nun' in a softer manner?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Elazar bar Avina also discusses the difference between the angel Gavriel and the angel Micha'el.   What does he extrapolate from the fact that with regard to the former, Yeshayah writes \" Vaya'af eilai Echad min ha'Serafim\", whereas Daniel writes \"ve'ha'Ish Gavriel ... \" Mu'af Bi'af \"?\n(b) What do we learn from the Gezeirah-Shavah \"Echad\" (in the above Pasuk in Yeshayah) \"Echad\" (in Daniel) \"ve'Hinei Micha'el Echad min ha'Sarim ... \"?\n(c) The Beraisa corroborates Rebbi Elazar bar Avina statement and elaborates.   If Eliyahu takes four steps, how many steps does the Angel of Death take?\n(d) On what occasion does the Angel of Death take only one step?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi say about reciting the Sh'ma before going to bed, even though one has already recited it at Ma'ariv?\n(b) From which Pasuk in Tehilim does Rav Asi (or Rav Yosef) learn it?\n(c) What does Rav Nachman (bar Yitzchak) say about a Talmid-Chacham?\n(d) According to Abaye however,, even a Talmid-Chacham is obligated to say at least one Pasuk of Rachamim.   Which Pasuk in Tehilim does he cite as an example?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 5,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Levi bar Chama quoting Resh Lakish states that one should always incite the Yeitzer Tov over the Yeitzer ha'Ra, as the Pasuk in Tehilim writes \"Rigzu ve'Al Techeta'u\".   Which two stages follow, in the event that the first one does not succeed to vanquish the enemy, should the first stage not succeed?\n(b) How does he learn them from the continuation of the Pasuk?\n(c) And in the Pasuk \"Va'etnah l'cha es Luchos ha'Even, ve'ha'Torah ve'ha'Mitzvah, asher Kasavti Lehorosam\", if Rav Levi bar Chama ... interprets \"Luchos\" as the Ten Commandments, \"ha'Torah\", as the written Torah, and \"ha'Mitzvah\", as the oral Torah (Mishnah), how does he interpret ...\n1. ... \"asher Kasavti\"?\n2. ... \"Lehorosam\"?\n(d) What does he say about them?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rav Yitzchak interpret the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Romemos Keil bi'Geronam, ve'Cherev Pi'fiyos be'Yadam\", based on the words \" ... Cherev Pifiyos\"?\n(b) Mar Zutra or Rav Ashi learn that this refers to 'K'ri'as Sh'ma she'Al ha'Mitah' from the previous Pasuk.   What does the previous Pasuk say?\n(c) What is the purpose of the sword?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) With reference to the Pasuk in Iyov \"u'Venei Reshef Yagbihu Of\", how does Rebbi Yitzchak translate the word ...\n1. ...  \"Reshef\" (based on the Pasuk in Ha'azinu \"M'zei Ra'av u'Lechumei Reshef ... \")?\n(b) \"Of\" (based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"ha'Sa'if Einecha bo ve'Einenu\")?\n(c) Rebbi Yitzchak therefore explains the Pasuk to mean that someone who recites Keri'as Sh'ma she'Al ha'Mitah (which is also considered Torah, as we shall see later), will remove from himself the power of the demons.   How does Resh Lakish, who translates \"Reshef\" as 'Yisurin' (suffering) interpret it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rebbi Yochanan query Resh Lakish from the Pasuk in Beshalach \"Kol ha'Machalah asher Samti ve'Mitzrayim Lo Asim Alecha, ki Ani Hash-m Rof'echa\"?\n(b) Rebbi Yochanan therefore cites the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Ne'elamti Dumyah Hecheseisi mi'Tuv, u'Che'eivi Ne'ekar\".   Based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Ki Lekach Tov Nasati lachem Torasi, Al Ta'azovu\", how does he translate the word \"mi'Tuv\"?\n(c) How does he now explain the Pasuk in Tehilim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What is generally the difference between the person who sells an object that is his and the person who buys it?\n(b) What does Rav Zeira (or Rebbi Chanina bar Papa) from the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Ki Lekach Tov Nasati lachem Torasi, Al Ta'azovu\"?\n(c) How does he learn from there that Hash-m is happy with the sale?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav (or Rav Chisda) learn (in connection with Yisurin) from the Pasuk ...\n1. ... in Eichah \"Nachp'sah Deracheinu ve'Nachkorah, ve'Nashuvah ad Hash-m\"?\n2. ... in Tehilim \"Ashrei ha'Gever asher Teyas'renu Kah, u'mi'Torascha Selam'denu\"?\n(b) Assuming that he cannot even find the sin of Bitul Torah, to what should he attribute his suffering, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Ki es asher Ye'ehav Hash-m Yochi'ach (for He rebukes the one whom He loves)\"?\n(c) What is the meaning of 'Yisurin shel Ahavah'?\n(d) And what does Rava quoting Rav S'chorah learn from the Pasuk ...\n1. ... in Mishlei \"va'Hashem Chafetz Dak'o Hecheli\"?\n2. ... there \"Im Tasim Asham Asham Nafsho\"? What is the significance of the Korban Asham here?\n(e) What happens to someone who accepts Yisurin shel Ahavah in good faith?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Ya'akov bar Idi and Rebbi Acha bar Chanina argue over the definition of Yisurin shel Ahavah. According to one, based on the Pasuk in Tehilim (\"Ashrei ha'Gever ... u'mi'Torascha Selamdenu\") they are only classified as 'Yisurin shel Ahavah' if they do not cause Bitul Torah.   What does the other one say, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei (\"Baruch ha'Gever asher Lo Heisir Tefilasi ... \")?\n(b) What does Rebbi Aba quoting ... Rebbi Yochanan say about this, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Eis asher Ye'ehav Yochi'ach\" both of the above are considered Yisurin shel Ahavah.\n(c) And he reads that Pasuk in Tehilim (not as \"u'mi'Torascha Selam'denu, but) as \"u'mi'Torascha Silm'denu\".   What does this now mean?\n(d) In fact, he learns it from 'Shein ve'Ayin'.   What exactly does he learn from there?\n(e) And this in turn, is similar to a D'rashah of Resh Lakish.  What did Resh Lakish learn from the Gezeirah Shavah \"B'ris\" \"B'ris\" from salt?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rebbi Shimon ben Yochai describe Torah and Eretz Yisrael?\n(b) What is the third gift that he incorporates in his statement?\n(c) What else do they all have in common?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) From which Pasuk in Tehilim does Rebbi Shimon in a Beraisa learn that Torah is given with Yisurin?\n(b) He learns Eretz Yisrael from the Pasuk in Eikev \"Ki ka'asher Yeyaser Ish es B'no Hash-m Elokecha Meyas'reka\".   How dowe know that this Pasuk is referring to Eretz Yisrael?\n(c) And what does he learn from the latter half of the Pasuk in Mishlei \"ki Ner Mitzvah ve'Torah Or, ve'Derech Chayim Toch'chos Musar\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) A Beraisa expert cited a Beraisa in front of Rebbi Yochanan which states that anyone who studies Torah and indulges in Gemilus Chasadim will earn a person pardon for all his sins.   Which third item did he add to his list?\n(b) How did Rebbi Yochanan (based on Pesukim in Mishlei) support the first two items from the Pasuk there \"be'Chesed ve'Emes Yechupar Avon\"?\n(c) What problem did he have with 'burying one's children'?\n(d) An old man quoting Rebbi Shimon ben Yochai answered him with a Pasuk in Yirmiyah.   Which Pasuk?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) One of the two things that Rebbi Yochanan listed that cannot be classified as Yisurin shel Ahavah is Nega'im (Tzara'as).  What is the other?\n(b) How do we initially reconcile the first of the two with the Beraisa, which describes any of the four types of Nega'im as a Mizbe'ach Kaparah?\n(c) In the second answer, we say 'Ha Lan, ha L'hu'? Who is 'Lan' and who is 'L'hu'?\n(d) Why are Nega'im ...\n1. ... not considered Yisurin shel Ahavah in Eretz Yisrael?\n2. ... considered Yisurin shel Ahavah in Bavel?\n(e) What do we mean when, in the third answer, we differentiate between in private and in public?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What was Rebbi Yochanan referring to when he used to declare 'Dein G'rama de'Asira'ah Bir'?\n(b) What problem does this create with his earlier statement that 'sons' is not considered Yisurin shel Ahavah?\n(c) How do we answer the Kashya?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) Both Rebbi Chiya bar Aba and Rebbi Yochanan gave the same reply when they were asked by Rebbi Yochanan and Rebbi Chanina respectively whether Yisurin were dear to them.   What did they both say?\n(b) How did both Rebbi Yochanan and Rebbi Chanina respond?\n(c) Seeing as Rebbi Yochanan was capable of healing a person from his ailments, why did he need Rebbi Chanina to cure him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) How did Rebbi Yochanan create light when he went to pay Rebbi Eliezer a Bikur Cholim visit,?\n(b) Besides a lack of Torah-knowledge or Parnasah, to which third possible problem did Rebbi Yochanan attribute Rebbi Elazar's tears?\n(c) Why did he not consider it worthwhile to cry over a lack of ...\n1. ... Torah-knowledge?\n2. ... Parnasah?\n3. ... children?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) So why did Rebbi Elazar cry?\n(b) How did Rebbi Yochanan react to that?\n(c) How does the story end?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) Why did Rav Yehudah the brother of Rav Sala Chasida (or Rav Ada bar Ahavah) and the Rabanan pay Rav Huna a visit?\n(b) What did they advise him to do?\n(c) What did they reply when Rav Huna asked them on what grounds they suspected him of having sinned?\n(d) Not knowing what he had done wrong, how did Rav Huna respond to that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What had they heard about his treatment of his Aris (resident gardener) that was incorrect?\n(b) How did Rav Huna justify his actions?\n(c) They answered him 'Basar Ganva G'nov, ve'Ta'ama di'Ta'im!' What does this mean?\n(d) How did Rav Huna respond to that?\n(e) Some say that the vinegar turned back into wine.   What do others say happened?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) When Aba Binyamin said that all his life, he was careful to Daven 'in front of his bed (Lifnei Mitaso)', why could he not have meant this literally?\n(b) From whom do we learn this?\n(c) Then what did he mean?\n(d) How do we therefore amend the statement to read?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) He was also careful to place his bed facing north to south.   Why did he do that?\n(b) What did Rebbi Chama b'Rebbi Chanina (or Rebbi Yitzchak) say, based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"u\"Tzefuncha Temalei Bitnam, Yisbe'u Banim\") about someone who adheres to this ruling?\n(c) What did Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak add to this (based on the 'Gezeirah-Shavah' \"Temalie\" \"Vayimle'u\" (in the Pasuk in Toldos \"Vayimle'u Yameihah Laledes\" [in connection with Rivkah])?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) What does Aba Binyamim in a Beraisa say about someone who walks home after Davening Ma'ariv, leaving his friend alone in the field in the dark (See Tosfos 6a DH 'ha'Mispalel')?\n(b) He learns this from the Pasuk in Iyov \"Toref Nafsheo be'Apo, ha'Lema'ancha Te'azev Aretz\".   What does the second half of the Pasuk imply in the current context?\n(c) And what does does the Tana learn further from the conclusion of the Pasuk \"Vaye'tak Tzur mi'Mekomo\" (bearing in mind that \"Tzur\" refers to Hakadosh-Baruch-Hu\")?\n(d) In what connection did Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina then quote the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"His peace will stretch like a river, his righteousness will be considered like the waves of the sea and he will have numerous children and offspring\"?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 6,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What was Aba Binyamin, in another Beraisa, referring to when he states that if the eye was able to see them, a person would go out of his mind?\n(b) And what did Abaye mean when he said ...\n1. ... 'Inhu Nefishi Minan!'?\n2. ... that they surround us 'ki Kisla le'Ugya'? What is 'Kisla le'Ugya'?\n(c) According to Rav Huna, there are a thousand on every person's right-hand side.   How many are there on his left?\n(d) Which Pasuk in Tehilim does he cite in support of this?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rava say about ...\n1. ... the terrible squash that one often finds at the D'rashah on Shabbos?\n2. ... 'the tired knees' and the clothes of the Talmidei-Chachamim that wear out prematurely?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What will a person who places sifted ashes round his bed at night-time find in the morning?\n(b) Rava prescribes taking the placenta of a black firstborn bitch.   What is the genealogy of that cat?\n(c) What does he then do with it after burning it in fire and grinding the ashes?\n(d) What will he achieve by doing this?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) Rava then advises that one takes the demon and places it inside a sealed metal pipe? Why is that?\n(b) It seems that they are even dangerous to look at. What happened to Rav Bibi bar Abaye when he followed Rava's instruction?\n(c) How did he recover?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What does Aba Binyamin in a Beraisa learn from the Pasuk in Melachim \"li'Shemo'a el ha'Rinah ve'El ha'Tefilah\"?\n(b) Ravin bar Rav Ada Amar Rebbi Yitzchak learns from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Elokim Nitzav ba'Adas Keil\", that Hash-m is to be found in Shul. What else does he learn from this Pasuk (in connection with ten people who Daven together [even not in Shul])?\n(c) What does he learn from ...\n1. ... the same Pasuk in Tehilim \"be'Kerev Elokim Yishpot\"?\n2. ... the Pasuk in Mal'achi \"Az Nidb'ru Yir'ei Hash-m Ish el Re'eihu Vayakshev Hash-m Vayishma\"?\n3. ... the continuation of the latter Pasuk \"u'le'Choshvei Sh'mo\"?\n4. ... the Pasuk in Yisro \"be'Chol Makom asher Azkir es Sh'mi Avo Eilecha u'Verachticha\"?\n(d) Now that the Shechinah is present even where even ...\n1. ... one person is studying Torah, why do we need a Pasuk where there are two?\n2. ... two people are studying Torah, why do we need a Pasuk where there are three people judging?\n3. ... three people are judging, why do we need a Pasuk where there are ten people who are studying Torah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) In the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"Nishba Hash-m bi'Yemino u'vi'Zero'a Uzo\", Rebbi Avin (alias Ravin) bar Rav Ada Amar Rebbi Yitzchak interprets \"Yemino\" as Torah and \"Oz\" as Tefilin\".   From which Pasuk in ve'Zos ha'Berachah does he learn the former?\n(b) He learns the latter from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Hash-m Oz le'Amo Yitein\".   From which Pasuk in Ki Savo do we know, based on a comment of Rebbi Eliezer ha'Gadol, that Tefilin are a source of strength for Yisrael?\n(c) What did Rebbi Eliezer say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What is the significance of the Pasuk in Divrei ha'Yamim that Rebbi Chiya bar Aba quoted to Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak \"u'Mi ke'Amcha Yisrael Goy Echad ba'Aretz\"?\n(b) Why did he then quote him the Pasuk in ...\n1. ... Ki Savo \"es Hash-m He'emarta ha'Yom ... va'Hashem He'emircha Hayom\"?\n2. ... Va'eschanan \"Sh'ma Yisrael ... \"?\n3. ... in Divrei ha'Yamim \"u'Mi ke'Amcha Yisrael Goy Echad ba'Aretz\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Why did Rav Ashi quote to Rav Acha b'rei de'Rava the Pesukim \"ki Mi Goy Gadol\" \"u'Mi Goy Gadol\" (both in Va'eschanan), \"Ashrecha Yisrael\" (ve'Zos ha'Berachah), \"O ha'Nisah Elokim ... \" (Va'eschanan) and \"u'Lesitcha Elyon\" (Ki Savo)?\n(b) What problem did Rav Acha b'rei de'Rava have with that?\n(c) What did Rav Ashi reply?\n(d) What is written in Hash-m's Tefilin shel Yad?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) What does Ravin bar Rav Ada about someone who generally Davens in Shul and misses one day?\n(b) Based on a Pasuk in Yeshayah, on what condition will Hash-m ...\n1. ... vindicate him for being absent?\n2. ... be angry with him?\n(c) Assuming he missed Shul for Parnasah reasons, why is Hash-m angry with him?\n(d) What does Rebbi Yochanan learn from the Pasuk (Ibid.) \"Madu'a Ba'si ve'Ein Ish, Karasi ve'Ein Oneh?\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav Huna say about a person who has a fixed place for Davening ...\n1. ... during his lifetime?\n2. ... after his death?\n(b) Why do they refer to him as 'a disciple of Avraham Avinu'?\n(c) How do we learn this from the Pasuk in Vayeira (following the destruction of S'dom) \"Vayashkem Avraham ba'Boker el ha'Makom asher Amad Sham es P'nei Hash-m\"), bearing in mind that the Pasuk does not mention Tefilah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) Why does Rabbi Chelbo Amar Rav Huna forbid a person to take large steps when leaving Shul?\n(b) What does Abaye learn from the Pasuk in Ve'neid'ah Nird'fah Lada'as es Hash-m\"?\n(c) What did Rebbi Zeira initially say about people he saw running to Shul?\n(d) He retracted however after he heard what Rebbi Tanchum Amar Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi said, based on the Pasuk in Hoshe'a \"Acharei Hash-m Yeilchu ke'Aryeh Yish'ag\".   What did Rebbi Tanchum learn from that Pasuk?\n(e) What did he subsequently begin doing?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Zeira gives the major reward for attending the Shabbos D'rashah as the running.   Why is that?\n(b) And by the same token, what does Abaye give as the major reward for attending the D'rashah on the Shabbos prior to Yom-Tov?\n(c) In similar fashion, various Amora'im give the major reward for a variety of Mitzvos as issues connected directly or indirectly with the actual Mitzvah, because without them, the Mitzvah itself is lacking.   What is the major reward that is due for ...\n1. ... learning a Sugya (Rava)?\n2. ... visiting a Beis Aveil (Rav Papa)?\n3. ... fasting on a Ta'anis (Mar Zutra)?\n4. ... eulogizing a deceased person (Rav Sheishes)?\n5. ... attending a wedding (Rav Ashi)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Saviv Resha'im Yis'haleichun\", what does Rav Huna say about someone who Davens behind the Shul (See Tosfos Amud 1, DH 'Achorei Beis ha'Keneses')?\n(b) What does he mean by 'behind the Shul'?\n(c) Why does he refer to it as 'behind the Shul'?\n(d) On what condition does Abaye permit it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) The Gemara records an incident where Eliyahu found a man Davening behind the Shul facing in a different direction.   How did he appear to him?\n(b) What did Eliyahu comment?\n(c) What did he promptly do?\n(d) Still in connection with the above Sugya, how did Rav Bibi bar Abaye explain to one of the Rabbanan (or Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak to Rav Bibi) the Pasuk in Tehilim \"K'rum Zullus li'Venei Adam\" (in the context of Tefilah)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) How do Rebbi Yochanan and Resh Lakish explain the same Pasuk in Tehilim, in connection with someone who needs the financial support of others?\n(b) This is based on Rav Dimi's translation of a 'K'rum'.   How does he translate it?\n(c) How does this enable us to interpret the Pasuk more accurately?\n(d) How do Rebbi Ami and Rebbi Asi explain the same scenario, only based on the Pasuk there \"Hirkavta Enosh le'Rosheinu, Banu ba'Eish u'va'Mayim\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) Which incident did Rebbi Chelbo Amar Rav Huna cite to stress the importance of Tefilas Minchah?\n(b) Why did Eliyahu see fit to mention the word \"Aneini\" twice in his request to Hash-m to send rain?\n(c) What did ...\n1. ... Rebbi Yochanan comment on that, based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Tikon Tefilasi Ketores Lefanecha, Mas'as Kapai Minchas Arev \"?\n2. ... Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak comment, based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Hash-m Boker Tishma Koli, Boker E'eroch L'cha Va'atzapeh\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Chelbo Amar Rav Huna say about someone who attends the Se'udah of a Chasan and fails to make him happy?\n(b) How does he learn it from the Pasuk in Yirmiyah \"Kol Sason ve'Kol Simchah ... \"?\n(c) What does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi say about a person who does make the Chasan happy?\n(d) How is this based on the Pasuk in Yisro \"Vay'hi ba'Yom ha'Shelishi bi'Heyos ha'Boker Vay'hi Kolos u'Verakim ... \"?\n(e) How do we solve the problem caused by the Pasuk \"ve'Chol Ro'im es ha'Kolos\", which seems to add two extra 'Kolos', making it seven?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) If Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi maintains that the person who makes the Chasan happy earns Torah, what will he receive according to ...\n1. ...  Rebbi Avahu, based on the Pasuk in Yirmiyah \"Mevi'im Todah Beis Hash-m\"?\n2. ... Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak, based on the Pasuk there \"ki Ashuv es Sh'vus ha'Aretz ke'Varishonah, Amar Hash-m\""
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav Chelbo Amar Rav Huna learn from the Pasuk in Koheles \"Sof Davar, ha'Kol Nishma, es ha'Elokim Y'ra ... \"?\n(b) What does Rebbi Elazar learn from the conclusion of the Pasuk \"ki Zeh Kol ha'Adam\"? What does Hash-m say about him?\n(c) Rebbi Aba bar Kahana learns from it that he is equal to the entire world.   How does Rebbi Shimon ben Azai (or ben Zoma) say about it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Chelbo Amar Rav Huna say about Reuven who knows that Shimon always greets him?\n(b) Bearing in mind that such behavior leads to peaceful relationships, on which Pasuk in Tehilim is this based?\n(c) On the other hand, based on the Pasuk in Yeshayah \" ... G'zeilas he'Ani be'Vateichem!\" he describe Reuven, in the event that Reuven fails to respond to Shimon's greeting as a thief.   How do we know that the Pasuk is referring to not greeting him."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 7,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rebbi Yochanan Amar Rebbi Yossi ben Zimra learn from the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"va'Havi'osim el Har Kodshi, ve'Simachtim be'Veis Tefilasi\" that Hash-m also Davens?\n(b) According to Rav Zutra bar Tuvya Amar Rav, the text of His Tefilah is 'May it be My will that My mercy quashes My anger and that My mercy 'overrides My Midos (ha'Din)'.   How does the text conclude?\n(c) Rebbi Yishmael ben Elisha describes how he once entered the Kodesh Kodshim to burn the Ketores.   Who was Rebbi Yishmael ben Elisha?\n(d) When did this incident take place?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Whom did he see there sitting on a high elevated throne?\n(b) What did Akasriel Kah Hash-m Tzevakos say to Him?\n(c) What did he reply?\n(d) What was Akasriel Kah Hash-m Tzevakos' reaction?\n(e) Which principle do we learn from this episode?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Who said to whom the Pasuk in Ki Sissa \"Panai Yeileichu va'Hanichosi lach\"?\n(b) What does it mean?\n(c) What does Rebbi Yochanan quoting Rebbi Yossi learn from there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) What do we learn from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"ve'Keil Zo'em be'Chol Yom\"?\n(b) What is the significance ...\n1. ... based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Ki Rega be'Apo ... \", of the number 'eight thousand, eight hundred and eighty-eight?\n2. ... of the Pasuk in Balak \"Yode'a Da'as Elyon!\"?\n(c) Why can the latter Pasuk not be understood literally?\n(d) What was the Navi Michah referring to when, with regard to the current context, he exhorted K'lal Yisrael to remember the kindness of Hash-m?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) We already discussed the Pasuk in Tehilim Ki Rega be'Apo ... \".  What did Ravin (or Rebbi Avina) comment with regard to the Shi'ur of Hash-m's anger as 'Rega'?\n(b) What do others learn from the Pasuk in Yehsayah \"Chavi Kim'at Rega ad Ya'avor Za'am\"?\n(c) What problem do we have with Abaye, who confines that moment to a point during the first three hours of the day when chickens stand on one foot and their combs turn white?\n(d) How do we solve the problem?\n(e) What reason does Rebbi Meir cite as the source of Hash-m's anger?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi try to do to counter a certain Tzedoki who consistently tried to catch him out by quoting Pesukim?\n(b) What cause his plan to fall through?\n(c) What did he learn from that episode, based on the Pasuk in 'Ashrei' \"ve'Rachamav al Kol Ma'asav\"?\n(d) Which other Pasuk from Mishlei did he quote to back up his conclusion?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yochanan, again quoting Rebbi Yossi ben Zimra, citing a Pasuk in Hoshe'a, states that one Mardus in a person's heart is better than many Malkiyos (lashes).   What is a 'Mardus'?\n(b) How does the Pasuk in Hoshe'a which informs us how Yisrael decided to leave their many 'lovers' and return to their first love (Hash-m) end?\n(c) What does Resh Lakish say about that, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Tachas Ge'arah be'Meivin me'Hakos K'sil Me'ah\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Yochanan, once again quoting Rebbi Yossi ben Zimra, what common response did Hash-m give with regard to the three things that Moshe requested from Him?\n(b) What did He answer when, following the sin of the Golden Calf, Moshe asked that Hash-m Himself continues to accompany Yisrael (and not an angel)?\n(c) Moshe's second and third requests were \"Veniflinu Ani ve'Amcha!\" and \"Hodi'eni Na es Derachecha!\"    What was he actually asking for when he said ...\n1. ... \"Veniflinu Ani ve'Amcha!\"?\n2. ... \"Hodi'eni Na es Derachecha!\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Initially, Rebbi Yochanan explains 'Tzadik ve'Tov lo' as Tzadik ben Tzadik and 'Tzadik ve'Ra lo' as Tzadik ben Rasha.  How does he explain Rasha ve'Tov lo' and 'Rasha ve'Ra lo'?      Rasha ve'Tov lo - Rasha ben Tzadik; Rasha ve'Ra lo - Rasha ben Rasha'.\n(b) We query this however, from a seeming contradiction between the Pasuk in Ki Sissa \"Pokeid Avon Avos al Banim\" and the Pasuk in Ki Seitzei \"u'Banim Lo Yumsu al Avosam\".   How do we reconcile the two Pesukim?\n(c) How does this disprove Rebbi Yochanan's initial statement?\n(d) He finally explains 'Tzadik ve'Tov lo' as a complete Tzadik, and 'Tzadik ve'Ra lo' as an incomplete Tzadik.   How does he then explain 'Rasha ...\n1. ... ve'Tov lo'?\n2. ... ve'Ra lo'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yochanan's explanation, however, does not tally with that of Rebbi Meir, who says that one of Moshe's requests was not granted.   Which of the three requests was that?\n(b) How does he learn it from the Pasuk in Ki Sissa \"Vechanosi es asher Achon Verichamti es asher Arachem\"?\n(c) According to Rebbi Yehoshua ben Korchah, who concurs with Rebbi Meir, what did Hash-m say to Moshe, even as He refused him his request?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Shmuel bar Nachmeni, what reward did Moshe receive for ...\n1. ... hiding his face (at the burning bush)?\n2. ... for being afraid to look at the Shechinah?\n3. ... for not looking?\n(b) According to Rav Chana bar Bizna Amar Rebbi Shimon Chasida, what did Moshe actually see, when Hash-m removed His Hand from the cleft of the rock behind which Moshe was concealed (when Hash-m announced the thirteen Midos of Rachamim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) Once again, Rebbi Yochanan quotes Rebbi Yossi ben Zimra.   What does he say about every good thing that he said He will do?\n(b) He learns this from Hash-m's promise to Moshe.   What did He say He would do to Yisrael/Moshe after the sin of the Eigel ha'Zahav?\n(c) On what grounds did He relent from what He said He would do to K'lal Yisrael?\n(d) What does the Pasuk in Divrei ha'Yamim say about Moshe's descendents?\n(e) What does the Beraisa cited by Rav Yosef learn from a Gezeirah-Shavah 'Reviyah' 'Reviyah' from the Pasuk in Sh'mos \"u'Venei Yisrael Paru ... Vayirbu ... \"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yochanan quoting Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai comment on the Pasuk in Lech-l'cha \" Adon-ai Elokim, ba'Mah Eida Ki Irashenah\"?\n(b) How does Rav connect this Pasuk with the Tefilah of Daniel more than a thousand years later (who concluded his prayer on behalf of the desolate Beis-ha'Mikdash with the words \"Lema'an Adon-ai\"?\n(c) What does Rebbi Yochanan quoting Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai learn from the Pasuk in Ki Sissa \"Panai (My anger) Yeileichu va'Ha'nichosi lach\"?\n(d) On what occasion did Le'ah declare \"ha'Pa'am Odeh es Hash-m!\"? Why did she do that?\n(e) What does Rebbi Yochanan quoting Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai comment on that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Elazar explains why Leah named her firstborn son 'Reuven'. She began by drawing a distinction between her son and the son of her father-in-law.   What was the name of her father-in-law's son?\n(b) What did she have in mind when she called him 'Reuven'?\n(c) How did she prove that Reuven was not hostile towards Yosef?\n(d) How does Rebbi Yochanan explain the name 'Rus'?\n(e) How does Rebbi Elazar prove from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"L'chu Chazu Mif'alos Hash-m asher Sam Shamos ba'Aretz\" that the name of a person has an affect on his character?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yoshanan in the name of Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai say about a rebel in one's own household?\n(b) How does he learn it from the two Pesukim in Tehilim \"Mizmor le'David be'Vorcho Mipnei Avshalom B'no\" and \"Lamah Ragshu Goyim u'Le'umim Yehegu Rik\"(in connection with the battle against Gog and Magog)? What does the former Pasuk add that the latter does not?\n(c) What is strange about the first of the two Pesukim that we just discussed?\n(d) What Mashal does Rebbi Shimon ben Avishalom give to explain it?\n(e) Why in fact was David ha'Melech relieved after the decree came to fruition?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yochanan quoting Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai learn from the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Ozvei Torah Yehalalu Rasha, ve'Shomrei Torah Yisgaru bam\"?\n(b) What does Rebbi Dustai bar Masun in a Beraisa say about that?\n(c) How do we reconcile this with the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Al Tischar ba'Merei'im, ve'Al Tekan'eh be'Osei Avlah\"? What does the latter Pasuk really mean?\n(d) Of whom should one be jealous?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) We query Rebbi Yochanan however, from a statement of Rebbi Yitzchak.   Based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Yachilu D'rachav be'Chol Eis\", what did Rebbi Yitzchak say about a Rasha who is experiencing a period of good fortune?\n(b) And what does he learn from the continuation of the Pasuk ...\n1. ... \"Marom Mishpatecha Negdo\"?\n2. ... Kol Tzorarav Yafi'ach bahem\"?\n(c) What do we mean when we answer that one speaks with regard to personal issues, the other regarding spiritual matters?\n(d) In the second answer, both are speaking with regard to spiritual issues. How do we then reconcile the two opinions (implied in the actual statement of Rebbi Yitzchak)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) In the third answer, Rebbi Yochanan too, is speaking about a successful Rasha.   How do we then reconcile the two opinions by differentiating between two kinds of Tzadik?\n(b) And we prove this from a Kashya asked by Rav Huna.   What problem did Rav Huna have with the Pasuk in Chavakuk \"Lamah Sabit Bogdim Tachrish be'Vala Rasha Tzadik mimenu\" (based on Pesukim in Tehilim and Mishlei)?\n(c) How did he explain the Pasuk \"Tzadik mimenu\", to answer the Kashya?\n(d) The final answer seems to merely repeat the second one.   How does it differ from it (See Hagahos Maharshal)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yochanan again quoting Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai, based on a Pasuk in Shmuel, say about someone who fixes a place for Davening (or for Torah-study, according to some texts)?\n(b) How does Rav Huna explain the discrepancy between the Pasuk there which says \"ve'Lo Yosifu Benei Avlah le'Anoso\" and a similar Pasuk in Melachim, which replaces \"le'Anoso\" with \"le'Chaloso\"?\n(c) And what does Rebbi Yochanan quoting Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai, learn from the words \"Yatzak Mayim\" (as opposed to  'Lamad'), in the Pasuk in Melachim \"Poh Elisha ben Shafat asher Yatzak Mayim al-Y'dei Eliyahu\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Nachman reply when Rebbi Yitzchak asked him why he did not turn up in Shul that day for Davening?\n(b) What did he then suggest that he (Rav Nachman) ought to have done?\n(c) What did he think he should have done when Rav Nachman found even that too difficult?\n(d) When Rav Nachman asked him why he was so insistent, he cited Rebbi Yochanan.   What did Rebbi Yochanan in the name of Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai say based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"va'Ani Tefilasi L'cha Hash-m Eis Ratzon ... \"?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 8,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina learn from the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"Koh Amar Hash-m be'Eis Ratzon Anisicha\", and Rebbi Acha b'Rebbi Chanina from the Pasuk in Iyov \"Hein Keil Kabir ve'Lo Yim'as\" and from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Padah ve'Shalom Nafshi Mikrav li, ki be'Rabim Hayu Imadi\"?\n(b) What does Rebbi Nasan in a Beraisa learn from ...\n1. ... the same two Pesukim?\n2. ... the words \"Padah ve'Shalom Nafshi\" regarding any person who learns Torah, indulges in Gemilus Chasadim and Davens with the Tzibur?\n(c) In connection with a Pasuk in Yirmyah, who does Resh Lakish label as 'a bad neighbor'?\n(d) And what else does he say about him, based on the same Pasuk \"Hin'ni Not'sham me'al Admasam ... !\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Which Pasuk in Eikev did Rebbi Yochanan quote in surprise, when they informed him that there were old men in Bavel?\n(b) When did his surprise dissipate?\n(c) This is based on a statement of Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi.   What did Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi tell his sons would happen if they Davened each morning and evening in Shul?\n(d) Rav Acha b'Rebbi Chanina supports this statement with the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Ashrei Adam Shome'a Li Lish'kod al Dalsosai Yom Yom Lishmor Mezuzos Pesachai ... \".   How does the Pasuk continue?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What problem do we have with Rav Chisda's ruling 'Le'olam Yikanes Adam Sh'nei Pesachim be'Veis ha'Kenesses'?\n(b) What must Rav Chisda therefore have meant?\n(c) What is the reason for his ruling?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rebbi Chanina, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Matza Ishah, Matza Tov\" explain the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Al Zos, Yispalel Kol Chasid Eilecha le'Eis Metzo\".\n(b) In the same vein, what would the B'nei Eretz Yisrael say to a Chasan on the day of his wedding?\n(c) If \"Matza\" refers to the above Pasuk in Mishlei, which Pasuk in Koheles does \"Motzei\" refer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"ki Motza'i Matza Chayim\", Rebbi Nasan interprets \"le'Eis M'tzo\" with reference to Torah.   How does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak interpret it, based on the Pasuk there \"la'Maves Totza'os\"?\n(b) How does the Beraisa corroborate this explanation, based on the Gematriyah of \"Totza'os?\n(c) If the most painful of these is Askara, what is the most painless?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What is 'Askara'?\n(b) Some compare the pain of Askara to a piece of wool that is caught in brambles and that rips off as one tries to separate it.   To what do others compare it?\n(c) To what does the Tana compare Neshikah?\n(d) How does Rebbi Yochanan interpret \"le'Eis M'tzo\", based on the Pasuk in Iyov cited by Rebbi Chanina \"ha'Semeichim Eilai, Gil Yasisu, ki Yimtze'u Kaver\"?\n(e) Based on Rebbi Yochanan's interpretation,Rabah bar Rav Shilo states that one should keep Davening for that 'ad Zibula Basraisa'.   What does this mean?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) The last interpretation of \"le'Eis Mtzo\" is that of Mar Zutra.   What does he say?\n(b) What did they say about Mar Zutra's interpretation in Eretz Yisrael?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) When Rava asked Rafram bar Papa to tell him a Chidushin the name of Rav Chisda concerning Shuls, he quoted him the Pasuk \"Oheiv Hash-m Sha'arei Tzion mi'Kol Mishk'nos Ya'akov\".   What did Rav Chisda learn from there?\n(b) What statement did Rebbi Chiya bar Ami citing Ula make based on Rav Chisda's Chidush concerning the era following the destruction of the Beis ha'Mikdash?\n(c) What did Abaye, who used to learn at home and Daven in Shul,  begin to do when he heard it?\n(d) Rebbi Ami and Asi too, would make a point of Davening 'between the pillars' where they learned.   In which town did they reside?\n(e) How many Shuls were there in Teverya?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) The Pasuk in Tehilim writes \"Ashrei Ish Yerei es Hash-m\".    How does a similar Pasuk there \"Yegi'a Kapecha ki Socheil\" end?\n(b) What does \"Ashrecha ve'Tov lach\" imply?\n(c) What does Rebbi Chiya bar Ami quoting Ula learn from the contrast between the two Pesukim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What was the relationship between Shimi ben Geira and Sh'lomoh ha'Melech?\n(b) What did the latter refrain from doing as long as the latter was alive?\n(c) What does Rebbi Chiya bar Ami quoting Ula learn from there?\n(d) How do we reconcile this with the Beraisa, which rules that one should not live in the vicinity as one's Rebbe?\n(e) What is the reason for the latter ruling?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav Huna bar Yehudah ... Amar Rebbi Ami learn from the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"ve'Ozvei Hash-m Yeichalu\"?\n(b) What did Rebbi Avahu nevertheless used to do?\n(c) Rav Papa asked whether one is permitted to leave between one Pasuk and the next.   What answer did he receive?\n(d) Rav Sheishes used to face the opposite direction.   What did he declare as he did so?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Huna ... Amar Rebbi Ami discusses being 'Mashlim Parshiyosav Im ha'Tzibur'.   What does he mean by that?\n(b) How does one fulfill the Mitzvah?\n(c) And what does one do with regard to Pesukim such as \"Ataros ve'Divon ... \"? Why does he mention specifically this Pasuk?\n(d) What reward does one receive for fulfilling this Mitzvah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) On what day did Rav Bibi bar Abaye initially intend to learn all the Parshiyos?\n(b) What did Chiya bar Rav from Difti, citing a Beraisa, point out to him based on the Pasuk in Emor \"Ve'inisem es Nafshoseichem be'Tish'ah la'Chodesh ba'Erev\"?\n(c) Why can the Pasuk not be understood literally?\n(d) Which Beraisa did that old man quote him when he then planned to finish all the Parshiyos on one or two Shabbasos at the beginning of the year?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) The old man also told Rav Bibi to be careful with the Varidin like Rebbi Yehudah. What are the 'Varidin'?\n(b) What exactly, did he mean?\n(c) And he also instructed him to treat an old man who has forgotten his learning with respect.   To which type of forgetting does this apply?\n(d) How did he learn this from the Luchos?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) Rava instructed his sons not to cut meat on the back of their hands, according to some, because of the obvious danger involved.  What do others say?\n(b) He also instructed them not to sit on the bed of a Nochris or to pass behind a Shul whilst the Tzibur were Davening.   There are two figurative explanations to this ruling. One is not to go to sleep without reciting the Sh'ma (like a Nochris does).   What is the other?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) The literal meaning of this unusual command is based on an episode that occurred with Rav Papa.   Why did he visit a Nochris?\n(b) What did he reply when she offered him a seat on a bed?\n(c) What did he discover when she complied?\n(d) What was she hoping to achieve with this intended blood libel?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) Rava's instruction not to go past the door of a Shul whilst Tefilah is in progress corroborates a statement of Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi.   What did he say in this regard?\n(b) Abaye adds five qualifications to the current ruling.   What does he say in a case where there is either another entrance to the Shul or there is another Shul in town.   Why is that?\n(c) He also permits it if one is carrying a load or running.   On what final condition does he absolve someone passing a Shul from going inside?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Akiva, in a Beraisa, admired the Medians because they were careful to cut meat on the table rather than whilst holding it in their hands, and because they would kiss each other on the back of the hand, rather than on the mouth.   What is wrong with kissing on the mouth?\n(b) He also admired them because they would consult (secret matters) with one another in the field.   Which Pasuk in Vayeitzei does Rav Ada bar Ahavah quote as the source for this concept?\n(c) In another Beraisa, Raban Shimon ben Gamliel explained how he loved the Persians because they were discreet in three areas. Two of them concerned the modest way in which they ate and in which they behaved in the bathroom.   What was the third?\n(d) How did Rav Yosef quoting a Beraisa explain the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"I commanded My 'holy ones'? If \"My 'holy ones' refers to the Persians, what does the term 'holy ones' really mean?\n(e) What did he command them?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) Like which Tana (regarding the latest time to recite Keri'as Sh'ma shel Arvis, does Rav Yehudah Amar Rav rule?\n(b) Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai in a Beraisa states that it is possible to read the Sh'ma twice at night-time, once before Amud ha'Shachar, and once, after it.   What exactly does he mean?\n(c) What problem do we have with the fact that he refers to after Amud ha'Shachar as 'night-time'?\n(d) We answer that it is in fact night-time (See Tosfos).   In which regard is it then considered day concerning Keri'as Sh'ma shel Yom?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai quoting Rebbi Akiva, mean in the second Lashon, when he says that one can recite the Shema twice by day, once before sunrise, and once, after sunrise?\n(b) What problem do we have, based on the fact that the Tana refers to before Hanetz ha'Chamah as 'daytime'?\n(c) We answer that it is in fact day-time (See Tosfos).   In which regard is it then considered night concerning Keri'as Sh'ma shel Arvis?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Acha b'Rebbi Chanina Amar Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi say about Rebbi Shimon in the name of Rebbi Akiva?\n(b) How does Rebbi Zeira qualify Rebbi Acha b'Rebbi Chanina's ruling?\n(c) According to which Lashon does he say that?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 9,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) When Rav Yitzchak bar Yosef came from Eretz Yisrael, what did he comment on Rebbi Acha b'Rebbi Chanina Amar Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi ruling like Rebbi Shimon in the name of Rebbi Akiva ... ?\n(b) Which incident did he cite (in connection with two Talmidim at a Se'udah) which served as the basis of his statement?\n(c) What did Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi rule on that occasion?\n(d) When did he allow them to recite the K'ri'as Sh'ma shel Arvis?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What problem do we have with our Mishnah, regarding the incident of Raban Gamliel's sons, who asked him about reciting the Sh'ma after midnight?\n(b) So what did they really ask him?\n(c) And what did he reply?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What additional problem do we have with the continuation of the Mishnah 've'Lo Zu Bil'vad, Ela Kol Makom ad Chatzos Mitzvasan ad she'Ya'aleh Amud ha'Shachar ... '?\n(b) How do we therefore amend Raban Gamliel's statement to his sons to justify it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) What further problem do we have with our Mishnah ('Hekter Chalavim ... ') based on the Beraisa, which lists K'ri'as Sh'ma Arvis, Hallel and Achilas Pesachim as Mitzvos that can be fulfilled until morning?\n(b) To answer the Kashya, like whom do we establish our Mishnah?\n(c) Who is then the author of the Beraisa?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah learn in another Beraisa, from the Gezeirah-Shavah \"Ve'achlu es ha'Basar ba'Laylah ha'Zeh\" from \"Ve'avarti be'Eretz Mitzrayim ba'Laylah ha'Zeh\" (both in Parshas Bo)?\n(b) How does Rebbi Akiva counter that from the word \"be'Chipazon\" (in the Pasuk there \"Va'achaltem oso be'Chipazon\")?\n(c) In the first of the two above Pesukim, how will Rebbi Akiva then explain the word ...\n1. ... \"ba'Laylah\"?\n2. ... \"ha'Zeh\"?\n(d) What would we otherwise have thought?\n(e) On what basis do we compare Pesach to Shelamim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) From which Pasuk (in Bo) does Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah learn that the Korban Pesach can only be eaten for one night?\n(b) How does Rebbi Akiva explain \"ad Boker\"?\n(c) How does Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah counter that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa cites a Machlokes Tana'im regarding the Pasuk in Re'ei \"Sham Tizbach es ha'Pesach ba'Erev, ke'Vo ha'Shemesh, Mo'ed Tzeis'cha mi'Mitzrayim\".   How do the Tana'im interpret the phrase ...\n1. ... \"Sham Tizbach es ha'Pesach ba'Erev\"?\n2. ... \"ke'Vo ha'Shemesh\"?\n3. ... \"Mo'ed Tzeis'cha mi'Mitzrayim\"?\n(b) What time-period does \"ba'Erev\" cover?\n(c) When is the Pesach actually burned?\n(d) Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Until when is one permitted to eat the Pesach according to Rebbi Eliezer?\n(b) What is his source for this?\n(c) Based on the Pasuk under discussion, what does Rebbi Akiva hold?\n(d) Why do we quote this Beraisa here?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Commenting on the Pasuk in Bo \"Daber Na be'Oznei ha'Am\", what  did Amri de'bei Rebbi Yanai say about the word \"Na\"?\n(b) What was the special request referring to?\n(c) Why did Hash-m consider this so important? What was he afraid that 'that Tzadik' might say?\n(d) Who was 'that Tzadik'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Why was it necessary to mention Hash-m's promise to Avraham? On what grounds would B'nei Yisrael have objected?\n(b) We support this with a Mashal.   What happened in the Mashal after the prisoner was promised his freedom on the following day together with a lot of money?\n(c) What did Rebbi Ami comment, based on the word (in Bo) \"Vayash'ilum\"?\n(d) What are the two ways of explaining his comment?\n(e) What reason do we now present to explain why Yisrael initially declined to ask the Egyptian for their vessels?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) Commenting on the Pasuk \"Vayenatzlu es Mitzrayim\", Rebbi Ami explains that they made it like a store-house devoid of corn.   What does Resh Lakish say?\n(b) How do we initially explain the Name of Hash-m \"Ehekeh asher Ehekeh\" that Hash-m revealed to Moshe at the burning bush?\n(c) On what grounds did Moshe object to that?\n(d) What was Hash-m's response?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rebbi Avahu explain the double Lashon of Eliyahu (in Melachim, by the confrontation with the prophets of Ba'al on Mount Carmel) \"Aneini Hash-m Aneini\"?\n(b) In the second issue, of what was Moshe afraid that Yisrael might say?\n(c) How does he then interpret the Pasuk \"Ve'atah Hasibosa es Libam Achoranis\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) According to the Tana Kama, one may recite Keri'as Shema shel Shachris from the moment that one can distinguish between white and the dark blue shade of the sky shortly before nightfall. What does Rebbi Eliezer say?\n(b) What is the final time of saying the Shema, according to the Tana Kama?\n(c) What is Rebbi Yehoshua's source for saying up till three hours in the day?\n(d) What does the Mishnah say about someone who reads the Sh'ma after the given time?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) Why can we not explain 'between dark-blue and white' with regard to two pieces of wool?\n(b) What then, does it mean?\n(c) Two of the other earliest times to recite the Sh'ma are when it is possible to distinguish 1. between a wolf and a dog (Rebbi Meir) and 2. Between a donkey and a wild ass (Rebbi Akiva).  Rav Huna however, rules like Acherim. What does Acherim say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) Abaye rules like Acherim regarding Tefilin.   How does he rule with regard to Keri'as Sh'ma?\n(b) When, according to Rebbi Yochanan, did the Vasikin conclude the Sh'ma?\n(c) What does the Beraisa that supports Rebbi Yochanan add to his statement?\n(d) How does Rebbi Zeira learn Rebbi Yochanan's Din from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Yira'ucha im Shemesh ve'Lifnei Yare'ach Dor Dorim\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Yossi ben Elyakim in the name of the Kehilah Kadisha of Yerushalayim testify about someone who is Somech Ge'ulah to Tefilah?\n(b) What objection did Rebbi Zeira raise to that statement?\n(c) Rebbi Yossi ben Elyakim replied that it was his own fault.   What exactly happened to him?\n(d) What had he done wrong that caused this punishment?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yossi ben Elyakim's reply is based on a statement of Rebbi Yochanan.   What did Rebbi Yochanan say one should do when going to see kings?\n(b) Why does this extend even to gentile kings?\n(c) Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) When Ula went to Eretz Yisrael, Rebbi Ila'a asked him to give his regards to B'runa together with all the group. What was the connection between Rebbi Ila'a and Rebbi B'runa?\n(b) What was special about the latter?\n(c) What happened to him once when he juxtaposed Ge'ulah to Tefilah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) We ask how it is possible to juxtapose Ge'ulah to Tefilah from a statement Rebbi Yochanan.   According to Rebbi Yochanan, what does one say immediately ...\n1. ... before the Amidah?\n2. ... after the Amidah?\n(b) What is now the problem?\n(c) On what grounds do we refute Rebbi Elazar's answer that Rebbi Yochanan's initial statement is confined to Ma'ariv? What did Rebbi Yochanan himself say about someone who juxtaposes Ge'ulah to Tefilah of Ma'ariv?\n(d) So we amend Rebbi Elazar's answer to Minchah (where Ge'ulah is not said).   How does Rav Ashi answer the Kashya even assuming that Rebbi Yochanan's statement pertains to all the Tefilos?\n(e) How does he prove it from Ma'ariv?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) How do we query taking for granted that 'Yih'yu le'Ratzon' is said after the Amidah? When else might it be appropriate to insert it?\n(b) How does Rebbi Yehudah the son of Rebbi Shimon ben Pazi answer the Kashya? Why indeed, do we insert it specifically after eighteen B'rachos?\n(c) What problem do we have with the answer?\n(d) We answer that \"Ashrei ha'Ish\" and \"Lamah Ragshu Goyim\" are really one Kapitel.   Why might we have thought otherwise?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) We prove the previous answer with another statement of Rebbi Yehudah the son of Rebbi Shimon ben Pazi himself.   What did he say about significance of the word \"Halelu-Kah\" in chapter hundred and three?\n(b) What does the Pasuk there say\n(c) What is the problem with that?\n(d) What does it therefore prove?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) We corroborate this with a statement of Rebbi Shmuel bar Nachmeni Amar Rebbi Yochanan.   What did he say about every Parshah that was dear to David?\n(b) What example did he give of this?\n(c) How do we now prove that \"Ashrei ha'Ish\" and \"Lamah Ragshu Goyim\" are one and the same Kapitel?"
      }
    ]
