      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What reason does Rav Yehudah Amar Shmuel give to explain why the Chachamim nixed the idea of reciting the Aseres ha'Dibros every day in Shul?\n(b) What did Rebbi Nasan in a Beraisa say about this?\n(c) What did Rav Chisda say to Rabah bar Chanah and Rav Ashi to Ameimar when they tried to introduce the recital of the Aseres ha'Dibros in Sura and Neherda'a respectively?\n(d) The Beraisa on the previous Amud referred to the B'rachah of the outgoing Mishmar.   What did the outgoing Mishmar say to the incoming one?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Why, if someone recites a B'rachah over a cup of wine, and thinking that it is beer, he begins the B'rachah intending to conclude 'Shehakol', but nevertheless concludes 'Borei P'ri ha'Gafen', is it obvious that he is Yotzei?\n(b) On which Mishnah in Perek Keitzad Mevorchin, is that based?\n(c) The She'eilah is where he is holding a cup of beer and thinking that it is wine, he begins the B'rachah intending to conclude 'Borei P'ri ha'Gafen', but nevertheless concludes 'Shekakol ... '.   Why might he ...\n1. ... not be Yotzei?\n2. ... nevertheless be Yotzei?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) We try to resolve the She'eilah from the Beraisa which discusses someone who makes a similar error in the B'rachos before the Sh'ma.   What does the Tana say about someone who begins the B'rachah of Yotzer Or (in the morning) with the intention of saying ...\n1. ... 'Yotzer Or' but ends up by saying 'Ma'ariv Aravim'?\n2. ... Ma'ariv Aravim but ends up by saying Yotzer Or?\n(b) And what does the Tana say if one begins the B'rachah of Ma'ariv Aravim (in the evening) with the intention of saying ...\n1. ... 'Ma'ariv Aravim', but ends up saying 'Yotzer Or'?\n2. ... 'Yotzer Or', but ends up saying 'Ma'ariv Aravim'?\n(c) How do we refute the proof from there that we contend with the beginning of the B'rachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) This answer is acceptable according to Rav, but problematic according to Rebbi Yochanan.   What does each one hold regarding the text of a B'rachah?\n(b) How do we reconcile it with Rebbi Yochanan?\n(c) This is based on a statement of Rabah bar Ula (that we cited earlier).   What did Rabah bar Ula say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) So we try to resolve the She'eilah from the Seifa of the Beraisa 'ha'Kol Holech achar ha'Chitum'.   What do we suggest that this comes to include?\n(b) We refute this however, by establishing the case with regard to bread and dates.   Why can this not refer to someone who ate bread, and thinking that he ate dates, he begins the Berachah intending to say 'al ha'Eitz' but actually says 'ha'Zan'?\n(c) To which case is it then referring?\n(d) Why is that not similar to our She'eilah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rabah bar Chin'na (or Chanina) the elder in the name of Rav say about anyone who does not say 'Emes ve'Yatziv' by day and 'Emes ve\"Emunah' in the night?\n(b) On which Pasuk in Tehilim is this based?\n(c) What did he also say about bowing down by the B'rachos of the Amidah? When does one bow down and when does one come up?\n(d) Which Pasuk in Tehilim did Shmuel cite as the basis for the latter ruling?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What do we ask on Rav from the Pasuk in Mal'achi \"Mipnei Sh'mi Nachas Hu\"?\n(b) How do we answer the Kashya based on the word \"Mipnei\"?\n(c) What supreme thing did Shmuel tell Rebbi Chiya bar Rav that his father had said?\n(d) How did he refer to him (Rebbi Chiya bar Rav)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) If Rav Sheishes would bow down like a stick, how did he come up?\n(b) What exactly does this mean?\n(c) What did Rabah bar Chin'na (or Chanina) the elder in the name of Rav say about 'ha'Keil ha'Kadosh' and 'Melech Oheiv Tzedakah u'Mishpat' that we say all the year round?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Elazar cites the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"Vayigbah Hash-m Tzevakos ba'Mishpat ... \" to prove that Bedi'eved, one is Yotzei during the Aseres Y'mei Teshuvah even if one says 'ha'Keil ha'Kadosh.   How does the Pasuk conclude?\n(b) How does Rebbi Elazar prove it from there?\n(c) Rav Yosef concurs with Rebbi Elazar that someone who says 'ha'Keil ha'Kadosh' or 'Melech Oheiv Tzedakah u'Mishpat' during this period is Yotzei.  What does Rabah say?\n(d) Like whom is the Halachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rabah bar Chin'na (or Chanina) the elder in the name of Rav also say about someone who is able to Daven on behalf of his fellow-Jew, but doesn't?\n(b) He learns this from a Pasuk in Shmuel.   What did Shmuel say to K'lal Yisrael in this regard?\n(c) What does Rava add to that, regarding where the sick person is a Talmid-Chacham?\n(d) Why is the Pasuk in Shmuel (in connection with Shaul ha'Melech) \"ve'Ein Choleh mikem alai ve'Goleh es Oznai!\" not an acceptable source for this?\n(e) The real source is the Pasuk there \"va'Ani ba'Chalosam Levushi Sak (and as for me, when they became ill, I wore sack-cloth)\".   Who said this about whom?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rabah bar Chin'na (or Chanina) the elder in the name of Rav say furthermore about someone who is ashamed of the sin that he performed?\n(b) Why is the Pasuk in Yechezkel (in connection with Hash-m vis-a-vis K'lal Yisrael) \"Lema'anTizk'ri Tizk'ri u'Vosht ... be'Kapri lach le'Chol asher Asis ... \" not an acceptable source for this?\n(c) From whom does he therefore learn it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) So Rabah bar Chin'na learns the current Limud from the episode of Shaul and the witch of Ein Dor (also in Shmuel).  To explain why he had asked the witch to conjure up Shmuel, what did Shaul tell him?\n(b) What did he deliberately omit?\n(c) Why did he do that?\n(d) Which sin was he ashamed of?\n(e) What did Shmuel reply that indicates that Shaul was forgiven?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) The Rabbanan cite the source as the Pasuk (there) \"ve'Hok'anum la'Hashem be'Giv'at Shaul\".   Who hanged whom (after their death)?\n(b) Why were they ...\n1. ... killed in the first place?\n2. ... hanged?\n(c) Which two words did the Navi add to the Pasuk which indicate that Shaul was forgiven?\n(d) Who actually said them?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Avahu bar Zutr'si ... informs us that the Chachamim contemplated inserting the Parshah of Balak together with Keri'as Sh'ma.   Why did they decide not to?\n(b) Why did they not institute the insertion of just the relevant Pasuk\n(c) On what grounds do we reject the suggestion that their initial intention was based on the fact that Parshas Balak contains the phrase \"Keil Motzi'am mi'Mitzrayim\"?\n(d) To which Pasuk did Rebbi Yossi bar Avin therefore attribute it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) Which Parshah containing Yetzi'as Mitzrayim did they ultimately decide to insert in the Sh'ma?\n(b) What reason does Rebbi Yehudah bar Chaviva give to explain why they picked specifically that Parshah?\n(c) Besides Yetzi'as Mitzrayim, two of the five items are the Mitzvah of Tzitzis and Da'as Miynim.  What does 'Da'as Miynim' mean?\n(d) What are the last two items (both connected with the Isur of 'Hirhur' [forbidden thoughts])?\n(e) The mention of Yetzi'as Mitzrayim and the Mitzvah of Tzitzis are clearly stated in the Parshah. The other three we learn from the Pasuk \"ve'Lo Sasuru acharei Levavchem ... \".  What do we learn from ...\n1. ... \"Acharei Levavchem\"?\n2. ... \"ve'Acharei Eineichem\"?\n3. ... \"asher Atem Zonim Achareihem\"?\n(f) We learn these three from Pesukim (the first from a Pasuk in Shoftim).  From which Pasuk there do we learn that \"Eineichem\" refers to immoral thoughts?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) What is the problem with reciting the Parshah of Tzitzis at night-time?\n(b) Then why do we say it?\n(c) From whom did Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah ultimately substantiate the Halachah that one mentions Yetzi'as Mitzrayim at night-time?\n(d) How did ben Zoma Darshen it from the Pasuk in Re'ei \"Lema'an Tizkor es Yom Tzeischa me'Eretz Mitzrayim Kol Y'mei Chayecha\"?\n(e) How old ...\n1. ... did Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah appear when he heard ben Zoma's D'rashah?\n2. ... was he really?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What do the Chachamim of Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah learn from the word \"Kol\"?\n(b) Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah queried them however, from a Pasuk in Yirmiyah.    What does the Pasuk there say about mentioning Yetzi'as Mitzrayim in the time of Mashi'ach?\n(c) To answer the Kashya, the Chachamim cited the Pasuk in Vayishlach \"Lo Yikarei Shimcha Od Ya'akov ki-im Yisrael ... \".  What must the Pasuk really mean (as we shall see in the Sugya)?\n(d) How does that answer Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah's Kashya?\n(e) We interpret the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"Al Tizk'ru Rishonos\" with reference to - Shi'bud Malchiyos (our subservience to the nations of the world since the Churban Beis-ha'Mikdash). Based on the previous answer to Rebbi Elazar's Kashya, in what connection do we interpret the continuation of that Pasuk ...\n1. ... \"ve'Kadmoniyos Al Tisbon'nu\"?\n2. ... \"Hin'ni Oseh Chadashah Atah Titzmach\", as explained by a Beraisa cited by Rav Yosef?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 13,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) To illustrate the miracles that succeeding generations of K'lal Yisrael experienced (that we just discussed), the Tana gives a Mashal of a traveler who is saved from an attack by a wolf.   What attacked him after ...\n1. ... the wolf?\n2. ... the lion?\n(b) What does the Mashal tell us other than the fact that the traveler talked about each act of salvation after it occurred?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Beraisa tell us concerning the switch from the name ...\n1. ... Avram to 'Avraham'\n2. ... Sarai to 'Sarah'.\n(b) Based on the Pasuk in Vayeira \"Vehayah Shimcha Avraham\", what does the Beraisa cited by bar Kapara say about anyone who calls Avraham 'Avram'?\n(c) And what does Rebbi Eliezer learn from the same Pasuk \"ve'Lo Yikarei Od es Shimcha 'Avram' \"?\n(d) Then why is there not also a La'v against calling ...\n1. ... Sarah 'Sarai' (\"Sarai Isht'cha Lo Tikra es Sh'mah Sarai ki Sarah Sh'mah\")?\n2. ... Ya'akov 'Ya'akov' (after his name was changed to Yisrael)?\n(e) Then why will the same not apply to Avraham, seeing as the Pasuk in Nechemyah writes \"Atah Hu Hash-m ha'Elokim asher Bacharta be'Avram ... \"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Mishnah say about someone who is reading in the Torah and reaches the Parshah of Sh'ma when the time to recite it falls due?\n(b) According to Rebbi Meir, between one Perek of Keri'as Sh'ma and the other, one may greet someone whom one honors, whereas in the middle of a Perek, one may only greet someone whom of whom one is afraid.  What does 'of whom one is afraid' mean?\n(c) To whom may one respond if he greets him first?\n(d) Rebbi Yehudah agrees with Rebbi Meir with regard to whom one may greet.   What does he say about responding to a greeting ...\n1. ... in the middle of a Perek?\n2. ... between Perakim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) What are the five 'bein ha'Perakim' according to the Tana Kama?\n(b) With which of these does Rebbi Yehudah disagree?\n(c) What reason does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Korchah give to explain why the Parshah of ...\n1. ... 'Sh'ma' precedes that of 'Vehayah Im Shamo'a'?\n2. ... 'Vehayah Im Shamo'a' precedes that of 'Vayomer'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What do we try to extrapolate from the Mishnah's first ruling ' ... Im Kivan Libo, Yatza'?\n(b) How do we initially refute the first answer, that what the Tana means is that he has Kavanah to read?\n(c) How do we answer that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi in a Beraisa mean when he says 'Keri'as Sh'ma ki'Chesavah'?\n(b) What do the Chachamim say?\n(c) If Rebbi learns his Din from\"Vehayu\" (be'Havayasan Y'hu), from where do the Chachamim learn theirs?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi learn from \"Sh'ma\"?\n(b) What do the Chachamim ...\n1. ... say to that?\n2. ... learn from \"Vehayu\"?\n(c) What does Rebbi learn from the 'Hey' of \"ha'Devarim\"?\n(d) And what do the Chachamim learn from the 'Hey' of \"ha'Devarim\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) What do we extrapolate from the fact that ...\n1. ... Rebbi requires a Pasuk (\"Vahayu\") to teach us that the Sh'ma must be recited in Lashon ha'Kodesh?\n2. ... the Chachamim require a Pasuk (\"Sh'ma\") to teach us that the Sh'ma can be recited in any language that one understands?\n(b) How do we refute both proofs?\n(c) What does each one therefore hold with regard to other Parshiyos?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) After presenting the Chachmim's (above-mentioned) D'rashah from \"Vehayu\", what does the Beraisa citing Rebbi Eliezer learn from ...\n1. ... the phrase \"ha'Devarim ... al Levavcha\"?\n2. ... the word \"ha'Eileh\"?\n(b) What does Rebbi Akiva say, based on the Pasuk \" ... asher Anochi Metzav'cha (See Tosfos DH 'asher ... \") ha'Yom al Levavecha\"?\n(c) Like whom does Rabah bar bar Chanah quoting Rebbi Yochanan rule?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Others cite Rabah bar bar Chanah quoting Rebbi Yochanan in connection with the ruling of Rebbi Acha in the name of Rebbi Yehudah. The Tana Kama of the Beraisa requires the entire Sh'ma to be said with Kavanah.   What does Rebbi Acha in the name of Rebbi Yehudah say?\n(b) Another Beraisa, after repeating the D'rashah ('she'Lo Yikra Lemafre'a) from\"Vehayu\", cites Rebbi Zutra, who says \"al Levavecha\", 'Ad Ka'n Mitzvas Kavanah, mi'Ka'n va'Eilech Mitzvas Keri'ah'.   What does 'ad Ka'n' mean?\n(c) What does Rebbi Yashiyah say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) How do we initially interpret 'mi'Ka'n va'Eilech Mitzvas Keri'ah' (of Rebbi Zutra)?\n(b) What problem do we have with this, bearing in mind that this ruling is based on the words \"Ledaber Bam\" (written in the second Parshah)?\n(c) How do we therefore reinterpret Rebbi Zutra's statement?\n(d) What problem do we have with that, bearing in mind that this ruling is based on the words \" Al Levavecha Vedibarta Bam\" (written in the first Parshah?\n(e) To answer this Kashya, we establish Rebbi Zutra like Rebbi Yitzchak.  What does Rebbi Yitzchak learn from \"al Levavchem\" (in the second Parshah)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) Bearing in mind that the Torah inserts \"Al Levavecha\" in the first Parshah, how do we interpret Rebbi Yeshayah's statement 'Ad Ka'n Mitzvas Kavanah' (implying 'Kavanah ve'Lo  Keri'ah')?\n(b) And bearing in mind that the Torah writes \"Al Levav'chem Ledaber Bam', how do we justify his statement 'mi'Ka'n va'Eilech Mitzvas Kavanah' (ve'Lo Keri'ah)?\n(c) What is the Torah then coming to teach us?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Meir in a Beraisa say about the Pasuk \"Sh'ma Yisrael ... \"?\n(b) What does Rava comment on Rebbi Meir's statement?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) What did Sumchus say about someone who is Ma'arich by the word \"Echad\"?\n(b) How does Rav Acha bar Ya'akov interpret Sumchus' statement?\n(c) What does Rav Ashi say that one should nevertheless take care not to do?\n(d) What did Rebbi Chiya bar Aba comment when he saw Rebbi Yirmiyah spend an abnormally long time saying \"Echad\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Nasan bar Mar Ukva Amar Rav Yehudah mean when he said that one must stand for \"al Levavecha\"?\n(b) What does Rebbi Yochanan say?\n(c) In fact, Rebbi Yochanan follows the statement that he made earlier, where he ruled like Rebbi Acha.  What did Rebbi Acha rule in the name of Rebbi Yehudah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Beraisa say about the Pasuk \"Sh'ma Yisrael\" in connection with Rebbi?\n(b) What did Rebbi Chiya reply when Rav commented that he did not notice Rebbi taking upon himself the yoke of the Kingdom of Heaven?\n(c) He addressed Rav as 'bar Pachsi'.  What does 'bar Pachsi' mean?\n(d) According to bar Kapara, Rebbi did not complete the Sh'ma after the Shi'ur.  What did Rebbi Shimon, Rebbi's son, say?\n(e) What did the latter reply when bar Kapara asked him why, according to him, Rebbi found it necessary to say a D'var Torah connected with Yetzi'as Mitzrayim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Ila the son of Rav Shmuel bar Marsa say in the name of Rav concerning someone who dozes off after reciting the first Pasuk of 'Sh'ma'?\n(b) What did Rav Nachman tell Daru his Eved in this regard?\n(c) What did Rav Yosef the son of Rabah reply when Rav Yosef asked what his father used to do when fighting sleep whist reciting the Sh'ma?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) What is a 'P'rakdan'?\n(b) What problem do we have with Rav Yosef's ruling that a P'rakdan may not recite the Sh'ma?\n(c) The Kashya is based on Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi.  What was Rebbi ben Levi's reaction to someone who lies on his back?\n(d) How do we solve the problem? What is permitted with regard to sleeping but is forbidden regarding the recital of the Sh'ma?\n(e) How do we reconcile this with Rebbi Yochanan, who would recite the Sh'ma whilst leaning?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) When Rebbi Meir says in our Mishnah that, between chapters 'Sho'el Mipnei ha'Kavod u'Meishiv', why can he not mean 'Meishiv Machmas Kavod'?\n(b) What must he then mean?\n(c) And, by the same token, what must he mean in the Seifa, when he says that in the middle of a chapter 'Sho'el Mipnei ha'Yir'ah,*u'Meishiv*'?\n(d) What problem does this create?\n(e) To answer the Kashya, we answer 'Chasuri Mechs'ra, ve'Hachi Katani ... .   How will we then read ...\n1. ... the Reisha?\n2. ... the Seifa?"
      }
    ]
