  {
    "daf": 39,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What problem did Rebbi Yirmiyah have with regard to the B'rachah Achronah that Rebbi Yochanan recited over the salted olive?\n(b) How did Rebbi Zeira resolve it?\n(c) And he proves it from a Mishnah in Keilim.   What does the Tana there say about a small olive and a large one?\n(d) What is a 'Zayis Aguri'?\n(e) Rebbi Avahu explains that Its real name is 'Avruti' or'Samrusi'.   So why did they call it 'Aguri'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Based on an episode that occurred with two Talmidim of bar Kapara before whom they placed Durmaskin (mountain spinach) and young birds, we suggest that the B'rachah over Shelakos is a Machlokes Tana'im.   When bar Kapara gave permission to eat, over which of the two did one of the Talmidim recite a B'rachah?\n(b) How did ...\n1. ... the other Talmid react?\n2. ... bar Kapara react?\n(c) Why did bar Kapara ...\n1. ... initially explain that he was angry with the second Talmid?\n2. ... subsequently explain that he was angry with the first Talmid?\n(d) What happened to the two Talmidim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) How do we initially interpret the Machlokes between the two Talmidim?\n(b) Then why did ...\n1. ... the first one recite a B'rachah over the birds?\n2. ... his friend then mock him?\n(c) We conclude however, that both Talmidim held that the B'rachah over Shelakos is 'Shehakol'.   In that case, why did the second Talmid mock his friend? What is the advantage of Durmaskin over young birds?\n(d) In hindsight, why can Durmaskin not mean plums, as some suggest?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Zeira relates how, when they were guests of Rav Huna, he would differentiate (B'rachah-wise) between heads of turnips that were cut up into large pieces and those that were cut up into small pieces.   What exactly did Rav Huna say?\n(b) What was his reason?\n(c) When they were of Rav Yehudah, what did he tell them to do in this regard?\n(d) Why was that."
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) In similar fashion, Rav Ashi relates how Rav Kahana initially differentiated between the B'rachah that one recites over a dish consisting of cooked beets and one consisting of cooked turnips. What B'rachah did he therefore require over the latter?\n(b) Why is that?\n(c) On what grounds did he change his mind?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Chisda describes a dish of cooked spinach as being good for the heart and for the eyes.   What else is it certainly good for?\n(b) What condition does Abaye require for this to be effective?\n(c) What does Rav Papa say, B'rachah-wise, about the juice of ...\n1. ... cooked beets and of cooked turnips?\n2. ... other cooked vegetables?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Papa asks what the Din will be regarding the juice of mint (of which one only places a little in the pot, which will be 'Borei P'ri ha'Adamah', assuming it is meant to sweeten the dish in which it is cooked.   On what grounds will the correct B'rachah be 'Shehakol'? What other purpose might the mint serve?\n(b) We resolve the She'eilah based on a Beraisa.   What does the Tana say about mint once it has given taste to the pot regarding ...\n1. ... T'rumah?\n2. ... Tum'ah?\n(c) What do we prove from there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav Chiya bar Ashi, one recites 'ha'Motzi' over 'Pas he'Tzenumah bi'Ke'arah'.   What is 'Pas he'Tzenumah bi'Ke'arah'?\n(b) This clashes with a statement of Rebbi Chiya however. What does Rebbi Chiya say about reciting 'ha'Motzi'.   When must one conclude it?\n(c) What is then the problem with Rav Chiya bar Ashi's ruling according to Rebbi Chiya?\n(d) What B'rachah will one therefore recite over 'Pas he'Tzenumah bi'Ke'arah' according to Rebbi Chiya?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rava ask on Rebbi Chiya?\n(b) What does Rava therefore say about the B'rachah of 'ha'Motzi'?\n(c) The Neherda'i did like Rebbi Chiya.   What did the Rabbanan do?\n(d) Ravina quoting his mother, repeats the Machlokes.   What did she tell him his father used to do?\n(e) Like whom is the Halachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Huna rules that if there are both whole loaves and pieces of bread lying on the table, one is permitted to recite the B'rachah over the pieces.   On what condition is it even obligatory to do so?\n(b) What does Rebbi Yochanan say?\n(c) On what condition does he concede that one recites the B'rachah over the pieces?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yirmiyah bar Aba suggests that the latter ruling is a Machlokes Tana'im, who argue in a Beraisa, over someone who has small complete onions and large pieces of onion that need to be Ma'asered.   The Tana Kama gives precedence to the former.   What does Rebbi Yehudah say?\n(b) What does Rebbi Yirmiyah bar Aba now suggest?\n(c) Refuting his suggestion however, we conclude that everyone agrees that the B'rachah over Chashuv takes precedence.   Why do the Chachamim then say in the case of T'rumah, one Ma'asers the Shalem? What is the case?\n(d) This is based on their opinion in a Mishnah in T'rumos.   What does Rebbi Yehudah say there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak say a G-d-fearing person should do regarding the initial Machlokes between Rav Huna and Rebbi Yochanan (Pesisin v Shalem)?\n(b) Which one does he then cut?\n(c) Why did he mention Mar b'rei de'Revina?\n(d) What did he used to do?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak ask Rav Shalman when the latter cited a Beraisa bearing out the previous ruling?\n(b) What did he comment when he heard his name?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) What similar statement did Rav Papa make concerning the Matzos on Pesach?\n(b) According to Rebbi Aba, what is the Din on a regular Shabbos?\n(c) Which Pasuk serves as the basis for ...\n1. ... the former ruling?\n2. ... the latter ruling?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Ashi see Rav Kahana do when he made 'Motzi' on Shabbos?\n(b) What did Ravina ask Rav Ashi regarding Rebbi Zeira's custom to cut off a chunk that was large enough for the entire meal on Shabbos?\n(c) What did the latter reply?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Ami and Rav Asi used to do when they came across bread that had been used for Eruv Chatzeros?\n(b) Why did they do that?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 40,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Rav draws a distinction between someone who, after reciting a 'Motzi' (on Shabbos), hands a slice of bread to one of the participants and says 'Tul Baruch!' and where he says 'Bring salt' or 'condiments'.   What does 'Tul Baruch' mean?\n(b) One of the sources for the Din that speaking between the B'rachah and the eating is considered a Hefsek is the Din that someone who speaks between the Tefilin shel Yad and the Tefilin shel Rosh must recite another B'rachah.   What is the other?\n(c) What distinction does Rav now draw between the two cases?\n(d) What is then the reason for the distinction?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yochanan say?\n(b) What does 'G'vil le'Turi!' mean?\n(c) Rav Sheishes goes even further.   What does he say about 'G'vil le'Turi!'?\n(d) This ruling is based on a statement of Rav Yehudah.   What did Rav Yehudah Amar Rav say about feeding one's animals?\n(e) On which Pasuk in the second paragraph of the 'Sh'ma' is this ruling based?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rava bar Shmuel in the name of Rebbi Chiya say about the person who is going to recite ha'Motzi on behalf of others? When does he permit him to go ahead and do so?\n(b) What did Rava bar Shmuel himself do when he once ate by the Resh Gelusa and they brought him bread over which to recite the B'rachah?\n(c) Why did he not abide by his own ruling?\n(d) What does 'Leis Dein Tzarich Bashash' mean?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rava bar Shmuel in the name of Rebbi Chiya say about urinating?\n(b) Why not when standing?\n(c) On what condition does Rav Kahana say 'even if one is standing'?\n(d) Why is that?\n(e) What option does one have even if there is no soft earth?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) And what does Rava bar Shmuel in the name of Rebbi Chiya say one should ...\n1. ... eat after one's meal in order to avoid health problems?\n2. ... drink after having drunk other beverages?\n(b) After citing a Beraisa in support of Rava bar Shmuel's latest statement, we cite a second Beraisa which warns what will happen if one does not take heed of this advice.   What will happen to someone who fails to do so ...\n1. ... by day?\n2. ... by night?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What does a third Beraisa say about someone who drinks a lot of water after eating? What does 'ha'Makpeh ... ' mean?\n(b) How much water does Rav Chisda say one needs to drink after bread?\n(c) And what does Rav Mari Amar Rebbi Yochanan say one should eat once every thirty days to avoid contracting ...\n1. ... Ask'ra (croup)?\n2. ... any illness?\n(d) What is the reason for his first statement?\n(e) Why should one then not eat mustard every day?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav Chiya bar Ashi Amar Rav, what illness to small fish prevent?\n(b) Besides keeping a person's body fit, what other good reason is there to eat small fish?\n(c) And according to Rebbi Chama b'Rebbi Chanina, what illness will a person who eats Ketzach (black cumin) avoid?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) We query this however, from a Beraisa. What does the Tana say about ...\n1. ... Ketzach that is highly detrimental?\n2. ... someone who sleeps on the east side of a Ketzach granary?\n(b) Why specifically on the east?\n(c) How do we reconcile Rebbi Chama b'Rebbi Chanina with the Beraisa?\n(d) What did Rebbi Yirmiyah's mother do when, whilst baking bread for her son, she decided to add Ketzach?\n(e) Why did she do that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yehudah learned in our Mishnah that over various species of herbs one recites 'Borei Miynei Desha'im'.   Like whom does Rebbi Zeira (or Rebbi Chin'na bar Papa) Pasken?\n(b) To explain Rebbi Yehudah's reasoning, the same Amora cites the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Baruch Hash-m Yom Yom\".   Why can the Pasuk not be taken literally?\n(c) How does he therefore explain it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What distinction does the same Amora draw between Hash-m and human beings regarding filling a vessel?\n(b) How does he learn the former from the Pasuk in Beshalach \"ve'Hayah Im Shamo'a Tishma\"?\n(c) How else does he explain the same Pasuk\"?\n(d) What if one fails to revise what one has learnt?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Mishnah say about someone who recites 'Borei P'ri ...\n1. ... ha'Adamah' over fruit that grows on a tree?\n2. ... ha'Eitz over fruit that grows from the ground?\n(b) Why the difference?\n(c) What does the Tana say about someone who recites 'Shehakol' over either of those two?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Tana Kama in the Mishnah in Bikurim say about a case where the fountain that waters the tree dries up or the tree is cut down with regard to Bikurim?\n(b) What does Rebbi Yehudah say?\n(c) What is his reason?\n(d) Based on that Mishnah, like whom does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak establish our Mishnah (which renders Yotzei someone who recites 'Borei P'ri ha'Adamah' over the fruit of a tree)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What is the problem with the Mishnah, which rules that someone who recites 'Borei P'ri ha'Eitz' over fruit that grows from the ground is not Yotzei?\n(b) Here too, Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak establishes the author as Rebbi Yehudah.   What does Rebbi Yehudah say about the tree from which Adam ha'Rishon ate?\n(c) What is the logic behind his opinion?\n(d) How does this resolve the problem?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the Pasuk in No'ach \"Vayesht min ha'Yayin va'Yishkor\", what does Rebbi Meir say about the fruit in question?\n(b) What is the logic behind his opinion?\n(c) And on what grounds does Rebbi Nechemyah maintain that they ate from the fig-tree?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) On what condition does one not recite 'Borei P'ri ha'Eitz' over the fruit of a tree?\n(b) Which B'rachah does one recite over it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav Huna, what are the two exceptions to the Mishnah's ruling that if one recites 'Shehakol' over any of the species listed there one is Yotzei?\n(b) What does Rebbi Yochanan say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Meir say in a Beraisa about someone who, before eating bread (or a fig) says 'How nice is this bread (fig), Baruch ha'Makom she'Bara'o (she'Bera'ah)'?\n(b) What does Rebbi Yossi say? Which principle does he cite that refutes Rebbi Meir's ruling?\n(c) Like whom do we initially try to establish ...\n1. ... Rav Huna?\n2. ... Rebbi Yochanan?\n(d) How do we reconcile ...\n1. ... Rav Huna with Rebbi Meir? Why will even the latter agree that one will not be Yotzei if one recites 'Shehakol' over bread?\n2. ... Rebbi Yochanan with Rebbi Yossi? Why will even the latter agree that one will be Yotzei if one recites 'Shehakol' over bread?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav comment when Binyamin the shepherd recited the B'rachah 'B'rich Ma'rei de'hai Pita (Blessed be the master of this bread)'?\n(b) What is the problem with this ruling, based on another statement of Rav?\n(c) Which additional word do we insert to answer the Kashya?\n(d) How do we refute the Kashya that over bread, one needs to recite three B'rachos (Birchas ha'Mazon)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) We query Rav from a Mishnah in Sotah.   What does the Tana there say about Parshas Sotah, Viduy Ma'aser, K'ri'as Sh'ma, Tefilah and Birchas ha'Mazon?\n(b) What is the Kashya on Rav?\n(c) What do we answer? Why might we nevertheless have thought that Binyamin the shepherd ought not to be Yotzei?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) If, as we just learned, Rav holds that 'Any B'rachah that does not contain the Name of Hash-m is not a B'rachah', what does Rebbi Yochanan say?\n(b) Abaye cites a Beraisa which explains the Pasuk in Ki Savo (in connection with Viduy Ma'aser) \" ... Lo Avarti mi'Mitzvosecha ve'Lo Shachachti\". The Tana learns from \"Lo Avarti mi'Mitzvosecha\"  - 'mi'le'Varech'cha alav'.  What does he learn from \"ve'Lo Shachachti\"?\n(c) What does Abaye prove from there?\n(d) How will Rebbi Yochanan amend the Beraisa?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) Over what does the Mishnah require 'Shehakol' to be recited?\n(b) What does the Tana say about vinegar, Novlos and locusts?\n(c) On what grounds does Rebbi Yehudah disagree?\n(d) According to Rebbi Yehudah, if a number of species contain the Shiv'as ha'Minim (the seven species with which Eretz Yisrael is specifically blessed), then that takes preference.   What do the Chachamim say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) Regarding the B'rachah of 'Shehakol', which item does the Beraisa add to the list of ...\n1. ... meat of Beheimos, Chayos and fowl?\n2. ... milk and eggs?\n(b) And what does the Tana say about ...\n1. ... bread that became moldy and wine that became ropey (formed a skin)?\n2. ... a cooked dish that has lost its form?\n3. ... salt, salt-water and mushrooms?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) We query the very last ruling, from the Beraisa which forbids someone who makes a Neder from fruit of the ground to benefit from fruit of the ground.   On what condition does he incorporate mushrooms in this ruling?\n(b) What does Abaye answer?\n(c) How do we reconcile this with the fact that our Mishnah says 'al Davar she'Ein Gidulo min ha'Aretz' (including mushrooms)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Zeira and Rebbi Ila'a argue over the meaning of 'Novlos' in our Mishnah. One of them says it is 'Bushli Kamra' (dates that are sun-burnt), the other, 'Tamri de'Zika'.   What are 'Tamri de'Zika'?\n(b) How do we query the latter opinion from Rebbi Yehudah in our Mishnah, who refers to Novlos as a kind of curse?\n(c) What do we answer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) Alternatively, we query the same opinion from the ruling in our Mishnah that the B'rachah over Novlos is 'Shehakol'.   What is the problem?\n(b) We answer that there is no Machlokes over 'Novlos' S'tam.   How does that answer the Kashya?\n(c) What are they then arguing about?\n(d) Where does 'Novlos Temarah' appear?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q26",
        "label": "26)",
        "text": "(a) The Mishnah in D'mai discusses 'ha'Kalin she'bi'Demai'.   What does this mean?\n(b) The list includes Shitin and Rimin (a species of white figs and of wild-figs), Uzradin (sorb-apples), B'nos-Shu'ach (another species of fig) and B'nos Shikmah (a fig branch that has been grafted into a chestnut tree), Gufnin (winter-grapes), Nitzpeh (a caper-bush) and Novlos Temarim (over which Rebbi Zeira and Rebbi Ila'a argue).   Why did the Chachamim exempt all of these from the Din of D'mai?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q27",
        "label": "27)",
        "text": "(a) Seeing as the Tana exempts all of the above from D'mai, what can we extrapolate will be the Din if the owner has not yet Ma'asered them?\n(b) What problem does this create with the opinion that defines Novlos Temarim as Tamri de'Zika (that have fallen off the tree)?\n(c) We solve the problem based on the ruling of Rebbi Yitzchak ... quoting Rebbi Eliezer ben Ya'akov.   What does he say about Leket, Shikchah and Pe'ah which the poor man gathers into the granary?\n(d) How does this answer the Kashya here?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q28",
        "label": "28)",
        "text": "(a) Others poiny out a discrepancy between the wording of our Mishnah and that of the Beraisa, according to the opinion that defines 'Novlos Temarim' as 'Bushli Kamra'.   Which discrepancy?\n(b) What is the Gemara's conclusion?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 41,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) According to Ula, the Machlokes between Rebbi Yehudah and the Rabbanan in our Mishnah (whether one recites a Berachah over the seven kinds, or over whichever one prefers), is confined to two foods with the same Berachah.   What will be the Din by two foods with different Berachos?\n(b) Then how will Ula explain the Beraisa which says that the Berachah over a radish exempts one from reciting a Berachah over an olive?\n(c) Others learn the Machlokes even when the two Berachos are different.   What is then the basis of the Machlokes?\n(d) According to Rebbi Chanan, the entire Pasuk (of \"Eretz Chitah u'Se'orah\" etc.) comes to teach us the various Shiurim: How do we interpret ...\n1. ... \"Eretz Chitah\" (regarding someone who enters a house which is stricken with Tzara'as)?\n2. ... \"Se'orah\" (regarding the Din of a bone of a corpse)?\n3. ... \"Gefen\" (regarding a Nazir)?\n4. ... \"Te'einah\" (regarding carrying on Shabbos)?\n5. ... \"Rimon\" (regarding Tum'as Keilim)?\n6. ... \"Eretz Zeis-Shemen\" (regarding most things). Which things?\n7. ... \"u'Devash\" (regarding Yom Kipur)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What do Rav Yosef or Rav Yitzchak (who require the Pasuk to list the order of priorities) do with the above Din of Rebbi Chanan? From where do they know the Shiurim?\n(b) Where are dates mentioned among the seven kinds?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) They brought Rav Hamnuna a bowl of dates and pomegranates. Although he intended to partake of both kinds, Rav Hamnuna recited a Berachah over the dates and not the pomegranates.   What bothered Rav Chisda?\n(b) And what did Rav Hamnuna answer him?\n(c) What did Rav Chisda mean when he exclaimed 'Ma'an Yahiv Lan Nagri de'Parzela, ve'Nashme'inach'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) Tosfos says that we do not rule like the minority opinion of Rav Sheishes, who says that fruit in the middle of the meal requires both a Berachah Rishonah and a Berachah Acharonah, but rather like Rav Huna and Rav Nachman.   What do they say?\n(b) Rav Sheishes maintains that the only thing that requires a Berachah before and not afterwards is 'Pas ha'Ba'ah be'Kisnin'. What is 'Pas ha'Ba'ah be'Kisnin', and what does Rav Sheishes mean?\n(c) What does Rebbi Chiya say about bread and wine?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What is meant by something which comes because of the meal ?\n(b) What does Rav Papa hold regarding both the Berachah Rishonah and the Berachah Acharonah, when it comes during the meal?\n(c) Rav Papa lists two other categories of food.   What will be the Din  regarding both Berachah Rishonah and Berachah Acharonah, by food that is brought ...\n1. ... during the meal, but not because of the it.\n2. ... because of the meal, but after it.\n(d) They asked Ben Zoma why it is that if bread exempts all foods that come during the meal because of the meal, from a Berachah, then why does it not exempt wine.   What did he answer?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 42,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Huna ate thirteen loaves of bread, after which he did not Bensch.   What is the simple explanation of this statement, and why does Rashi reject it?\n(b) Rashi therefore opts to learn like the Behag.   What is the Behag's explanation?\n(c) Rav Yehudah bar Chaviva explained that he recited 'ha'Motzi over Pas ha'Ba'ah be'Kisnin, because of Shmuel, who ruled like Rebbi Muna, who quoted Rebbi Yehudah as saying that that is the correct Berachah to recite.   What did Rav Yehudah comment on that?\n(d) If, on the other hand, the Halachah is not like Rebbi Muna, then why did Rav Yehudah himself rule like Shmuel, who holds that one may use 'Lachmaniyos' for an Eiruv, and that the appropriate Berachah to recite is therefore 'ha'Motzi'? What are 'Lachmaniyos'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Why did Rav Papa eat (without Bensching and reciting a fresh Berachah), after they had already concluded the meal?\n(b) And why did Raba, who was sitting at the Chief Rabbi's table, eat - without Bensching and a fresh Berachah, even after they had removed the table?\n(c) 'ha'Ra'uy be'Shemen, Shemen Me'akvo'.   What does this mean?\n(d) Some say that the conclusion of the meal forbids one to continue eating without Bensching and a fresh Berachah; others say it is the removal of the table, and according to others, it is the washing with oil.   What is the Halachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) We have just learnt that 'Teikef li'Netilas Yadayim Berachah'. What are the other two 'Halachic Teikefs'.\n(b) Abaye added 'Teikef le'Talmidei-Chachamim Berachah, which he supported  with two sources (from Ya'akov and Yosef).   What are the two sources?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) What is  'Yayin she'Lifnei ha'Mazon', and what is 'Yayin she'le'Achar ha'Mazon'? Does a Berachah over the former exempt one from reciting a Berachah over the latter?\n(b) What is the Parperes that came before the meal, and what is the Parperes that comes after the meal? Does a Berachah over the former exempt one from reciting a Berachah over the latter?\n(c) Does a Berachah over the Parperes exempt one from reciting a Berachah over bread, and vice-versa?`"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) If a number of people sit down to eat, why can one not be Motzi all the other members of the group - like he would do if they were leaning?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) We learnt in our Mishnah that a Berachah over the wine before the meal covers the wine after the meal.   When does this not apply, and why?\n(b) When does it apply even when it is not Shabbos or Yom-Tov?\n(c) Why did Abaye recite a Berachah on every cup - even on Yom-Tov?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) If the Berachah over wine before the meal covers the wine after the meal, why might a Berachah over the wine during the meal be different?\n(b) In fact, the Amora'im argue over this point.   What proof does the Gemara attempt to bring from our Mishnah, which says: 'Ba Lahem Yayin be'Soch ha'Mazon, Kol Echad ve'Echad Mevarech le'Atzmo; Achar ha'Mazon, Echad Mevarech le'Kulam'?\n(c) Why is it not, in fact, a proof?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Our Mishnah writes 'Beirach Al ha'Pas Patar es ha'Parperes; Al ha'Parperes, Lo Patar es ha'Pas'. Beis Shamai Omrim, Af Lo Ma'aseh Kedeirah'.   What are the two possible interpretations of Beis Shamai's statement?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Our Mishnah requires three people to have eaten reclining, before they may Bensch with a Mezuman. The Beraisa obligates a Mezuman even if they only sat.   How do we reconcile the two?\n(b) At the funeral of Rav, Rav Ada bar Ahavah tore a second Keri'ah for his Rebbe.   Why did he do that?\n(c) What put his mind at ease?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 43,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Yochanan, reclining also helps with regard to wine.   What does this mean?\n(b) What does Rav hold? (two opinions)\n(c) Why did they used to wash one hand before the meal?\n(d) When all the guests arrived, and they subsequently went into the dining-room to eat, would they then need to wash one or two?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa also writes, that when the guests were served wine before entering the dining-room - when it was not customary to lean - everyone had to recite the Berachah himself), so we see that leaning is necessary for wine, too.   How can Rav then say (according to the first Lashon) that wine does not require leaning?\n(b) On the other hand, in light of the Seifa of the Beraisa, where we specifically see that leaning helps, how can Rav say, in the second Lashon, that leaning is not effective by wine?\n(c) Why is it, that when wine is brought at the end of the meal, one person recites the Berachah for everyone, yet when it is brought in the middle of the meal, each person must recite the Berachah himself?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Why does the person who recites the Berachah over the wine at the end of the meal also recite the Berachah over the incense, and what is the proof from the person who washes 'last'.\n(b) What did Rebbi say to Rav that had him worried, and what was he worried about?\n(c) What did Rebbi really mean?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) When does one recite a Berachah over incense?\n(b) Why did this bother Rebbi Zeira?\n(c) How did they reassure him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) According to the contention of many Amora'im, which Berachah does one recite over the various types of incense?\n(b) Which is the exception (and why), and what Berachah does one recite over it?\n(c) How does the Gemara refute the above contention?\n(d) Rav Yehudah would recite the Berachah of 'Borei Shemen Artzeinu' over Afarsemon oil.   Why can we not follow Rav Yehudah's opinion, and which Berachah do we recite over it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) The correct Berachah over 'Kosht' (one of the eleven spices of the Ketores) is 'Borei Atzei Besamim'.   Is this also the Berachah that one recites if one soaks 'Kosht' in oil, or if one grinds it?\n(b) What Berachah does one recite over ...\n1. ... jasmin?\n2. ... Chilfi de'Yama (alias Shiboles Nerd - lavender)? Why is this called 'Eitz'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What Berachah does recite over ...\n1. ... a garden lily?\n2. ... a lily that grows in the field?\n(b) What Berachah does one recite when smelling an Esrog or a quince?\n(c) On what occasion does one recite the Berachah 'Baruch ... Asher Lo Chisar be'Olamo Kelum ... '?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) From where do we learn that smelling requires a Berachah?\n(b) What do we learn from the Pasuk in Koheles \"es ha'Kol Asah Yafeh be'Ito\" - and what has this to do with hanging a creeper round a pig's neck?\n(c) 'Avukah ki'Shenayim, ve'Yarei'ach ki'Sheloshah'.   What does this mean?\n(d) Do the two and the three include him or not - and how do we know that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) In connection with whom does the Torah in va'Yishlach, \"Hi Mutzeis\"? What do we learn from her?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Why does Raban Gamliel rule like Beis Shamai, who holds that, when, at the end of the meal, oil to wash the hands and a myrtle twig to smell were brought into the room, one would first recite the Berachah over the oil?\n(b) Why (according to our - Rashi's - text in the Gemara) did Rav Papa first recite a Berachah over the myrtle-twig?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) According to Beis Shamai, the oil is held in one's right hand, and the wine in one's left.   Which wine are we talking about, and over which does he recite the Berachah first?\n(b) What do Beis Hillel hold in this regard, and what does one then do with the oil on one's fingers?\n(c) What does one do if the Shamash is a Talmid Chacham, and why should the Din be different in this case - Why might this not be the Halachah?\n(d) When is it permitted for a Talmid-Chacham to go out wearing perfume, and under which circumstances is it nevertheless permitted?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) A Talmid-Chacham has a more stringent code of conduct than others. He should not go out alone at night, nor should he talk to a woman in the street.   Why are these forbidden?\n(b) Under which circumstances is going out alone at night permitted?\n(c) Why is talking to a woman in the street forbidden even with one's own closest relatives?\n(d) Walking in the street with patched shoes is forbidden.   Under which circumstances is it permitted, and why does the prohibition not apply in the winter?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) Neither is a Talmid-Chacham permitted to sit in a gathering of unlearned people.   Why is that?\n(b) He should not be the last to enter the Beis Hamedrash.Others add that he should not take large steps.   Why not?\n(c) What is the antidote for this?\n(d) Neither should he walk with his head held high.   Why not?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 44,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) If they bring in a salty dish together with bread, the Berachah over the salty dish will exempt the bread from a Berachah.   To which sort of salty dish would bread be secondary?\n(b) Rabba bar bar Chanah claimed that they would follow Rebbi Yochanan to eat the fruit of Ginusar, and that 'Ki Havinan Bei Mei'ah, Menaktinan Lei le'Chol Chad ve'Chad Asarah Asarah'.   What does this mean?\n(c) What happened to the various Amora'im when they partook of the fruit of Ginusar?\n(d) There was a tree on Har Hamelech (in the days of Yanai ha'Melech), from which they used to obtain forty Sa'ah of young birds, which were hatched three times monthly, to feed the workers who cut the figs.   What is the Gemara coming to teach us with this statement?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) It is a great Yichus for a Kohen to marry a Bas Kohen. How many pairs of brothers who were Kohanim married pairs of Benos Kohen who were sisters in Gufnis (See Maharsha regarding the significance of the name 'Gufnis'), and how many such cases could they find in Bavel (from Sura to Neherda'a)?\n(b) What significance does the Gemara attach to salt and to a dish with gravy?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rabban Gamliel, which Berachah Acharonah does one recite over grapes, figs and pomegranates?\n(b) What is the opinion of the Chachamim?\n(c) And what does Rebbi Akiva say?\n(d) In the opinion of Rebbi Tarfon, which Berachah Rishonah does one recite over water?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) What is Rabban Gamliel's source for necessitating Bensching over all the seven kinds?\n(b) Seeing as the Pasuk does indeed mention all seven kinds before writing \"ve'Achalta ve'Sava'ata u'Veirachta\", why do the Rabbanan restrict Bensching to bread?\n(c) What does Rabban Gamliel do with the fact that 'Eretz' is written where it is?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) Over what kinds of food does one recite 'Mezonos' before, and 'Al ha'Michyah' after, eating.\n(b) According to Rav Chisda, the Berachah Acharonah over fruit concludes 'Al ha'Aretz ve'Al Peiroseha', and according to Rebbi Yochanan 'Al ha'Aretz ve'Al ha'Peiros'.   What makes this version of the Machlokes illogical?\n(c) Then how do we amend it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) According to some Amora'im, no Berachah Acharonah is required over vegetables or over water.   What does Rav papa say?\n(b) What did Rav Ashi used to do, and what is the Halachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) There is nothing that requires a Berachah Acharonah but not a Berachah Rishonah. There are however, things that require a Berachah Rishonah, but no Berachah Acharonah.   What would these be ...\n1. ... according to the Amora'im whom we cited above?\n2. ... according to Rav Papa?\n(b) Which Berachah did the B'nei Eretz Yisrael used to recite after removing their Tefilin?\n(c) According to them, what is it that requires a Berachah before and not after?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Of all foods the size of an egg, which is the healthiest?\n(b) What did Ravin mean when he said, 'Tava Bei'sasa Gulgalta mi'Shita Kaisi Sulta'?\n(c) According to Rav Dimi, what is healthier still than a slightly-boiled (and still runny) egg?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Which kind of vegetable is considered a meal (and which Rebbi Akiva therefore maintains requires Bensching)?\n(b) Why should one chew the spleen of an animal, but not swallow it?\n(c) And why would one boil leek and swallow it but not chew it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What is the effect of  eating food that has only partially grown?\n(b) Until which stage of growth does this apply?\n(c) When they brought raw vegetables before Ameimar, Rav Ashi and Mar Zutra - before four hours in the morning had passed, the former two ate, but Mar Zutra did not.   Why were the former two surprised at Mar Zutra?\n(d) How did Mar Zutra justify himself?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Gemara say about a tiny fish that is found among the reeds?\n(b) And what does the Gemara say about the neck (the Beis ha'Shechitah) of the animal?\n(c) Mangold (a kind of beet) is healthy, but what are the advantages of eating cabbage?\n(d) Which other two things, besides Mei Sisin (a type of herb), the womb and the lobe of the liver, are included in the list of things which the Beraisa considers healthy?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) According to Abaye, turnip, which is unhealthy when eaten on its own, is healthy when it is cooked with juicy meat.   What does Rava say?\n(b) Rebbi Yochanan agrees with Rava's opinion.   What do Shmuel and Rav Papa hold?\n(c) Why did Rava refer to Rav Papa as 'Sudni'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) Salted fish is unhealthy on certain days after it has been salted.   When does the salt make no difference?\n(b) What is a good antidote for someone who eats it when it is not well cooked?\n(c) When does one not recite a Berachah over water?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 45,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What is the difference between two people who ate together and three people who ate together?\n(b) The Mishnah lists various cases of people who seemingly ate ba'Aveirah, and nevertheless combined for a Mezuman.   What is the Chidush in all these cases?\n(c) How much must one have eaten in order to Bensch Mezuman?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Asi learns 'Mezuman' from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Gadlu la'Hashem Iti\" etc.   From which Pasuk in Devarim does Rebbi Avahu learn it?\n(b) What else do we learn from \"Gadlu la'Hashem Iti \" (or perhaps it is from the continuation of the Pasuk \"u'Neromemah Shemo Yachdav\")?\n(c) What do we learn from the Pasuk in Shemos \"Moshe Yedaber, ve'ha'Elokim Ya'anenu be'Kol\", and how do we learn it from there?\n(d) What should the speaker do if he knows that the translator is unable to speak as loudly as he does?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yochanan and Rav argue about whether two people who have eaten together are permitted to Bensch Mezuman, or not.   How does the one who says that they are , explain our Mishnah, which writes 'Sheloshah she'Achlu ke'Achas, Chayavin le'Zamein', implying that three people Bensch Mezuman, but not two .\n(b) The Gemara asks on him from a Beraisa, which writes that three people who ate together are forbidden to separate - but are obligated to Bensch together with a Mezuman.   What is the Kashya from there?\n(c) How do we answer the Kashya?\n(d) And what does he do with the Beraisa, which permits a Shamash to join the two people whom he is serving, even though he has not been invited to do so (something which he is not permitted to do when there are three), only because we take for granted the fact that they are more than pleased to have a Mezuman. But why should they be pleased, if they can Bensch Mezuman anyway?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) Since a hundred women have no more obligation to Bensch Mezuman than two men, how will the opinion which holds that two men are not permitted to Bensch Mezuman, explain the Beraisa, which writes that a group of women is ?\n(b) Why are a group comprising women and slaves not permitted to Bensch Mezuman together?\n(c) Rav says that if one person out of a group of three left the group, one calls him to participate in the Mezuman - from wherever where he is. This implies that, if he does not answer, the remaining two are not permitted to Bensch Mezuman without him.   Does this prove that Rav is the one to say that two people may not Bensch Mezuman, even if they want to?\n(d) Rebbi Yochanan says that if two people ate together, one can be Yotze with the Bensching of the other.   What does the Gemara prove from here?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) The Rabbanan who came from Eretz Yisrael taught, that two people who ate together, are permitted to Bensch Mezuman . How does this clash with what we just concluded?\n(b) Whom were the Rabbanan from Eretz Yisrael quoting?\n(c) We learnt earlier, that if one person leaves a group of three, they call him to answer there where he is.   Will this also apply to the tenth person out of a group of ten? If not, why the difference?\n(d) Rav Ashi however, does not agree with this. According to him, the reverse is more logical.   Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What is the meaning of 'Mitzvah Leichalek', and to what does it refer?\n(b) When does it not apply?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) When must one stop eating, to answer Mezuman, and when is this not necessary?\n(b) Why did Rav Papa and a friend stop eating for Aba Mar, Rav papa's son?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Why did Yehudah bar Mereimar, Mar bar Rav Ashi and Rav Acha mi'Difti not Bensch Mezuman, although they had eaten together?\n(b) What did Mereimar tell them?\n(c) Why did they not recite Mezuman there and then?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) What does someone who did not eat answer, if he hears three people Bensching Mezuman?\n(b) Why did Rav Papa say that one answers 'Amen'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) One Beraisa praises someone who answers 'Amen' after his own Berachos, another Beraisa writes that this is despicable. How do we reconcile the two Beraisos?\n(b) Abaye would say the 'Amen' after 'Bonei ve'Rachamav Yerushalayim' aloud, Rav Ashi would say it quietly.   What is each one's reason?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 46,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Who was nicknamed 'Ketina Charich Shaki'? What does this mean?\n(b) Why did Rebbi Avahu pay him a visit?\n(c) What did the latter promise to do in the vent that he (Rebbi Zeira) was cured?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Avahu mean when, at the Se'udah that subsequently took place, he said to Rebbi Zeira 'Lishri lan Mar'?\n(b) Rebbi Zeira objected, based on a statement of Rav Huna. Why did he refer to him as 'Rav Huna ha'Bavli'?\n(c) According to Rav Huna, who recites 'ha'Motzi'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Avahu however, held like Rebbi Yochanan.   According to Rebbi Yochanan in the name of Rebbi Shimon, who is supposed to recite ...\n1. ... 'ha'Motzi'? Why is that?\n2. ... Birchas ha'Mazon? Why is that?\n(b) What is the initial text of the B'rachah that the guest recites on behalf of the Ba'al ha'Bayis?\n(c) To this, Rebbi added three basic requests: 1. Concerning the success of the host's business ventures and the location of both the host and one's own property; 2. That the Satan should have jurisdiction neither over the host nor over oneself.   What is the third request?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav Nachman, Mezuman ends with 'Nevarech (she'Achalnu mi'Shelo').   What does Rebbi Sheishes say?\n(b) We suggest that their Machlokes is equivalent to the Machlokes between two Beraisos. One Beraisa says that Birchas ha'Mazon comprises two and three.   What does the other Beraisa say?\n(c) Assuming that 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv' is not d'Oraysa, how do we initially explain the Tana that says ...\n1. ... 'two and three'?\n2. ... 'three and four'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) We reject that suggestion however, by explaining the Beraisos according to the respective opinions of Rav Nachman and Rav Sheishes. According to Rav Nachman, both Tana'im hold 'until Nevarech'.   How does he then explain the Tana who holds 'two and three' (in connection with laborers)?\n(b) Whereas according to Rav Sheishes, both Tana'im hold 'until ha'Zan'.   How does he then establish the Tana who holds 'three and four' (in connection with 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv')?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rav Yosef prove (from laborers) that ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv is not min ha'Torah?\n(b) How does Rav Yitzchak bar Shmuel bar Marsa in the name of Rav prove it from the format of the B'rachah?\n(c) The source for this is a Beraisa which states that 'All B'rachos begin and end with a Baruch, with three exceptions; Birchas ha'Peiros, Birchas ha'Mitzos' and 'any B'rachah ha'Semuchah la'Chavertah'.   What is the fourth?\n(d) Why ...\n1. ... do the first two exceptions not end with a 'Baruch'?\n2. ... does a B'rachah ha'Semuchah la'Chavertah not begin with a Baruch?\n(e) ... does 'Emes ve'Yatziv' (and 'Emes ve'Munah') not begin with a Baruch?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav now prove from the conclusion of the Beraisa 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv' begins with a Baruch, but does not end with a Baruch' (like a regular B'rachah ha'Semuchah la'Chavertah)?\n(b) How does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak prove the same thing from the text of Birchas ha'Mazon in the house of an Aveil."
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) According to the Tana Kama, the fourth B'rachah of Birchas ha'Mazon in the house of an Aveil is 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv'.   What does Rebbi Akiva say?\n(b) How do we answer the Kashya on the Tana Kama 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv In, Baruch Dayan Emes, Lo?'\n(c) What has Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak proved from the opinion of Rebbi Akiva?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) On what occasion did Mar Zutra Bichas Birchas ha'Aveil ('Keil Emes, Dayan Emes. Shofet be'Tzedek ... ') in 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv'?\n(b) The gist of the B'rachah is that Hash-m rules over us, and that we are subservient to Him and that He does as He sees fit, because all His ways are just, and we are forever obligated to thank and to bless Him.   How did he end the B'rachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav Z'vid in the name of Abaye, when the third person who continued eating after answering Mezuman finishes his meal, he must recite Birchas ha'Mazon from the beginning.   What do the Rabbanan say?\n(b) Like whom is the Halachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) What did the Resh Galusa comment to Rav Sheishes concerning the Persians (in spite of acknowledging that he [Rav Sheishes] and his colleagues were sages)?\n(b) If, when two people were eating together, the senior participant would seat himself first and the other person, above him, what did they do when there were three?\n(c) What objection did Rav Sheishes raise to ...\n1. ... that?\n2. ... to the Persian Minhag that the senior person washed Netilas Yadayim first before eating?\n(d) How did the Resh Galusa counter Rav Sheishes' ...\n1. ... first objection?\n2. ... second objection?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What objection did Rav Sheishes raise to the Persian Minhag that the senior person washed Mayim Achronim last?\n(b) And how did the Resh Galusa counter that?\n(c) How did Rav Sheishes refute all these Persian customs in one fell swoop?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) According to the Beraisa, how do they sit when there are ...\n1. ... two people eating?\n2. ... three people eating?\n(b) Why does the second one not sit below and the third one above  (to enable him [the senior participant] to speak with him without having to turn round)?\n(c) Who is the first to wash ...\n1. ... Netilas Yadayim?\n2. ... Mayim Achronim, if there are five people?\n(d) What is the procedure regarding Mayim Achronim in the event that there are more than five participants?\n(e) What does the Tana then say about the first of the five last people to wash Mayim Achronim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) The previous ruling supports a statement of Rav.   What did Rav Chiya bar Ashi say in the name of Rav concerning the first person of the last group to wash Mayim Achronim?\n(b) What did Rebbi once say to Rav when he and his uncle Rebbi Chiya were sitting with him, after they had just eaten?\n(c) How did Rav react to that?\n(d) What did Rebbi Chiya tell him?\n(e) Why did Rebbi Chiya refer to him as 'bar Pachsi'? What does this mean?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 47,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Beraisa say about giving deference to a senior when travelling or when crossing a bridge?\n(b) On which other occasion does he issue the same ruling?\n(c) What happened once when Ravin and Abaye were travelling together on their donkeys?\n(d) What did Abaye comment ...\n1. ... at that point?\n2. ... when they arrived at the entrance to a Shul, and Ravin honored Abaye with entering first?\n(e) Why, in his first statement, did Abaye refer to Ravin's having come from Eretz Yisrael?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What did Ravin (quoting Rebbi Yochanan) reply?\n(b) How do we reconcile that statement with the fact that Ravin himself gave deference to Abaye whey they entered a Shul, which does not require a Mezuzah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Yehudah the son of Rav Shmuel bar Shilas say about eating before the one who has recited the B'rachah?\n(b) Rav Safra amended the wording to 'taste' (instead of 'eat').   Seeing as it has no direct Halachic ramifications, why did he do that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Beraisa say about ...\n1. ... two people waiting for each other 'by the serving-dish?\n2. ... if they are three?\n3. ... eating before the person who recites Birchas ha'Motzi (the ha'Botze'a)?\n(b) What does 'ha'Botze'a' really mean?\n(c) On what condition is the Mevarech permitted to allow somebody else to eat before him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) On which occasion did Rabah bar bar Chanah arrive early at the Se'udah and proceed to teach his son a Din in 'Betzi'as ha'Pas'?\n(b) Why did he see fit to do so specifically then?\n(c) Which pertinent Halachah did he therefore teach him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) How did Rav Chisda slightly amend that ruling?\n(b) On what grounds did Rami bar Chama query his amendment?\n(c) What did Rav Chisda answer"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa prohibits answering an Amen Chatufah, Ketufah or Yesomah.   What is an 'Amen ...\n1. ... Chatufah'?\n2. ... Ketufah'?\n3. ... 'Yesomah'?\n(b) How do we reconcile this with the men in the big Shul in Alexandria, who could not hear the Chazan and who answered 'Amen' when they saw flags being waved?\n(c) What else does the Tana say one should not do when reciting a B'rachah?\n(d) What does ben Azai say about a person who recites an Amen ...\n1. ... Yesomah?\n2. ... Chatufah\"\n3. ... Ketufah?\n(e) And what does he say about a person who recites a 'long B'rachah'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Shimi bar Ashi once do when he came and found Rav and Shmuel at the tail-end of a Se'udah?\n(b) What comment did Rav make at Rav Shimi bar Ashi's attempt to join them for Mezuman?\n(c) How did Shmuel counter Rav's objection?\n(d) Why did he say 'Mushrooms for me and chicks for Rav'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) What did the Talmidim of Rav declare when Rav Acha arrived whilst they were in the middle of a Se'udah?\n(b) What did he respond to that?\n(c) What is the Halachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What objection do we raise to the Mishnah's ruling permitting someone who has eaten D'mai to participate in Mezuman?\n(b) Based on which principle should it be forbidden?\n(c) The source for this prohibition is the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Botze'a Barech Ni'etz Hash-m\".   What dos this mean?\n(d) Based on this Pasuk, what does Mar say in the first Perek of Sanhedrin about a person who steals a Sa'ah of wheat, then grinds and bakes it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) How do we refute the objection, based on the Mishnah in D'mai?\n(b) Who, besides poor people, does the Tana there permit one to feed D'mai?\n(c) Why is this permitted?\n(d) On what grounds were the Chachamim so lenient regarding D'mai?\n(e) In the supporting Beraisa cited by Rav Huna, Beis Shamai forbid feeding the poor and the visiting troops D'mai.   What do Beis Hillel say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What problem do we have with the Mishnah's ruling that someone who eats Ma'aser Rishon whose T'rumah has been taken is eligible to participate in Mezuman?\n(b) How do we solve the problem?\n(c) This is based on the ruling of Rebbi Avahu in the name of Resh Lakish.   How did he learn it from the Pasuk in Korach \"va'Haremosem mimenu T'rumas Hash-m, Ma'aser min ha'Ma'aser\"?\n(d) What is the case?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Papa mean when he asked Abaye, why in that case, one is not Patur even he came first to the K'ri?\n(b) Abaye replied by quoting the Pasuk there \"mi'Kol Ma'asroseichem Tarimu\".   To whom is the Pasuk speaking?\n(c) How does this answer Rav Papa's Kashya?\n(d) How did Abaye answer Rav Papa's Kashya how we know to differentiate between before the Miru'ach and after the Miru'ach?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) How do we answer the Kashya 'P'shita' with regard to the Mishnah's ruling that ...\n1. ... someone who eats Ma'aser Sheini and Hekdesh that have been redeemed may participate in Mezuman?\n2. ... a Shamash who ate a k'Zayis may participate?\n(b) What does the former ruling now teach us?\n(c) And what problem do we have with the Mishnah's ruling that a Kuto is permitted to participate?\n(d) Abaye establishes the Mishnah by a Kuti Chaver (a Talmid-Chacham).   How does Rava solve the problem (based on a Beraisa), even assuming that the Mishnah is speaking about a Kuti Am ha'Aretz?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Meir there defines an Am ha'Aretz as someone who does not eat his Chulin be'Taharah.   What do the Chachamim say?\n(b) How does this answer the Kashya? Why is a Kuti now permitted to participate in Mezuman, even though an Am ha'Aretz is not?\n(c) The Kutim are particular about Ma'asering their fruit based on a statement of Mar.   What did Mar say about the Kutim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) We now cite a six-sided Machlokes as to how to define an Am ha'Aretz that the Chachamim often refer to. Of the first four who define him as someone who does not fulfill one specific Mitzvah, Rebbi Eliezer says 'Someone who does not recite the Sh'ma morning and evening'.   What does Rebbi Yehoshua say?\n(b) ben Azai defines him as someone who wears a garment without Tzitzis.   How does Rebbi Nasan define him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rebbi Nasan bar Yosef, define an Am ha'Aretz, in connection with the upbringing of his children?\n(b) Acherim says 'Kara ve'Shanah ve'Lo Shimesh Talmidei-Chachamim, harei Zeh Am ha'Aretz'.   What does he mean by that?\n(c) Like whom does Rav Huna rule?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Menashya bar Tachlifa learned Sifra, Sifri and Halachos.   Why did Rami bar Chama refuse to include him in Mezuman?\n(b) What statement did Rava make about Rami bar Chama's death?\n(c) What problem do we have with Rava's statement?\n(d) How do we resolve the problem? What was Rami bar Chama's mistake?\n(e) What is the alternative answer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) How do we answer the Kashya 'P'shita' regarding the Mishnah's prohibition of including someone who ate Tevel in Mezuman?\n(b) What is the case of Tevel Tavul mi'de'Rabbanan?\n(c) How do we ...\n2. ... resolve the problem?\n(d) On what grounds might we otherwise have thought that one may include him in Mezuman?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) How do we explain the Mishnah's insertion among those who are prohibited from participating in Mezuman of someone who eats Ma'aser Sheini or Hekdesh that have not been redeemed? Why is that too, not obvious?\n(b) What does 'not properly' mean with regard to ...\n1. ... Ma'aser Sheini?\n2. ... Hekdesh?\n(c) What do we learn from the Pasuk in Bechukosai \"ve'Nasan ha'Kesef (not the actual words in the Pasuk) ve'Kam lo\"?\n(d) The last case in the current list is a Shamash who eats less than a k'Zayis, which is obvious.   Then why does the Tana insert it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) How do we answer the Kashya 'P'shita' with regard to the Mishnah's ruling precluding a Nochri from Mezuman, based on a statement of Rebbi Zeira?\n(b) What Rebbi Zeira quoting Rebbi Yochanan say?\n(c) How does he learn this from the fact that Moshe sprinkled the blood of the Korbanos on the people at Har Sinai?\n(d) How is the Kashya 'P'shita' now answered?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yossi say about a baby in his cot?\n(b) We reconcile this with the Mishnah, which precludes Ketanim from participating in Mezuman by citing Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi.   What did Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi say about ...\n1. ... a baby in his cot, despite the fact that he cannot participate in Mezuman?\n2. ... an Eved?\n(c) We query this however, from an incident cited in a Beraisa.   What did Rebbi Eliezer once do when they were short of one person for a Minyan?\n(d) Why does this pose a Kashya on Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) We answer that they were actually two short of a Minyan.   How does that answer the Kashya?\n(b) We query this however, based on a statement of Rav Yehudah.   What did Rav Yehudah say about someone who sets his Eved free?\n(c) Which Asei does he transgress?\n(d) On what basis do we refute the answer that Rebbi Eliezer did it for the sake of a Mitzvah?\n(e) What do we answer? Why was making a Minyan different?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yehoshua be Levi say further about going early to Shul?\n(b) What problem do we have with his next statement that the first ten people in Shul receive the reward of (even) a hundred people who arrive after them?\n(c) How do we therefore amend it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) What problem does Rav Nachman have with Rav Huna's initial statement that nine people plus the Aron make up a Minyan?\n(b) How do we therefore amend it?\n(c) Some say that this refers to where they are standing close to one another.   What do others say?\n(d) What is the basis of their Machlokes?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q26",
        "label": "26)",
        "text": "(a) What problem does Rav Nachman have with Rebbi Ami's initial statement that two plus Shabbos form a Mezuman?\n(b) So how do we amend it?\n(c) Rav Chisda pointed to Rav Sheishes and himself as an example of Rebbi Ami's ruling.   What did Rav Sheishes do?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q27",
        "label": "27)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yochanan permits a Katan Pore'ach to make up a Mezuman.   What is a 'Katan Pore'ach'?\n(b) We cite a Beraisa in support of Rebbi Yochanan.   How does the Tana conclude?\n(c) What problem do we have with that?\n(d) We conclude that the Tana is coming to include a Katan Pore'ach.   How do we then explain 'Ein Medakd'kin be'Katan'?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 48,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) We conclude that the Halachah is not like the current rulings (See Tosfos DH 've'Leis Hilch'sa'), but like a statement of Rav Nachman.   According to Rav Nachman, on what condition can one include a Katan in Mezuman?\n(b) What did little Abaye and Rava answer when Rabah once asked them to whom once recites a B'rachah?\n(c) When Rabah asked them where 'Rachmana' is, Rava pointed to the ceiling.   What did Abaye do?\n(d) What did Rabah subsequently predict?\n(e) Of which popular adage (concerning a pumpkin) is this episode reminiscent?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Yehudah b'rei de'Rav Shmuel bar Shilas say in the name of Rav about nine people who ate bread and one, vegetables, with regard to Mezuman with the Name of Hash-m?\n(b) Rebbi Zeira asked Rav Yehudah whether the same Din will apply if only eight or even seven out of the ten participants ate bread.   What did Rav Yehudah reply?\n(c) What did Rebbi Yirmiyah comment on the fact that Rebbi Zeira did not ask what the Din would be if there were six?\n(d) Then why was Rebbi Zeira sorry that he did not do so?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Who was Yanai ha'Melech?\n(b) Why did he kill all the Chachamim?\n(c) What problem did he subsequently face when he ate a meal with the queen?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) On what condition did the queen volunteer to bring someone who could Bensch for them?\n(b) Whom did she subsequently produce?\n(c) What was her connection to him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What was the king referring to when he pointed out how much Kavod he was giving him?\n(b) How did Shimon ben Shetach respond to that, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Salselehah u'Seromimcha Techabdecha ... \"?\n(c) What did Yanai comment?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What was Shimon ben Shetach's quandary? What B'rachah did he want to avoid reciting?\n(b) So what did he do when they gave him a cup of wine to Bensch?\n(c) What did Rebbi Aba the son of Rebbi Chiya bar Aba mean when he said that Shimon ben Shetach followed his own opinion when he Bensched?\n(d) He based this on a statement of Rebbi Chiya bar Aba Amar.   What did Rebbi Chiya bar Aba Amar Rebbi Yochanan say about Bensching Mezuman that clashed with Shimon ben Shetach?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) How can someone who has eaten a k'Zayis, whose Chiyuv to Bensch is only mi'de'Rabbanan, be Motzi someone who has eaten enough to be satisfied (whose Chiyuv is mi'd'Oraysa)?\n(b) In that case, why can a child who has reached the age of Chinuch not be Motzi grown-ups?\n(c) What is the problem with the B'hag, who, due to the first Kashya, requires the other participants to have also eaten a k'Zayis (or a k'Beitzah, according to others), but not enough to be satisfied?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) And we support Rebbi Aba's statement with a ruling of Raban Shimon ben Gamliel.   What did Raban Shimon ben Gamliel say in a Beraisa about someone who merely dipped his food in brine or who ate only a dried fig?\n(b) What do we extrapolate from there that supports Rebbi Aba's statement?\n(c) What did Rav Chanah bar Yehudah say in the name of Rava that supports what we just said?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav Chana bar Yehudah in the name of Rava say about someone who ate only a leaf of vegetable or who drank a cup of wine?\n(b) And when can he actually Bensch Mezuman?\n(c) Rav Nachman lists the authors of Birchas ha'Mazon.   When did ...\n1. ... Moshe instigate Birchas ha'Zan?\n2. ... Yehoshua, Birchas ha'Aretz?\n(d) Who instigated Boneh Yerushalayim'?\n(e) If David instigated 'al Yisrael Amecha ve'al Yerushalayim Irecha', what did Shlomoh instigate?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Who instigated 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv'?\n(b) Where did they instigate it?\n(c) Based on a statement of Rav Masna, on what occasion did they instigate it?\n(d) If 'ha'Meitiv' commemorates the fact that the corpses were brought to burial (after lying in the open after many years), what does 'ha'ha'Tov' commemorate?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa lists the four B'rachos of Birchas ha'Mazon that we just discussed, to which the Tana Kama adds that we begin with 'Nacheim' and end with 'Nacheim', and mention Kedushas ha'Yom ('Retzei') in the middle.   Why does he refer to the B'rachah of 'Racheim' as 'Nacheim'?\n(b) What does the Tana mean?\n(c) What does Rebbi Eliezer say about the insertion of Retzei?\n(d) The Chachamim basically concur with the opinion of the Tana Kama.   In which point do they argue with him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Beraisa learn from the Pasuk in Eikev ...\n1. ... ve'Achalta ve'Sava'ta ... \" from the word \"u'Veirachta\"?\n2. ... \"es hashem Elokecha\"?\n3. ... \"al ha'Aretz ... \"?\n4. ... \"ha'Tovah\"?\n5. ... \"asher Nasan lach\"?\n(b) What does he learn from the Pasuk in Va'eshanan \"ha'Har ha'Tov ve'ha'Levanon\"?\n(c) And he learns the B'rachah Rishonah from a 'Kal va'Chomer'   Which 'Kal va'Chomer'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) That is the opinion of Rebbi Yishmael. Rebbi Akiva largely agrees with him, only he learns Birchas ha'Zan from \"Uverachta es Hash-m Elokecha\".   What does he learn from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Gadlu la'Hashem iti ... \"?\n(b) What, according to him, is the source of Birchas 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv'?\n(c) And from where does he learn the B'rachah Rishonah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Yitzchak, the last D'rashah is superfluous, because he learns the B'rachah Rishonah from the Pasuk in Mishpatim \"u'Veirach es Lachm'cha ve'es Meimecha\".   How does he 'amend' the word \"u'Veirach\"?\n(b) How does he know that the Pasuk is referring to the B'rachah Rishonah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Nasan considers Rebbi Yitzchak's D'rashah superfluous, because he learns the B'rachah Rishonah from the Pasuk in Shmuel \"ke'Vo'achem es ha'Ir ... ki Hu Yevarech ha'Zevach Acharei-Chein Yochlu ha'Keru'im\".  Who said it to whom about whom?\n(b) Based on the Pasuk in Re'ei \"ve'ha'Basar Tochel\" (from which we learn the Mitzvah of eating the meat of Kodshei Mizbe'ach), which B'rachah did Shmuel recite?\n(c) Some attributed the lengthy response of the women to the fact that women are talkative.   To what does ...\n1. ... Shmuel attribute it (based on the appearance of Shaul)?\n2. ... Rebbi Yochanan attribute it, based on the fact that Shmuel would immediately crown Shaul king?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) From where does Rebbi Yishmael learn the Chiyuv to recite a B'rachah over learning Torah?\n(b) Rebbi Chiya bar Nachmeini citing Rebbi Yishmael maintains that this is not necessary.   Who was Rebbi Chiya bar Nachmeini?\n(c) He learns it from a Gezeirah-Shavah 'Nesinah' 'Nesinah', since it says in Mishpayim \"va'Etnah l'cha es Luchos ha'Even, ve'ha'Torah ve'ha'Mitzvah\".   From which Pasuk in Eikev does he learn it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Meir learn from the Pasuk in Ki Savo \"asher Nasan l'cha Hash-m Elokecha\"?\n(b) According to Rebbi Yehudah ben Beseira, Rebbi Chiya bar Nachmeini's D'rashah is unnecessary.   How does he learn the obligation to recite a B'rachah over learning Torah from the Pasuk \"al ha'ha'Aretz ha'Tovah\" itself?\n(c) What does he learn from the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Ki Lekach Tov Nasati lachem ... \"?\n(d) And what does he learn from the 'Hey' in \"ha'Tovah\"?\n(e) Which Pasuk in Va'eschanan indicates that Yerushalaim is called 'Tov'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Eliezer in a Beraisa, say about someone who does not say \"Eretz Chemdah Tovah u'Rechavah\" in Birchas ha'Aretz?\n(b) What must he likewise omit in Birchas ha'Aretz in order not to be Yotzei?\n(c) Nachum ha'Zakein applies the same ruling to someone who omits 'B'ris' from Birchas ha'Aretz.   What does Rebbi Yossi add to that?\n(d) According to P'limu, what is the significance of the order in which he mentions them?\n(e) On what grounds does he give B'ris precedence over Torah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) Three out of the four possible places (See Maharsha) where the Torah was given with a covenant were Sinai, the Ohel Mo'ed, Har G'rizim.   What is the fourth?\n(b) Whereabouts in the Torah are the thirteen covenants of the B'ris Milah mentioned?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 49,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Aba, whereabouts in Birchas ha'Aretz, is one obligated to insert Hoda'ah?\n(b) How what does he say about someone who does not say it even once?\n(c) And how does the Beraisa describe someone who ...\n1. ... says 'Manchil Aratzos' in Birchas ha'Aretz and ''Moshi'a es Yisrael in 'Boneh Yerushalayim'?\n2. ... fails to say 'B'ris' and 'Torah' in Birchas ha'Aretz and 'Malchus Beis David' in 'Boneh Yerushalayim'?\n(d) This supports a ruling of Rebbi Ila'a.   What did Rebbi Ila'a Amar Rebbi Ya'akov bar Acha in the name of Rabeinu (presumably with reference to either Rebbi or Rav)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Aba Yossi ben Dustai and the Rabbanan argue over the text of 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv. One of them says that it requires 'Malchus'.   What does the other one say?\n(b) What is the basis of their Machlokes?\n(c) If ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv is not Semuchah la'Chavertah, why does it begin with a B'rachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) According to the Tana Kama in a Beraisa, one concludes the third B'rachah of Birchas ha'Mazon with 'Boneh Yerushalayim'.   What problem do we have with Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Yehudah, who says 'Moshi'a Yisrael'?\n(b) What do we answer?\n(c) What is his reason? What has 'Moshi'a Yisrael' got to do with the text of the B'rachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) Rabah bar Rav Huna once ate by the Resh Galusa.   What do we mean when we say that he ...\n1. ... 'began (the B'rachah of Boneh Yerushalayim) with one'?\n2. ... 'concluded with two'?\n(b) Rav Chisda's objection to Rabah bar Rav Huna 'Gevurta 'le'Mechtam be'Tarti?' ('Is it a big deal to conclude with two things?') was based on a brief statement of Rebbi.   What did Rebbi, in a Beraisa, say?\n(c) Why is it wrong to do so?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi reply when Levi queried him from the conclusion of the B'rachah ...\n1. ... 'al ha'Aretz ve'al ha'Mazon'?\n2. ... 'al ha'Aretz ve'al ha'Peiros'?\n3. ... 'Mekadesh Yisrael ve'ha'Zemanim'?\n4. ... 'Mekadesh Yisrael ve'Roshei Chodashim'?\n5. ... 'Mekadesh ha'Shabbos ve'Yisrael ve'ha'Zemanim'\n(b) Why did Rebbi not give the same answer here as he gave in the previous cases?\n(c) How did Rebbi reconcile this dual B'rachah with his principle?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Sheishes maintains that someone who begins Birchas ha'Aretz with 'Rachem Hash-m ... al Amcha Yisrael' concludes 'Moshi'a Yisrael'.   How does he conclude if he begins 'Rachem al Yerushalayim'?\n(b) What does Rav Nachman say?\n(c) He bases his opinion on a Pasuk.   Which Pasuk in Tehilim equates the salvation of Yisrael with the building of Yerushalayim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Chisda reply when Rebbi Zeira asked to sit and learn together?\n(b) In reply to Rebbi Zeira's query, he described what happened once when he was one honored with the Bensching by the Resh Galusa.   How did Rav Sheishes react to his text of Birchas ha'Mazon?\n(c) Which three things did Rav Chisda omit that upset Rav Sheishes?\n(d) Rav Chisda excused himself by citing of Rav Chananel Amar Rav.   What did Rav Chananel Amar Rav say about someone who omits B'ris, Torah and Malchus?\n(e) What was Rav Zeira's final comment?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) What is Rabah bar bar Chanah coming to teach us when he says that 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv' requires 'Malchus'?\n(b) What problem do we have with this answer?\n(c) Rebbi Zeira answers that Rabah bar bar Chanah is coming to add a second Malchus (apart from 'Melech ha'Plam').   Where do we insert it?\n(d) What is the significance of the extra 'Malchus'?\n(e) We query this in that, if so, we ought to add a third 'Malchus' in 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv'. Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) To counter the previous argument, how do we explain the fact that Birchas ha'Aretz and 'Boheh Yerushalayim' do not contain 'Malchus'?\n(b) Then how do we justify Rabah bar bar Chanah Amar Rebbi Yochanan? Why did they need to supplement the missing 'Malchus' of 'Boneh Yerushalayim' in 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv'?\n(c) How does Rav Papa deal with the Kashya that 'Malchus' is omitted from Birchas ha'Aretz, too?\n(d) Where do we add the second (third) 'Malchus'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Who was sitting behind Rav Gidal, when he once sat in front of Rav Huna and made the following statement?\n(b) 'Someone who forgot 'Retzei' on Shabbos says 'Baruch ... she'Nasan Shabbasos li'Menuchah le'Amo Yisrael be'Ahavah, le'Os ve'li'B'eris'.   How does one conclude?\n(c) What did Rav Gidal asked reply when Rav Zeira asked him who said it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) On two other occasions, when Rav Gidal asked Rav Huna the same She'eilah regarding Yom Tov and Rosh Chodesh, he gave the same answer, replacing 'Shabbasos' and 'be'Ahavah' with 'Yamim Tovim' and 'le'Simchah u'le'Zikaron' by the one and with 'Roshei Chodashim' and 'le'Zikaron' by the other.   How did he conclude the B'rachah on Yom Tov?\n(b) In the B'rachah on Rosh Chodesh, what was Rav Gidal not sure about concerning ...\n1. ... the middle of the B'rachah? Over which word was he in a dilemma?\n2. ... the conclusion of the B'rachah?\n3. ... the source of the ruling?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Nachman once do in the presence of Rav Gidal bar Minyumi, when he once erred and forgot 'Retzei' on Shabbos?\n(b) Rav Nachman answered Rav Gidal's query from Rav's previous ruling by citing Rav Shiloh Amar Rav.   What did he say about someone who forgot 'Retzei' on Shabbos?\n(c) Rav Nachman reconciled that with Rav Shiloh Amar Rav's ruling by citing a ruling of Rav Menashya bar Tachlifa Amar Rav.   What did he say to qualify Rav Shiloh's ... ruling?\n(d) On what grounds does this Din differ from that of the Amidah, where one only needs to start again if one already took the three steps backwards?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What distinction does Rav Idi bar Avin Amar Rav Amram Amar Rav Nachman Amar Shmuel draw between someone who forgot 'Ya'aleh va'Yavo' on Rosh Chodesh in Tefilah and someone who forgot it in Bensching?\n(b) What did Rav Amram reply when Rav Idi asked him for the reason for the difference?\n(c) Rav Nachman in turn, told them that Shmuel had not explained the reason.   What did he therefore figure out by himself?\n(d) What prompted Rav Amram to ask him whether, in that case, if the same thing happened on Shabbos or Yom Tov, one is Chayav to repeat Bensching?\n(e) What did Rav Nachman, once again citing Rav Shiloh Amar Rav, reply?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) How do we reconcile what we just said in the name of Rav with Rav Huna Amar Rav, who said that someone who forgot 'Retzei' on Shabbos or 'Ya'aleh ve'Yavo' on Yom-Tov says 'Baruch she'Nasan' (as we learned earlier)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) We learned in our Mishnah that Rebbi Meir requires one to Bensch after a k'Zayis, and Rebbi Yehudah, after a k'Beitzah. We query this from the Mishnah in Pesachim, which discusses someone who leaves Yerushalayim and realizes that he has with him Basar Kodesh.   At which point does he burn it there where he is?\n(b) What must he do if he has not yet passed Tzofim?\n(c) Where does he then burn it? What does he burn it with?\n(d) According to Rebbi Meir, he is only obligated to return for a k'Beitzah.   What does Rebbi Yehudah say?\n(e) How does this pose a Kashya on our Mishnah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) What simple answer does Rav Nachman give to answer the Kashya?\n(b) Abaye answers it without switching the opinions.   How does he then explain the basis of their Machlokes ...\n1. ... here (by Bensching)?\n2. ... there (by Kodshim)?\n(c) What does Rebbi Meir learn from the word ...\n1. ... \"ve'Achalta\" (in the Pasuk in Eikev ve'Sava'ta u'Verachta ... \")?\n2. ... \"ve'Sava'ta\"?\n(d) How does Rebbi Yehudah explain the words \"ve'Achalta ve'Sava'ta\"?\n(e) Regarding Kodshim, Rebbi Meir compares the Shi'ur for which one needs to return to that of Tum'ah, which is a k'Zayis.   To what does Rebbi Yehudah compare it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What distinction does the Mishnah draw between a Mezuman comprising just three people, or ten, a hundred, a thousand or even ten thousand on the one hand, and one comprising three, ten a hundred, a thousand or ten thousand besides the Mevarech, on the other?\n(b) If one adds 'Elokeinu' when there are ten people, what does one add when there are ...\n1. ... a hundred?\n2. ... a thousand?\n3. ... ten thousand?\n(c) If this is the opinion of Rebbi Yossi ha'Gelili, how does he learn it from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"be'Makheilos Borchu Hash-m. Hash-m mi'Mekor Yisrael\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Akiva say about the number of people participating in Mezuman?\n(b) From where does he learn it?\n(c) According to Rebbi Akiva, one says in Shul 'Borchu es Hashem'.   What does Rebbi Yishmael say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) What did Shmuel say about taking oneself apart from the community?\n(b) How do we query himfrom our Mishnah, regarding where there are three or ten ... besides the Mevarech?\n(c) What do we answer?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 50,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) We prove that the Mishnah means 'Af Borchu' from Rav Ada bar Ahavah Amri bei Rav, who discusses the Din where six or nine people ate together.   What does he say about that?\n(b) How does this prove the point?\n(c) And we support this with a Beraisa, which states initially that it makes no difference whether one says 'Nevarech' or 'Borchu'.   The Nakdanim however, disagreed.   Who are the 'Nakdanim'?\n(d) What did they do?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What, according to the Tana, can one tell from the way one recites a B'rachah?\n(b) An example of this, says Rebbi, is whether he says 'u've'Tuvo Chayinu' or 'u'mi'Tuvo Chayinu' (whom he refers to as a Bur [an uncultivated person]).   What is wrong with saying 'u'mi'Tuvo Chayinu'?\n(c) How did Rav Dimi answer Abaye's query from the Pasuk in Shmuel (when David ha'Melech said to Hash-m) \"u'mi'Birchascha Yevorach Beis Avd'cha Le'olam\"?\n(d) And how did he answer Abaye's next Kashya from the Pasuk in Tehilim (which is also a request) \"Harchev Picha va'Amal'eihu\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) On what grounds does Rebbi also call a Bur someone who says 'u've'Tuvo Chayim' and not 'u've'Tuvo Chayinu'?\n(b) Why do the Neherbela'i then say the reverse? Why is 'Chayim' better than 'Chayinu'?\n(c) Like whom is the Halachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) On what grounds did Rebbi Yochanan add someone who says 'le'Mi she'Achalnu mi'Shelo' (instead of 'she'Achalnu mi'Shelo') to the list of Burim?\n(b) What did Rav Ashi answer, when Rav Acha b'rei de'Rava queried him from (what we say at the Seider) 'le'Mi she'Asah la'Avoseinu ve'Lanu es Kol ha'Nisim ha'Eilu'?\n(c) Rebbi Yochanan adds that someone who says 'she'Achalnu mi'Shelo' is a Talmid-Chacham, but a Bur if he says 'al ha'Mazon she'Achalnu'.   Why is that?\n(d) How does Rav Huna b'rei de'Rav Yehoshua qualify Rebbi Yochanan's statement?\n(e) How does he prove it from the conclusion of the Mishnah's statement \"ke'Inyan she'Hu Mevarech, kach Mevorchin acharav 'Baruch Hash-m Elokei Yisrael ... '.   How do the participants conclude?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What problem do we have with the Mishnah? What does the Tana say after 'Echad Asarah, ve'Echad Asarah Ribu ... ' that contradicts it?\n(b) Rav Yosef establishes the first statement like Rebbi Yossi ha'Gelili, and the second, like Rebbi Akiva, who compares Bensching to Tefilah.   From which Pasuk in Tehilim does Rebbi Yossi ha'Gelili learn to differentiate between different size groups?\n(c) Rebbi Akiva explains the Pasuk in Tehilim like Rebbi Meir.   What did Rebbi Meir say with regard to the Shirah by the Yam-Suf, based on that Pasuk?\n(d) From where did Rebbi Yossi ha'Gelili learn that?\n(e) Like whom does Rava Pasken?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Chama bar Buzi search for, when he and Ravina once ate by the Resh Galusa?\n(b) What did Ravina comment?\n(c) Rava recalled how, when they used to eat by the Resh Galusa, who spent a long time at table, they used to Bensch Mezuman in groups of three. Why did they not ...\n1. ... rather divide into groups of ten?\n2. ... wait until the Resh Galusa Bensched and Bensch together with him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rabah Tosfa'ah say about three people who ate together and one of Bensched on his own, assuming ...\n1. ... he Bensched Mezuman?\n2. ... he Bensched without Mezuman, and subsequently wants to be Yotzei with their Mezuman?\n(b) What is the reason for the latter ruling?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rafram bar Papa once say when he was called up to the Torah in the Shul of Abei Givar that caused a stir?\n(b) What did everybody shout out?\n(c) What did Rava say to him (besides asking him why he gets involved in a Machlokes by not doing like Rebbi Yishmael)?\n(d) He reffered to him as Pasya Uchma.   What does 'Pasya Uchma' mean?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) The Mishnah discusses a group of people who ate together and who want to Bensch Mezuman separately.   How many people must eat together in order to be permitted to divide into ...\n1. ... two groups for Mezuman?\n2. ... three groups?\n(b) What if four or five people ate together?\n(c) If more than six people ate together, how many must there be to be obligated to Bensch together?\n(d) Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Tana say about twenty people who ate together?\n(b) On what condition does he permit two groups who ate separately in the same room to combine for Mezuman?\n(c) According to Rebbi Eliezer, one can only recite a B'rachah over wine after one has added water to it.   What do the Chachamim say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) In spite of having already taught us that three people who ate together are Chayav Zimun, the Tana nevertheless repeats it, based on a statement of Rebbi Aba.   What did Rebbi Aba Amar Shmuel say about three people who sit down to eat but have not yet begun eating?\n(b) Alternatively, he is coming to teach us the Din of Rav Huna.   What did Rav Huna Amar Rav say about three people who left the three groups with whom they were eating and combined to eat together?\n(c) How does Rav Chisda qualify Rav Huna's statement? How many people must there have been in each of the three original groups?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What if, in the current case, after the three men combined, they did not eat anything together?\n(b) On what condition did Rava say that the three men are not permitted to Bensch Mezuman together?\n(c) How can the groups have completed Mezuman without them?\n(d) How can the three men then have been Yotzei if they were not there when they Bensched Mezuman?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) Rava's source is the Mishnah in Keilim which discusses half a bed that has been stolen, lost or that brothers or partners had divided between them.  What does the Tana say ...\n1. ... about the Din of Tum'ah?\n2. ... in a case where the half-bed is returned or found?\n(b) What does Rava extrapolate from the words 'mi'Ka'an u'le'Haba'?\n(c) What does that have to do with his current ruling concerning Mezuman?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) How does the Beraisa qualify the ruling in our Mishnah concerning two groups who cannot see each other not combining for Mezuman?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) One of the two rulings cited by Rebbi Eliezer in the Beraisa (in connection with undiluted wine) is that one does not recite 'Borei P'ri ha'Gafen' over it.   What B'rachah does one then recite over it?\n(b) What is the second ruling (in connection with Netilas Yadayim)?\n(c) What is Rebbi Eliezer's reason for ...\n1. ... the first ruling?\n2. ... the second ruling?\n(d) According to the Chachamim, either way, one recites 'Borei P'ri ha'Gafen'.   What do they say about Netilas Yadayim?\n(e) What is their reason?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) What does Shmuel say about using bread for one's own personal needs?\n(b) On what grounds do we establish Shmuel like Rebbi Eliezer?\n(c) Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina maintains that when it comes to the Kos shel B'rachah (for Benching), the Chachamim concede to Rebbi Eliezer that one cannot Bench over wine unless one has added water to it.   What reason does Rav Oshaya ascribe to this ruling?\n(d) If undiluted wine was not drinkable under any circumstances, the Chachamim would not require \"Borei P'ri ha'Gafen'.   What does Rebbi Zeira say it is fit for?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) The first of the four things that the Tana lists concerning bread is that one does not place raw meat on it.   What may one not pass over it?\n(b) The third thing is a prohibition against throwing it.   What is the fourth?"
