  {
    "daf": 51,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) They asked Rav Chisda, whether someone who ate or drank without reciting a B'rachah (Rishonah), should continue eating, or whether he should perhaps make a B'rachah in the middle of the meal.   What did Rav Chisda comment on this She'eilah?\n(b) What did Ravina add to Rav Chisda's ruling regarding reciting the B'rachah after the meal?\n(c) And he based this ruling on a Beraisa.   What does the Tana say about a Ba'al-Keri reciting a B'rachah over the Tevilah?\n(d) On what grounds do we reject Ravina's proof?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) We learned in a Beraisa that 'Aspargus' that is drunk regularly is good for the eyes and the heart, and certainly, for the intestines.   What is 'Aspargus'?\n(b) How do we know that the Tana is referring to wine-Aspargus?\n(c) When is Aspargus bad for the entire body?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Another Beraisa states that Aspargus is good for 'L'A'T' but bad for 'R'M'aT'. If the 'Lamed' and the 'Alef' of 'L'A'T' stand for Leiv and Ayin, what does the 'Tav' stand for?\n(b) And if the 'Reish' and the 'Mem' of 'R'M'aT' stand for Rosh and 'Me'ayim', what does the 'Tav' stand for?\n(c) What problem do we now have with the earlier Beraisa?\n(d) To resolve the discrepancy, how do we establish the earlier Beraisa, based on a Mishnah in Nedarim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) The Mishnah in Nedarim discusses someone who declares a Neder on wine.   What reason did he give for doing so?\n(b) What was his reaction when they informed him that smoked wine is good for the intestines?\n(c) What does the Tana there conclude?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) How many specifications does the Beraisa list regarding Aspargus?\n(b) The first of these are 'Chai' and 'Malei' (that the cup should be full).   What does 'Chai' mean?\n(c) If one receives the cup that one is handed with the right hand, with which hand does one hold it whilst drinking it?\n(d) What should one not do ...\n1. ... after drinking it?\n2. ... whilst drinking it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Beraisa say about returning the cup after having drunk the Aspargus?\n(b) What should one do after drinking it?\n(c) What does the Tana mean when he conclused 've'ein Somchin oso Ela be'Miyno'?\n(d) To reconcile this Beraisa with the Beraisa 'Ein Somchin oso Ela be'Pas', we establish the latter by Aspargus made from wine.  Then what is the former Beraisa talking about?\n(e) How will we then interpret 'be'Miyno'? Which three kinds of beer are there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) How do we reconcile the Beraisa that we learned earlier 'le'L'A'T' Yafeh, li'R'M'aT' Ra', with the Beraisa which inverts the two lists (li'R'M'aT Yafeh, le' L'A'T' Ra')?\n(b) Which is which?\n(c) And how do we reconcile the above Beraisa, which says that one should spit after drinking it (not to doso is life-threatening), with the Beraisa which states that to do so is life-threatening?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yishmael ben Elisha cites three things that Suriel taught him.   Who was ...\n1. ... Rebbi Yishmael ben Elisha?\n2. ... Suri'el?\n(b) What did he teach him with regard to ...\n1. ... getting dressed in the morning?\n2. ... washing 'Neigel-Vasser'?\n3. ... a cup of Aspargus after having drunk its contents?\n(c) Some say that the reason for these things is because of Tachs'fis (a group of demons); others, because of Istalgis.   What is 'Istalgis'?\n(d) What do these groups eagerly declare?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) The Angel of Death taught Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi three things, two of them corresponded to two of the same things that Suri'el taught Rebbi Yishmael ben Elisha (not to take one's clothes from the valet and not to allow him to wash his hands for Neigel-Vaser).   What was the third?\n(b) What is the reason for it?\n(c) Someone who did should jump four Amos from his place, leaving him with three options; two of them are to cross a river, or to change to another route.   What is the third?\n(d) If all this is not possible, which Pasuk (in Zecharyah) should he turn round and recite?\n(e) How many times should he repeat it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Zeira Amar Rebbi Avahu (or a Beraisa) now discusses Kos shel B'rachah.   What is the 'Kos shel B'rachah (See Hagahos ve'Tziyunim)'?\n(b) How many things does it require?\n(c) The first four are Hadachah, Sh'tifah' Chai and Malei.  What are 'Chai' and 'Malei' (which we have already discussed)?\n(d) To reconcile 'Chai' with the Mishnah, which rules that one does not recite a B'rachah over undiluted wine, we explain that after pouring the undiluted wine into the cup, one adds water.  How else might we resolve the discrepancy?\n(e) How does the Beraisa define ...\n1. ... 'Hadachah'?\n2. ... 'Sh'tifah'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) Besides Itur and Ituf, which will be discussed shortly, the Kos shel B'rachah must also be taken with both hands.   Where does one then place it?\n(b) How high from the table should it be held?\n(c) Where should one look whilst reciting Birchas ha'Mazon?\n(d) What eleventh thing does Yesh Omrim add?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yochanan brings it down to four.   Which four?\n(b) What did he also say about anyone who recites a B'rachah over a full cup of wine, based on the Pasuk in ve'Zos ha'Berachah \"u'Malei Birchas Hash-m Yam ve'Darom Yerachah\"?\n(c) According to Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina, he will inherit two worlds (as hinted in the Pasuk [See Tosfos DH 'Zocheh ... ').   Which worlds?\n(d) To fulfill 'Itur', Rav Yehudah would surround the Kos with Talmidim.   With what did Rav Chisda surround it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav Sheishes, at which point does one add water to the Kos shel B'rachah?\n(b) In order to fulfill 'Ituf', Rav Papa would wrap himself in his Talis before taking the Kos shel B'rachah.   What did Rav Asi used to do?\n(c) Still in connection with the Kos shel B'rachah, what does Rebbi Chin'na bar Papa learn from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Se'u Yedeichem Kodesh u'Varchu es Hash-m\"?\n(d) What did the 'Rishonim' cited by Rebbi Chiya bar Aba Amar Rebbi Yochanan ask with regard to the requirement of holding the Kos shel B'rachah in one's right hand?\n(e) What did Rav Ashi Pasken, bearing in mind that the Rishonim posed a She'eilah which went unanswered?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) Which Pasuk in Tehilim did Rav Acha bar Chanina cite as the source for raising the Kos shel B'rachah (a Tefach)?\n(b) What reason do we give for the obligation of looking at the Kos whilst reciting Birchas ha'Mazon?\n(c) Why should one send the Kos shel B'rachah to one's wife?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) When Ula, who was a guest of Rav Nachman recited Birchas ha'Mazon after the meal, sent the Kos shel B'rachah to his host, the latter requested that he also send some of it to Yalsa.   Who was Yalsa?\n(b) Ula responded by citing Rebbi Yochanan.   What did Rebbi Yochanan say based on the Pasuk in Eikev \"u'Veirach P'ri Bitn'*cha*\"?\n(c) What did Rebbi Nasan in a Beraisa say about this?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) How did Yalsa react when she heard about their conversation?\n(b) How did they attempt to pacify her?\n(c) She replied 'mi'Mahaduri Mili (people who have nothing to do talk a lot) u'mi'Martuti Kalmi'.   What does 'u'mi'Martuti Kalmi' mean?\n(d) What did she mean by that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav Asi mean when he says 'Ein Masichin Al Kos shel B'rachah'?\n(b) And what does he learn from the Pasuk in Amos \"Hikon Likras Elokecha Yisrael\" (regarding the B'rachah over the two cups of wine)?\n(c) How does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak interpret a cup of punishment?\n(d) What does the Beraisa say about this?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Avahu (or a Beraisa), how one is supposed to Bench if he ate whilst ...\n1. ... walking?\n2. ... standing?\n3. ... leaning?\n(b) What is the Halachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) The first of the differences cited by the Mishnah regarding the differences between Beis Shamai and Beis Hillel is that according to Beis Shamai, Kidush precedes the B'rachah over the wine for two reasons; one of them, because it is the day that causes the wine to be brought.   What is the other one?\n(b) Beis Hillel too, give two reasons as to why the B'rachah over the wine comes first; one of them, because were it not for the wine, there would be no Kidush.   What is the other one?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) Which kind of Ner and Besamim may one not use for Havdalah, besides those of Avodah-Zarah and of Meisim?\n(b) On what condition is one permitted to recite a B'rachah over Ner?\n(c) What do Beis Shamai say in the event that after forgetting to Bench, one changed one's location?\n(d) What do Beis Hillel say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) Up to when is one permitted to still Bench?\n(b) According to Beis Shamai, if a cup ofwine arrives at the end of the meal and it is the only one available, one first recites a B'rachah over the wine and then Birchas ha'Mazon.   What do Beis Hillel say?\n(c) What does the Tana mean when he states that one answers 'Amen' to the B'rachah of a Yisrael? What is the Chidush?\n(d) Then why is one not similarly permitted) to answer 'Amen' to the B'rachah of a Kuti?"
      }
    ]
