  {
    "daf": 52,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What problem do we have with the Beraisa which rules like Beis Hillel with regard to the correct order of the B'rachos over wine and Kidush?\n(b) One answer is that the Beraisa preceded the Bas-Kol.   What is the other one?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) We query Beis Shamai (who gives precedence to Kidush over wine) from a Beraisa, which discusses the order of B'rachos regarding a person who arrives home from Shul on Motza'ei Shabbos ('Yayin, Ma'or, Besamim, Havdalah').  What if he does not have any spare wine for Kos shel B'rachah after eating?\n(b) What is now the problem?\n(c) The juxtaposition of which two B'rachos teaches us that the author of the Beraisa is Beis Shamai?\n(d) And who is the Tana who presents the Machlokes Beis Shamai and Beis Hillel in connection with Ner and Besamim?\n(e) What did Rebbi Yehudah say about Mazon and Havdalah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) We suggest that the author of the Beraisa is Beis Shamai according to Rebbi Meir (who is the author of their Machlokes in our Mishnah).   What did Rebbi Meir say in this regard?\n(b) How do we refute this suggestion, based on the positioning of Mazon in our Mishnah?\n(c) To resolve the discrepancy, what distinction do we draw between bringing Shabbos in and accompanying Shabbos out?\n(d) Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) We now query Beis Shamai from a Beraisa which states that if wine arrived only at the end of the meal, one recites a B'rachah over it and then Benches.   What do we now ask on Beis Shamai, assuming that 'recites a B'rachah over it' means that he then drank it?\n(b) What objection do we raise to the answer that ...\n1. ... after reciting the B'rachah he Benched with it, and drank it only afterwards.\n2. ... he drank from it and Benched over the rest of the Kos?\n3. ... he drank from the wine that he poured into his hands?\n4. ... the cup initially contained a little more than the Shi'ur?\n(c) How do refute the final objection?\n(d) We reinstate the Kashya however, by citing a Beraisa learned by Rebbi Chiya.   What does the Tana, quoting Beis Shamai, rule in the current case, where one recites a B'rachah over the wine and then Benches?\n(e) So how do we finally resolve the discrepancy in Beis Shamai?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) According to Beis Shamai in our Mishnah, one first washes one's hands and then pours out the Kos.   What exactly are they referring to?\n(b) What procedure are they now following?\n(c) What reason does the Beraisa give for Beis Shamai's ruling? What are they afraid would happen if one were to pour out the wine first?\n(d) Why are they then not afraid that his hands will render the Kos Tamei anyway?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) According to Beis Hillel, one first pours out the wine. What are they afraid would happen if one were to wash one hands first?\n(b) Why are they then not afraid that the Kos will render his hands Tamei anyway?\n(c) Based on a Mishnah in Keilim, how do we establish the case, to explain why the Kos is not Metamei the wine that it contains?\n(d) What degree of Tum'ah generally pertains to liquids?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Mishnah there say about a receptacle whose outside became Tamei via Tamei liquids, vis-a-vis ...\n1. ... the inside?\n2. ... its rim, its various handles?\n(b) And what if the Tamei liquid rendered the inside Tamei?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Beis Shamai and Beis Hillel argue over whether one is permitted to use a K'li whose back became Tamei via liquid (Beis Hillel) or not (Beis Shamai), due to a decree.   Which decree?\n(b) On what basis do Beis Hillel not hold of the decree (which explains why they are afraid of the Kos being Metamei the liquid on his hands)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Following their previous reason, Beis Hillel in our Mishnah add a second reason 'Teikef li'Netilas Yadayim, Se'udah'.   What do they mean by that?\n(b) What are they actually saying to Beis Shamai?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) According to Beis Shamai in our Mishnah, one wipes one's hands on the designated cloth which one then places on the table.   What are they afraid might happen if one were to place it on the cushion on which one is leaning?\n(b) Why are they not afraid that the cushion will be Metamei ...\n1. ... the cloth?\n2. ... the person himself?\n(c) According to Beis Hillel, after drying one's hands, one places the cloth on the cushion.   What are they afraid might happen if one were to place it on the table?\n(d) How do we establish the status of the table to explain why the table does not render the food Tamei?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) What is the basis of the Machlokes between Beis Shamai and Beis Hillel in this case?\n(b) What is Beis Shamai's reason?\n(c) On what grounds do Beis Hillel disagree with this decree?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What second reason do Beis Hillel in our Mishnah add to explain why we are more concerned about the food becoming Tamei than the hands? a second 'Ein Netilas Yadayim le'Chulin min ha'Torah'.\n(b) What are they actually saying to Beis Shamai?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) According to Beis Shamai in our Mishnah, one first sweeps and then washes Mayim Acharonim.   Why is that?\n(b) Why are Beis Hillel not worried about that?\n(c) What Halachah do we learn from Beis Hillel's opinion?\n(d) What is the basis of their Machlokes?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina Amar Rav Huna say about all the cases in the Perek except for the current one?\n(b) How can Rebbi Oshaya agree with Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina's ruling on the one hand, yet he Paskens like Beis Hillel in the entire Perek, including this case?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) According to Beis Shamai in our Mishnah, the order of priorities is 'Ner, Mazon, Besamim, Havdalah'.   What is the order of priorities according to Beis Hillel?\n(b) What did Rav Huna bar Yehudah, a guest of Rava, see his host do that surprised him?\n(c) In reply, Rava pointed out that this was the opinion of Rebbi Meir in a Beraisa. Who is Rebbi Meir's disputant there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yehudah in the Beraisa say about 'Mazon' and Havdalah'?\n(b) And what does he say about 'Ner' and 'Besamim' according to ...\n1. ... Beis Shamai?\n2. ... according to Beis Hillel?\n(c) What did Rebbi Yochanan comment on this double Machlokes?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) According to Beis Shamai in our Mishnah, the correct wording for the B'rachah over fire is 'she'Bara Ma'or ha'Eish'.   What do Beis Hillel say?\n(b) Both opinions agree that 'Bara' implies the past.   Over which past event do we recite the B'rachah of Ner during Havdalah?\n(c) Why do we light it specifically on Motza'ei Shabbos?\n(d) How does Rabah then explain the Machlokes?\n(e) Why, according to Beis Shamai, can one not then say 'Borei Me'orei ha'Eish'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rav Yosef query Rabah from the Pesukim \"Yotzer Or u'Vorei Choshech\", \"Yotzer Harim  u'Borei Ru'ach\" and \"Borei Shamayim ve'Noteihem\"?\n(b) Rav Yosef therefore concludes that they do not argue over \"Bara\" and \"Borei\", both of which can refer to the past (See Tosfos DH 'be'Bara').   What then, is the Machlokes?\n(c) He explains the source of their Machlokes as - whether the fact is that there is only one flame (Beis Shamai), or whether, when all's said and done, a flame comprises a number of colors."
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) We ask why the Ner belonging to an Akum is not eligible to be used for Havdalah. The Besamim of a Nochri does not present a problem - because the reason there is obvious (i.e. since the light did not reat on Shabbos, as we will explain shortly)\n(b) Rav Yehudah Amar Rav establishes the Mishnah by a group of Nochrim who have gathered to party - and when Nochrim party it is generally connected with idolatry.\n(c) The problem with this answer is - that we know this already from the Seifa, which disqualifies a Ner of Avodah-Zarah.\n(d) To which Rebbi Chanina from Sura answers - that the Seifa Ner u'Besamim shel Avodah-Zarah) is actually coming to explain why it is Pasul in the Reisha (by Ner u'Besamim shel Akum)."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 53,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What distinction does the Beraisa draw between a Ner she'Shavas (which literally means a lamp that rested) and one that did not?\n(b) We refute the suggestion that a Ner she'Lo Shavas refers even to a lamp that did not  even 'rest' from a Melachah that is permitted on the basis of a Beraisa which discusses a lamp that was lit for a Chayah or for a sick person.   What is a Chayah?\n(c) How does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak therefore interpret 'Ner she'Lo Shavas'?\n(d) What does the Beraisa say about a lantern that was lit the whole Shabbos that bears this out?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What does another Beraisa say about using a lamp that ...\n1. ... a Nochri lit from a Yisrael?\n2. ... a Yisrael lit from a Nochri?\n3. ... a Nochri lit from a Nochri?\n(b) Which two of these three rulings do we query (since they appear to clash)?\n(c) We query the suggestion that when a Yisrael lights from a Nochri, it is considered a new flame, from a Beraisa which obligates someone who carries a flame into the R'shus ha'Rabim.   How did he do that?\n(d) What is now the problem?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What reason do we therefore give finally to explain why the light that a Yisrael lit from a Nochri is permitted?\n(b) Then why is the light that a Nochri lit from the Nochri also permitted for the same reason?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) If someone who is travelling outside the city on Motza'ei Shabbos sees a light, on what condition does the Beraisa ...\n1. ... permit reciting the B'rachah over Ner?\n2. ... forbid him to do so?\n(b) What problem do we have with these two rulings?\n(c) We answer that in reality, by Mechtzah al Mechtzah, one is permitted to recite the B'rachah.   Then why in the Seifa, does the Tana say 'Rov Yisrael'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What does another Beraisa say about someone who is travelling outside the city on Motza'ei Shabbos and who comes across a child holding a torch? On what condition is one permitted to recite the B'rachah?\n(b) How does Rav Yehudah Amar Rav establish the Beraisa, to explain why the Beraisa mentions specifically a Katan?\n(c) How does that answer the Kashya?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Tana say about someone who sees a lit oven from outside the town on Motza'ei Shabbos? On what condition can he recite a B'rachah over it?\n(b) Why is that?\n(c) What do we mean, when, to reconcile the Beraisa which permits reciting a B'rachah over the light of a furnace and one which forbids it, we establish the latter Beraisa 'bi'Techilah',and the former, 'be'Sof'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What do two conflicting Beraisos say about reciting a B'rachah over the light of a Shul or a Beis ha'Medrash?\n(b) To reconcile them, we establish one of them where there is an important person there, and the other, where there isn't.   Which is which?\n(c) Alternatively, both speak where there is an important person there, and one speaks where there is a Chazan staying on the premises and the other, where there isn't.   What does 'Chazan' mean?\n(d) What is then the Gemara's answer? Which is which?\n(e) What is the final answer, even assuming that there is both an important person there and a Chazan who stays on the premises? On what condition will one nevertheless not be permitted to recite a B'rachah over the lamp?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) What do Beis Shamai say about a case where a number of people are sitting in the Beis-ha'Medrash on Motza'ei Shabbos and someone brings a light? Who recites the B'rachah?\n(b) Based on which Pasuk in Mishlei do Beis Hillel argue?\n(c) What is Beis Shamai's reason?\n(d) In a Beraisa supporting the reason of Beis Shamai, what did they not used to do in Raban Gamliel's Beis-ha'Medrash?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Why does the Mishnah not permit reciting a B'rachah over Ner shel ...\n1. ... Meisim?\n2. ... shel Besamim?\n(b) According to Rav Yehudah Amar Rav, when will one recite a B'rachah over a Ner shel Meis?\n(c) Why is that?\n(d) What does Rav Huna say about Besamim that are ...\n1. ... placed in the bathroom?\n2. ... brought to remove the sweat and dirt from one's hands? On what occasion did they tend to do this?\n(e) If this does not mean that he does not recite a B'rachah at all, then what does it mean?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) We query the current rulings from a Beraisa which discusses someone who enters a spice-shop.   What distinction does the Tana there draw between whether he remains there all day or whether he leaves and returns a number of times?\n(b) How does this pose a Kashya on the previous cases?\n(c) How do we answer it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) On what condition does the Tana Kama of the Beraisa require a person who is walking outside the town and who encounters a beautiful aroma to recite a B'rachah?\n(b) On what grounds does Rebbi Yossi rule that even if the majority of residents are Jewish, one does recite a B'rachah?\n(c) How do we answer the Pircha that it is inconceivable that all the women do that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Chiya bar Aba Amar Rebbi Yochanan say about someone who encounters a beautiful aroma whilst walking ...\n1. ... in Teverya on Erev Shabbos?\n2. ... in Tzipori on Motza'ei Shabbos?\n(b) Why is that?\n(c) And what does the Beraisa say about someone who is walking through a Nochri market and who deliberately inhales the  beautiful aroma that pervades there?\n(d) Another Beraisa goes even further.   What does the Tana say about someone who is walking through a Shuk shel Avodah-Zarah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) We learned in our Mishnah that one is forbidden to recite a B'rachah over a light until one benefits from it.   How does Rav Yehudah Amar Rav interpret it.\n(b) How close must one be to the Ner?\n(c) Rav Ashi condones Rav Yehudah's explanation.   How does he specifically establish the Mishnah?\n(d) We query this however, from a Beraisa.   What does the Tana there say about someone who is carrying a lamp hidden in his bosom or inside a lantern, if he saw a flame but did not benefit from it or if he used a flame without actually seeing it?\n(e) Which two conditions does he require before reciting a B'rachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) How do we interpret the last of the three cases in the current Beraisa?\n(b) How do we initially explain the middle case, which poses a Kashya Rav Yehudah and Rav Ashi?\n(c) To answer the Kashya, how do we establish the Beraisa?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) We learned in a Beraisa that one may recite a B'rachah over Gechalim Lochshos, but not over Gechalim Om'mos.  How does Rav Yitzchak bar Avdimi define 'Gechalim Lochshos'?\n(b) What She'eilah do we ask regarding the spelling of the word 'Om'mos'?\n(c) Rav Yitzchak bar Avdimi resolves the She'eilah from the Pasuk in Yechezkel \"Arazim Lo Am'muhu be'Gan Elokim\".   How is the word spelt there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) Rava disagrees with Rav Yehudah Amar Rav and Rav Ashi.   How does he explain 'ad she'Ye'Osu le'Oro'?\n(b) According to Ula, this mean that one is close enough to discern the difference between an Isar and a Pundiyon.   What do the two have in common?\n(c) According to Chizkiyah, it is the difference between the Meluzma of Teverya and that of Tzipori.   What is a 'Meluzma'?\n(d) Rav Yehudah recited a B'rachah over a lamp that he saw burning in the house of Ada Dayla, Rava over a lamp that he saw burning in the house of Gurya bar Chama.   What was the difference between the two?\n(e) What is the significance of ...\n1. ... the two Amora'im concerned?\n2. ... Abaye, who recited a B'rachah over a lamp that he saw burning in the house of bar Avuhah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Yehudah Amar Rav say about searching for a lamp over which to recite Birchas ha'Ner?\n(b) What did Rebbi Zeira comment upon hearing Rav Yehudah's statement?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) We learned in our Mishnah that, according to Beis Shamai, someone who forgot to Bench where he ate and left the room, is obligated to return and Bench where he ate.   What do Beis Hillel say?\n(b) Rav Z'vid (or Rav Dimi bar Aba) establish the Machlokes specifically where he forgot.   What if he did so be'Meizid?\n(c) The Gemara asks 'P'shita?' Why is that?\n(d) How do we answer the Kashya? If the same applies to Meizid, then why does the Mishnah mention Shogeg?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) What did Beis Shamai retort when Beis Hillel asked them in surprise whether this means that someone who, after eating on the top floor of a tall building, forgot and descended, is Chayav to climb to the top to Bench?\n(b) What happened to the Talmid who followed the ruling of Beis ...\n1. ... Shamai (be'Shogeg) and returned to the place where he ate, in order to Bench?\n2. ... Hillel (be'Meizid) and Benched where he was?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) What was the dilemma of Rabah bar bar Chanah, who was once about to travel in a caravan when he remembered that he had not Benched?\n(b) What did he therefore decide to tell them?\n(c) Why, based on a Pasuk in Tehilim), did he choose specifically the wings of a dove?\n(d) And why is Yisrael compared specifically to a dove?\n(e) What happened next?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) We learned in our Mishnah that one is permitted to still Bench as long as the food has not yet digested. Rebbi Yochanan defines this as 'as long as one is not yet hungry'.   What does Resh Lakish say?\n(b) Rav Yeimar bar Shalmaya (or bar Shizbi) queried Resh Lakish from a statement of Rav Ami in his (Resh Lakish's) name.  What Shi'ur did Rav Ami give during which time one is still permitted to Bench?\n(c) How did Mar Zutra resolve the discrepancy in Resh Lakish?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) Our Mishnah clearly implies that one answers Amen to the B'rachah of a Yisrael even if one hear the entire B'rachah.   What problem did we initially have with this?\n(b) What did Chiya bar Rav answer?\n(c) What did Rav Nachman Amar Rabah bar Avuhah say about it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav and Rav Huna mean when they instructed their sons Chiya and Rabah, respectively 'Chatofu'Varech!'?\n(b) Which principle did Rebbi Yossi in a Beraisa teach which clashes with that?\n(c) Rebbi Nehorai swore that this is so, based on the Gulayrin and the Giborim.   Who are the Gulayrin and the Giborim? What do they respectively, do?\n(d) How does this not pose a Kashya on Rav and Rav Huna?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) We answer that it is in fact, a Machlokes Tana'im. What is the Pasuk in Nechemya referring to when i says ...\n1. ... \"Kumu Borchu es Hash-m Elokeichem\"?\n2. ... \"Viyevar'chu Shem Kevodecha\"?\n(b) What is the connection between the latter Pasuk and 'Amen'?\n(c) What does the Tana now say about the two?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) What did Shmuel ask Rav about answering 'Amen' after children who recite a B'rachah?\n(b) What reason did Rav give for answering in the negative?\n(c) What is the sole exception?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q26",
        "label": "26)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Zila'i in a Beraisa mean when he says that the oil that they bring at the end of the meal holds back the B'rachah?\n(b) What other ramifications does this ruling have\"\n(c) What does Rebbi Ziva'i say?\n(d) Rebbi Acha seems to make a compromise. What does he say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q27",
        "label": "27)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Zuhama'i, what does the Dinim of the Avodah and of Benching have in common?\n(b) Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak disagrees with Rebbi Zila'i, Rebbi Ziva'i and Rebbi Zuhama'i. He does however, hold of a Beraisa (some cite it as a statement of Rav Yehudah Amar Rav).  If, citing a Pasuk in Kedoshim, the Tana interprets ...\n1. ... \"Vehiskadishtem\" as 'Mayim Rishonim', howdoes he interpret \"Vih'yisem Kedoshim\"\n2. ... \"ki Kadosh Ani\" as 'Shemen ha'Tov', how does he interpret \"Ani Hash-m Elokeichem\"?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 54,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Which B'rachah does one recite when one sees ...\n1. ... a place where miracles were performed on behalf of Yisrael?\n2. ... a place in Eretz Yisrael where idolatry was destroyed?\n3. ... (or hears) comets, earthquakes, thunder, storm-winds or lightning?\n4. ... mountains, famous hills, seas, (the four) rivers (see Tosfos) and deserts?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Yehudah, which B'rachah does one recite upon seeing the ocean (or the Mediterranean Sea)?\n(b) Which B'rachah does one recite over ...\n1. ... the first rains and good news?\n2. ... bad news?\n3. ... a new house or new utensils?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Mishnah say about ...\n1. ... good news that contains some bad, and bad news that contains some good?\n2. ... someone who cries out to Hash-m about something that has already happened?\n(b) One example of this is if someone Davens that the baby that his wife is expecting should be a boy.  What is the other, involving someone who arrives in his home-town and hears a scream.   What is the other?\n(c) According to the Tana Kama, upon entering a town, one recites two Tefilos.   What is the significance of these two Tefilos?\n(d) And what is the significance of the four Tefilos prescribed by Ben Azai?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) From which words in the Pasuk in the Sh'ma \"Ve'ahavta es Hash-m Elokecha ... \" do we learn that a person is Chayav to recite a B'rachah over the bad as well as over the good?\n(b) What B'rachah does one recite over bad news?\n(c) What does the Beraisa learn from ...\n1. ... \"be'Chol Levavcha\"?\n2. ... \"u've'Chol Nafshecha\"?\n(d) We just cited one D'rashah that the Tana learns from \"u've'Chol Me'odecha\".   What alternative D'rashah does he learn from it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What is one not permitted to do 'opposite the eastern gate of the Har ha'Bayis'?\n(b) Why is that?\n(c) What may a person not carry with him (or wear) when he enters the area of the Har ha'Bayis?\n(d) What else may one not bring with him into the Har ha'Bayis?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) One is also not permitted to make it a Kapendarya.   What is a 'Kapendarya'?\n(b) What does the Mishnah say about spitting there?\n(c) Initially, whoever recited a B'rachah in the Beis-ha'Mikdash would conclude with the words 'min ha'Olam'.   Who caused them to change this?\n(d) What did they subsequently say?\n(e) Who initiated this Takanah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) Which other Takanah did the Chachamim initiate, based on a Pasuk in Megilas Rus, in connection with Bo'az?\n(b) How did Bo'az greet the harvesters, when he arrived from Beis Lechem?\n(c) How did they respond?\n(d) Why would we otherwise have thought that it is forbidden to do so?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) If we learn from the Pasuk in Shoftim \"Hash-m im'cha Gibor ha'Chayil\" that the angel corroborated Bo'az's initiative, what do  we learn from the Pasuk ...\n1. ... in Mishlei \"ve'Al Tavuz ki Zaknah Imecha\"?\n2. ... in Tehilim \"Eis La'asos la'Hashem, Heiferu Torasecha\"?\n(b) From which other Pasuk in Tehilim do we learn this principle?\n(c) What did Rebbi Nasan comment on the Tana Kama's last quote?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yochanan learn from the Pasuk in Yisro \"Baruch Hash-m asher Hitzil eschem mi'Yad Mitzrayim\"?\n(b) What did Rava tell the man who was fallen upon by a lion and who managed to escape to do?\n(c) What do we learn from that incident and a number of other incidents that we are about to discuss?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What happened to Mar b'rei de'Ravina when he was once ...\n1. ... traveling in the valley of Arvos and he became extremely thirsty?\n2. ... walking through the market-place of Mechuza?\n(b) How did he manage to escape the latter attack?\n(c) What did he subsequently say whenever he passed ...\n1. ... Arvos?\n2. ... through the market-place of Mechuza?\n(d) What distinction do we draw between the B'rachah over a communal miracle (as in our Mishnah) and a private one?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) What common ruling does the Beraisa issue concerning the crossings of the Reed-Sea, the crossings of the Jordan River and the crossings of the Rivers of Arnon (which will be explained later)?\n(b) What exactly are the crossings of the Reed-Sea and the crossings of the Jordan River?\n(c) The last item on the list is the walls of Yericho, which sank in into the ground during the first battle of the conquest of Yericho.   Which 'famous' ...\n1. ... stone (besides the stone that Og attempted to hurl at Yisrael), does the Tana mention?\n2. ... woman does he list?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What do we prove by citing the Pasuk in ...\n1. ... Beshalach \"Vayavo'u B'nei Yisrael b'Soch ha'Yam ba'Yabashah\"?\n2. ... Yehoshua \"Vaya'amdu ha'Kohanim nos'ei ha'Aron B'ris Hash-m be'Charavah B'soch ha'Yarden\" Hachein ... \"?\n(b) To explain what were 'the crossings of the rivers of Arnon, we cite the Pasuk in Chukas \"al-Kein Ye'amer be'Seifer Milchamos Hash-m, es Vaheiv be'Sufah ... \".    How do we interpret the words \"Es va'Heiv\"?\n(c) What is the significance of the caves facing the jutting rocks?\n(d) What were the Emori'im doing in the caves?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What did the Emori'im not know?\n(b) What happened on that occasion?\n(c) Who informed K'lal Yisrael about the miracle?What did they tell them?\n(d) How did Yisrael react to the news?\n(e) What is the significance of the Pasuk \"ve'Eshed ha'Nechalim asher Natah Lesheves Or Venish'an li'Gevul Mo'av\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) Describing the 'Avnei Elgavish' cited in the Beraisa on Amud Alef, another Beraisa gives the acronym 'Avanim she'Amdu al-Gav Isha'.   What does the acronym mean?\n(b) How do we know that \"Ish\" refers to Moshe?\n(c) Which stones is it then referring to?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa adds that they also came down 'al-Gav Ish'.   This time, \"Ish\" refers to the man about whom the Torah writes \"Ish asher Ru'ach bo\".   About whom is this said?\n(b) What is it now referring to?\n(c) And what has this to do with the Pasuk in Yehoshua in connection with the kings of the Emori) \"Vay'hi be'Nusam mipnei B'nei Yisrael, Heim be'Morad Beis Choron\"? What happened next?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) From where do we know that Og Melech ha'Bashan attempted to hurl a rock at the B'nei Yisrael?\n(b) Why did he take a mountain that measured three Parsah (twelve Mil)?\n(c) How dowe know that?\n(d) How did he obtain it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) After Og placed the rock on his head, what did Hakadosh-Baruch-Hu do to prevent him from carrying out his diabolical plan?\n(b) And what stopped him from lifting the mountain from off his neck and hurling it at them?\n(c) How does Resh Lakish therefore interpret the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Shinei Resha'im Shibarta\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) How does the story continue?   What did Moshe take in his hand to dispense with Yisrael's arch-enemy?\n(b) What did he subsequently do? How high did he reach?\n(c) How did he manage to reach such an incredible height?\n(d) How do we know that Moshe was ten Amos tall?\n(e) What happened next?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) What is the significance of the stone on which Moshe sat? What purpose did it serve?\n(b) What problem do we have with the inclusion of Lot's wife in the list?\n(c) Why is the answer that on seeing Lot's wife one recites 'Baruch Dayan ha'Emes' not acceptable?\n(d) So how do we finally explain her insertion? What did the Tana really say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) What B'rachah does one recite concerning the salvation of Lot?\n(b) To which Tzadik does this refer?\n(c) What does Rebbi Yochanan comment on the fact that Hash-m remembered Avraham at that point?\n(d) How do we reconcile our Mishnah, which refers to the walls of Yericho sinking into the ground, with the Pasuk which tells us that they fell?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Yehudah Amar Rav cites four people who are obligated to thank Hash-m for their salvation. Two of them are someone who travels across the sea and someone who travels through a desert.   What are the other two?\n(b) What is the common source for all four?\n(c) What is the significance of the Pasuk ...\n1. ... \"Vayitz'aku/Vayiz'aku el Hash-m ba'Tzar lahem ... \"?\n2. ... \"Yodu la'Hashem Chasdo ... \"?\n(d) How does the latter Pasuk end?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav Yehudah, what is the text of the B'rachah that the above four people make?\n(b) What does Abaye add, based on the Pasuk there \"Viyeromemuhu bi'Kehal Am\"?\n(c) And what does Mar Zutra add, based on the Pasuk \"u've'Moshav Zekeinim Yehaleluhu\"?\n(d) How do we answer Rav Ashi's Kashya that perhaps all ten men should be Talmidei-Chachamim?\n(e) What Kashya do we finally ask to which we have no answer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) When Rav Chana Bagdesa'ah and the Rabbanan went to visit Rav Yehudah after the latter had recovered from his illness, they declared 'B'rich Rachmana de'Yahavach Nehelan ve'Lo Yahavach le'Afra!'.   What does this mean?\n(b) What did Rav Yehudah respond to that?\n(c) How do we reconcile this with Abaye's earlier ruling that requires the B'rachah to be recited in front of ten people?\n(d) How could this be effective seeing as Rav Yehudah did not recite the B'rachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) Two of the three people that Rav Yehudah initially lists who need to be guarded are a sick person and a Chasan.   Who is the third?\n(b) Who does the Beraisa add to the list?\n(c) Some add an Aveil (a mourner).   Who do others add?\n(d) Against whom do they require guarding?\n(e) The demons are jealous of the Chasan, the Kalah, and of the Talmid-Chacham.   What makes a sick person, an Aveil and a woman who has given birth more vulnerable than other people?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Yehudah also lists three things that earn a person long life.   If two of them are Davening long and spending a long time over one's meal, what is the third?\n(b) Why does spending a long time over one's meal earn a person long life?\n(c) How do we reconcile Davening long with the statement of Rebbi Chiya bar Aba, that 'Someone who Davens long and looks into it (convinced that Hash-m will answer him), will end up disappointed?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 55,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Two of the things that, Rebbi Yitzchak says, bring Hash-m's attention to the person who does them are a leaning wall and Iyun Tefilah (scrutiny in prayer, as we just explained).   What is the third?\n(b) Besides the leaning wall, which is subject to the principle 'The Satan accuses at a time of danger', which common reason to all three cases?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What problem do we have with the Pesukim in Yechezkel \"ha'Mizbe'ach Eitz Shalosh Amos Gavohah\" ... \"va'Yedaber eilai, 'Zeh ha'Shulchan asher Lifnei Hashem' \"?\n(b) What do we learn from there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) We query Rebbi Yochanan, who just included sitting long in the bathroom among the things that grant a person long life from a Beraisa.   How many things does the Tana include that cause a person to contract piles?\n(b) The last (eleventh) case that 'Yesh Omrim' adds to the list is that of 'Toleh Atzmo be'Veis ha'Kisei'.   How do we reconcile this with Rebbi Yochanan?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) A Roman matron suggested two reasons as to why Rebbi Yehudah had a healthy complexion.   One was because he reared Chazeirim.       What was the second reason?\n(b) Why should these occupations cause a person to have a healthy complexion\n(c) What was Rebbi Yehudah's initial response?\n(d) So how did he explain his healthy complexion?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) The first two items on the above list (that one should not eat to avoid piles) are the leaves of canes and vine-leaves.   What other part of a vine should one not eat?\n(b) The fourth tem is Morigei Beheimah.   What are 'Morigei Beheimah'?\n(c) The fifth and sixth items are connected with a fish.   If the fifth item is the spine of a fish, what is the sixth?\n(d) Which part of wine constitutes the seventh item on the list?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) Which two things must one avoid using (eight and nine) when cleaning oneself after going to the bathroom?\n(b) Finally, what else should one avoiding using for that purpose to avoid contracting piles?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) How many things does Rav Yehudah list that curtail a person's life?\n(b) The first of these is someone who is called up to the Torah and declines to go.   From which Pasuk in Yehoshua does he learn it?\n(c) What is the second thing, based on the Pasuk in Lech-L'cha \"Va'avarchah Mevorchecha\"?\n(d) How does he learn it from that Pasuk?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) And what is the third thing, based on a statement of Rebbi Chama bar Chanina (about Yosef ha'Tzadik), that causes a person's early demise?\n(b) What did Rebbi Chama bar Chanina say about Yosef ha'Tzadik?\n(c) From which Pasuk in Sh'mos did he learn it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav Yehudah Amar Rav, two of the three things that require Divine mercy are a good year and a good dream.   What is the third?\n(b) He learns a good dream from the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Palgei Mayim Leiv Melech be'Yad Hash-m ... \".   What does he learn from the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"Vatachlimeini Vatechayeini\"?\n(c) And from which Pasuk in Eikev does he learn 'a good year'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Yochanan, Hash-m Himself declares three things; two of them, hunger and being satiated, which he learns from Pesukim in Melachim and Yechezkel.   What is the third?\n(b) He learns that from the Pasuk in Ki Sissa, which refers to a famous personality whom Hash-m \"called by Name\".   What was the name of famous personality?\n(c) What was he being chosen to do?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yitzchak learn from the Pasuk in Vayakhel \"See (Re'u plural), Hash-m has called by name Betzalel ... ?\n(b) What did ...\n1. ... Hash-m reply when Moshe retort that if he was good in the Eyes of Hash-m, then he was good in his eyes too?\n2. ... Yisrael reply when Moshe asked them whether they agreed to the choice of Betzalel?\n(c) In what order did Moshe tell Betzalel about the Mishkan and its Keilim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Shmuel bar Nachmeni Amar Rebbi Yonoson therefore mean when he said that Betzalel was thus named on account of his Chochmah?\n(b) What did he say?\n(c) What did Moshe reply?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Yehudah Amar Rav say that Betzalel was conversant with?\n(b) From which Pasuk in Ki Sissa did he learn it (based also on the P'sukim in Mishlei \"Hash-m be'Chochmah Yasad Aretz ... be'Da'to Tehomos Nivka'u\")?\n(c) What did Rebbi Yochanan learn from the Pasuk in Daniel \"Yahav Chochm'sa la'Chakimin u'Mind'a le'Yod'ei Binah\"?\n(d) When Ra Tachlifa bar Ma'arva told this to Rebbi Avahu.  From which Pasuk in Ki Sissa did Rebbi Avahu learn it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Chisda mean when he said that every dream can be good except for Tavas?\n(b) What did he also say about ...\n1. ... a dream that is not interpreted?\n2. ... good dreams and bad dreams in general?\n3. ... bad  dreams in relation to good ones?\n(c) What is the reason behind Rav Chisda's last statement?\n(d) And what did he say about the sadness and the joy that follow bad and good dreams respectively?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Yosef testify with regard to Rav Chisda's last statement?\n(b) Why did he say 'even me'?\n(c) What did Rabah bar bar Chanan comment on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"ve'ha'Elokim Asah she'Yir'u mi'Lefanav!\"\n(d) How does Rebbi Yochanan in the name of Rebbi Shimon bar Yochai explain the insertion of 'produce and straw' in the Pasuk in Yirmiyah (in connection with dreams)?\n(e) Rebbi B'rachyah seems to confirm this when he says that not every detail in a dream actually comes true.   How does he learn this from one of Yosef's dreams?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) Up to how many years does Levi say a person should wait for a good dream to materialize?\n(b) He learns this from Yosef, who was seventeen years old when his father sent him on his fateful mission which ended with his sale to Egypt.   How old was he when he stood before Par'oh?\n(c) How do we account for the remaining nine years?\n(d) What does Rav Huna initially say about a good person and a bad one with regard to dreams?\n(e) What is the reason for ...\n1. ... the former?\n2. ... the latter?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) We support Rav Huna's statement with a Beraisa.   What does the Tana there say about David and Achitofel?\n(b) we query the former part of the statement from a statement by Rav Chisda.   What did Rav Chisda Amar Rebbi Yirmiyah bar Aba comment on the Pasuk in Tehilim ...\n1. ... \"No harm will befall you\"?\n2. ... \"and no plague will come near to your home\"?\n(c) How do we reconcile this with Rav Huna, who intimates that a Tzadik will see bad dreams?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) We query the current explanation, which intimates that a Tzadik sees neither a good dream or a bad one from the Pasuk in Mishlei \"ve'Save'a Yalin bal Yipaked Ra\".   How does Rebbi Ze'ira read the Pasuk, that leaves us with a Kashya?\n(b) What does the Pasuk now mean?\n(c) To answer the Kashya, how do we explain Rav Huna's statement that a Tzadik does not have a good dream?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) What does Huna bar Ami ... in the name of Rebbi Yochanan advise someone who is miserable on account of a dream that he had to do?\n(b) What problem do we have with his initial advice based on a statement of Rav Chisda?\n(c) How do we therefore amend the Lashon 'Yifterenu'?\n(d) What in effect, do the three people that one calls say to the dreamer?\n(e) How many times do they ask Hash-m to decree that it should be good (See also Tosfos)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) How many Pesukim should they recite that contain ...\n1. ... 'Hafachos' (beginning with the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Hafachta Misp'di le'Machol li ...\")?\n2. ... ''Peduyos' (beginning with the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Padah ve'Shalom Nafshi\")?\n(b) Of which third group of three Pesukim is the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"Borei Niv Sefasayim, Shalom Shalom la'Rachok ... \" the first?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) What did Ameimar, Mar Zutra and Rav Ashi once suggest that each one of them does?\n(b) What did one of them say a person should do if he had a dream but cannot remember what it was?\n(c) In the course of the Tefilah, one refers to Yosef's dreams on the one hand, and the water of Marah, Miriam's Tzara'as, Chizkiyhu's illness, and the stricken water in the time of Elisha.   What is the connection between them?\n(d) What care should he take when concluding his Tefilah?\n(e) How do the Kohanim respond, after the conclusion of Birchas Kohanim, when they turn back to face the Aron ha'Kodesh (See also Hagahos ha'G'ra)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) The second member of the trio offered a suggestion to someone who enters a town and is afraid of an Ayin ha'Ra.   What did he advise him to do after taking hold off his right thumb in his left hand?\n(b) Based on the Pasuk in Vay'chi \"Ben Poras ... Ben Poras alei Ayin!\", whose offspring did he advise the frightened man to claim to be?\n(c) How did ...\n1. ... he interpret the words \"alei Ayin\"?\n2. ... Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina learn the same thing from the Pasuk there \"Veyidgu la'Rov be'Kerev ha'Aretz!\"?\n(d) About who was the latter said?\n(e) And what did he advise a man who is afraid of his own Ayin ha'Ra to take hold of?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) The third member of the trio advised a sick man not to publicize his illness for the first day.   Why is that?\n(b) What did Rava instruct his servant to do after the first day of his illness?\n(c) Why did he also instruct him to announce that whoever hated him should rejoice?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the Pasuk in Zecharyah \"ve'ha'Chalomos Shav Yedaberu ( ... dreams are nonsensical)\", what did Shmuel used to declare after ...\n1. ... a bad dream?\n2. ... a good dream?\n(b) Which Pasuk in Beha'aloscha (in connection with Moshe Rabeinu) did he cite to corroborate his latter statement?\n(c) How did Rava resolve the contradiction between the two Pesukim (\"ve'ha'Chalomos Shav Yedaberu\" and \"ba'Chalom Adaber bo\")?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) How many dream-interpreters were there in Yerushalayim, according to Rebbi Bizna bar Zavda ... in the name of a certain Zakein?\n(b) What was the name of that Zakein?\n(c) What happened once, when he took his dream to all of them for interpretation?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q26",
        "label": "26)",
        "text": "(a) What important principle can we extrapolate from Rebbi Ban'ah's testimony?\n(b) We refer to the principle as a Pasuk.   Which Pasuk (in Vayeishev, in connection with Yosef), according to Rebbi Elazar's interpretation?\n(c) What condition does Rava require for the principle to apply?\n(d) From which Pasuk there does he learn it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q27",
        "label": "27)",
        "text": "(a) The Pasuk relates how the baker saw that Yosef had interpreted the butler's dream correctly.   From where did he know that?\n(b) What did Rebbi Yochanan say about someone who gets up in the morning and for no particular reason, a specific Pasuk springs to mind?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q28",
        "label": "28)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Yochanan say about a morning dream?\n(b) He says the same about two other dreams; one of them, a dream that Reuven dreams about Shimon.   What is the other?\n(c) What dream do others add to the list, based on the Pasuk in Mikeitz (in connection with Yosef's interpretation of Par'oh's dream) \"ve'al Hishanos ha'Chalom\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q29",
        "label": "29)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Shmuel bar Nachmeni Amar Rebbi Yonasan say, based on the Pasuk in Daniel \"Ant Malka Ra'Yanach al Mishk'vach Salku!\"?\n(b) In what connection do others cite the Pasuk there \"ve'Ra'yonei Levavach Tinda!\"?\n(c) What examples does Rava give (that one does not tend to dream) in support of Rebbi Shmuel bar Nachmeni's statement?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 56,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What did the emperor of Rome ask Rebbi Yehoshua ben Chananya to do, since he was so wise?\n(b) In response, who did he tell him would capture him in his dream?\n(c) What would they make him hold as he tended to their Sheratzim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Of whom did Shavur Malka make a similar request? Who was Shavur Malka?\n(b) Who did Shmuel say would capture him in his dream?\n(c) What would he make him grind?\n(d) With which kind of mill?\n(e) On what grounds did the predictions of both Raban Gamliel and Shmuel come true?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What strange coincidences occurred to Abaye and Rava over and over again?\n(b) Both went to bar Hedya.   Who was bar Hedya?\n(c) When both Amora'im dreamt the Pasuk in Ki Savo \"Shorcha Tavu'ach le'Einecha ... \", how did he interpret it on behalf of ...\n1. ... Rava?\n2. ... Abaye?\n(d) Why, in this case and all the subsequent cases, did bar Hedya interpret all of Abaye's and Rava's dreams the way he did?\n(e) How is it possible to interpret the same same dream in such diverse ways?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) When both Abaye and Rava dreamt the Pasuk there \"Banim u'Banos Tolid ve'Lo Yih'yu l'cha ki Yeilchu ba'Shevi\", he interpreted the Pasuk literally for Rava.   How did he interpret it for Abaye?\n(b) They then dreamt the Pasuk there \"Banecha u'Venosecha Nesunos le'Am Acher\".   What quarrel did bar Hedya foretell would occur between Abaye and his wife concerning their many children?\n(c) Who was destined to win the arguments?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the word \"Acher\" in the previous dream what dual tragedy did bar Hedya inform Rava was about to occur?\n(b) To whom did \"Am Acher' refer to in the case of ...\n1. ... Abaye?\n2. ... Rava?\n(c) How did Rava himself, quoting ... Rav, interpret \"Am Acher\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) Their next dream involved the Pasuk in Koheles \"Lech Echol be'Simchah Lachmecha ... \".   What would cause Abaye to eat, drink and rejoice?\n(b) What did he say to Rava?\n(c) Both Abaye and Rava were destined to read the Pasuk.   Why did ...\n1. ... Abaye read it?\n2. ... Rava read it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) How did bar Hedya interpret the Pesukim there \"Zera Rav Totzi ha'Sadeh, u'Me'at Te'esof ... and \"Zeisim Yih'yu l'cha be'Chol Gevulecha, ve'Shemen Lo Sasuch ... \" ...\n1. ... for Abaye?\n2. ... for Rava?\n(b) And how did he interpret the Pasuk there \"ve'Ra'u Kol Amei-ha'Aretz ki Shem Hash-m Nikra alecha ve'Yar'u mimeka\" ...\n1. ... for Abaye?\n2. ... for Rava?\n(c) What happened the following day?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) What business did both Abaye and Rava indulge in?\n(b) When they both dreamt that they saw lettuce on top of a barrel of wine, he told Abaye that his business would prosper like lettuce (which is wide and grows double.   What did he tell Rava?\n(c) And when they both saw in their dream meat on top of a barrel of wine, what did he tell ...\n1. ... Abaye?\n2. ... Rava?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) When they both dreamt that they saw a barrel of wine  hanging on a date palm, what did bar Hedya tell ...\n1. ... Abaye?\n2. ... Rava?\n(b) And when they dreamt that they saw pomegranates growing on a barrel, what did he tell ...\n1. ... Abaye?\n2. ... Rava?\n(c) Next they dreamt that the saw a barrel of wine falling into a pit.   What did he say to ...\n1. ... Abaye?\n2. ... Rava?\n(d) Finally, they dreamt that they saw a donkey standing by their cushion (heads). Bar Hedya told Abaye that he would become king (Rosh Yeshivah) and that he a Meturg'man will stand beside him to say over his D'rashos to the people.   What did he tell Rava ...\n1. ... initially?\n2. ... when Rava replied that he had seen the words himself?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Ultimately, Rava went to bar Hedya alone.   What did the latter tell him when he dreamt that ...\n1. ... the outer door of his house fell down?\n2. ... molars and his front teeth fell out?\n3. ... two doves flew away?\n4. ... he saw two heads of turnips?\n(b) What is the connection between ...\n1. ... the outer door of his house and his wife?\n2. ... wives and doves?\n3. ... heads of turnips and a beating with a club?\n(c) What happened when, after spending a day in the Beis-ha'Medrash, Rava tried to intervene in a fight between two poor men?\n(d) What did he declare when they wanted to strike him once more?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) On the next five occasions that Rava went to bar Hedya to interpret a dream, the forecast was more positive.   What did he tell him when he dreamt that ...\n1. ... a wall fell down?\n2. ... Abaye's house collapsed and that dust covered the bricks?\n3. ... His own house collapsed and people came and helped themselves to the bricks?\n4. ... his head split open and his brains spilt out?\n5. ... he recited Hallel ha'Mitzri?\n(b) What caused bar Hedya to switch to positive interpretations?\n(c) What caused bar Hedya to leave the ferry as he and Rava were about to cross the river?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What happened as bar Hedya turned to leave the ferry?\n(b) When Rava glanced at the book, what did he discover written inside it?\n(c) What had he thought previously?\n(d) What title did he then confer upon bar Hedya?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) If there was one thing which Rava could not forgive bar Hedya, what was it?\n(b) What did he wish him before they parted company?\n(c) Why ...\n1. ... was bar Hedya afraid?\n2. ... particularly of Rava's curse?\n(d) Why did he therefore flee to Rome?\n(e) Where did he station himself in Rome?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) What practice did bar Hedya continue even when in Rome?\n(b) What did he therefore tell the keeper of the royal wardrobe when he dreamt that a needle had pierced his finger?\n(c) What did the royal keeper dream next?\n(d) What did bar Hedya tell the keeper when he dreamt that his entire hand had become wormy."
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) What did the emperor do when he discovered what had happened to his wardrobe?\n(b) Why did they then bring bar Hedya before him?\n(c) What did the Emperor say to him before sentencing him to death?\n(d) How did they carry out the death-sentence?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) ben Dama related his dreams to Rebbi Yishmael.   Who was ben Dama?\n(b) In one dream, his two jaws fell out.   How did Rebbi Yishmael interpret it?\n(c) How did Rebbi interpret bar Kapara's dream that ...\n1. ... his nose fell off?\n2. ... his two hands were severed?\n3. ... his two feet were severed?\n(d) In his next dream, bar Kapara dreamt that he would die in Adar and not see Nisan.   How did Rebbi interpret ...\n1. ... the first part of his dream?\n2. ... the second part of his dream?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) How did Rebbi Yishmael interpret the dream of a certain Tzedoki who dreamt that he ...\n1. ... was watering an olives with oil?\n2. ... tore out a star?\n3. ... swallowed a star?\n(b) What is the connection between the two latter dreams and the interpretation?\n(c) And what did he tell him when he dreamt that ...\n1. ... his two eyes kissed each other?\n2. ... two moons kissed each other?\n3. ... he walked in the shade of a myrtle-tree?\n4. ... that the load that he was carrying on his shoulder was underneath him?\n(d) How did Rebbi Yishmael interpret his next two dreams (that he saw first ravens and then pigeons, surrounding his bed)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) How did Rebbi Yishmael interpret the Tzedoki's dream ...\n1. ... that the two doves he was holding flew away?\n2. ... he was shelling eggs?\n(b) What happened when he claimed that everything that Rebbi Yishmael had said was correct except for that?\n(c) Finally, the Tzedoki dreamt that his father left him property in Kepudki.    Before interpreting it, Rebbi Yishmael asked him two questions, one of them, whether he owned property in Kepudki.   What was the second question?\n(d) When the Tzedoki answered in the negative, he interpreted the dream, based on the acronym of the word 'Kepudki'.   What is ...\n1. ... 'Kapa' in Persian?\n2. ... 'Dika' in Greek?\n(e) What did he therefore tell him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) There are three set interpretations of seeing a well in a dram.   How does ...\n1. ... Rebbi Chanina interpret it, based on the Pasuk in Chayei Sarah \"va'Yachper Avdei Yitzchak va'Yimtze'u Sham Be'er Mayim Chayim\"?\n2. ... Rebbi Nasan interpret it, by means of a Gezeirah-Shavah between the same Pasuk and the Pasuk  in Mishlei (whose main theme is Torah) \"Ki Motza'i Matza Chayim\"?\n3. ... Rava learn it from the simple meaning of the Pasuk?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Chanan, based on Pesukim in Yeshayah, what do a river, a bird and a pot in a dream signify\"\n(b) How did Rebbi Chanina, based on a Pasuk in Michah, qualify the last item?\n(c) What has this to do with the Pasuk in Michah \"u'Farsu ka'asher ba'Sid, u'che'Basar asher ba'Tzlachas\"?\n(d) According to Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi, what is the connection between someone who dreams about ...\n1. ... a river and the two Pesukim (in Yeshayah) \"Hin'ni Noteh eilehah ke'Nahar Shalom\" & \"Ki Yavo ke'Nahar Tzar\"?\n2. ... a bird and the two Pesukim \"ke'Tiparim Afos, kein Yagein Hash-m ... al Yerushalayim\" (Yeshayah) & \"ke'Tzipor Nodedes min Kaneh\" (Mishlei)?\n3. ... a pot and the Pesukim \"Hash-m Tishpos Shalom lanu\" (Yeshayah) & \"Sh'fos ha'Sir, Sh'fos ha'Ro'eh\" (Yechezkel)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi say further about a dream concerning ...\n1. ... grapes and the two Pesukim \"ka'Anavim ba'Midbar\" (Hoshe'a)  & \"Anoveimo Invei Rosh\" (Ha'azinu)?\n2. ... a mountain and the two Pesukim \"Mah Navu al he'Harim Raglei Mevaser\" (Yeshayah) & \"al he'Harim Esa Bechi\" (Yirmiyah)?\n3. ... a Shofar and the two Pesukim \"Vehayah ba'Yom ha'Hu Yitaka be'Shofar Gadol\" (Yeshayah) & \"Tik'u Shofar be'Givah\" (Hoshe'a)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) If one dreams about a dog, which Pasuk in Bo does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi advise one to recite before the Pasuk (in Yeshayah)  \"ve'ha'Kelavim Azei Nefesh\" springs to mind?\n(b) And what does he say about a dream concerning a lion and the Pesukim \"Aryeh Sha'ag Mi Lo Yiyra\" (Amos) & \"Alah Aryeh mi'Subcho\" (Yirmiyah)?\n(c) When dreaming about taking a shave, which Pasuk (in Mikeitz) does he advise a person to recite before the Pasuk (in Shoftim) \"ve'Gulachti ve'Sar Kochi\" springs to mind?\n(d) And what does Rebbi Yehishua ben Levi finally say about a person who dreams about ...\n1. ... a well and the Pesukim \"Be'er Mayim Chayim\" (in Shir ha'Shirim) & \"ke'Hakir Bor ... Meimehah\" (Yirmiyah)?\n2. ... a cane and the Pesukim \"Kaneh Ratzutz Lo Yishbor\" (Yeshayah) & \"Hinei Batachta l'cha al Mish'enes ha'Kaneh ha'Ratzutz\" (Melachim)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) According to the Beraisa, what should a person hope for if he dreams ...\n1. ... a cane, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Reishis Chochmah K'nei Chochmah\"?\n2. ... canes, based on the Pasuk there \"u've'Chol Kinyanecha K'nei Binah\"?\n(b) What does Rebbi Zeira say about 'Kara (a pumpkin), Korei (a creeper that grows round a date-palm), Kira (wax) and Kanya (a cane)'.   What do they all have in common?\n(c) What are 'Delu'in'?\n(d) According to another Beraisa, what sort of person sees them in a dream?\n(e) If someone dreams about an ox, which Pasuk in ve'Zos ha'Berachah should he recite before the Pasuk in Mishpatim \"ve'Chi Yigach Shor es Ish u'Meis\" springs to mind?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) The first in the list of five things that the Beraisa says about a dream containing an ox is that if he eats from it, he will become rich.   What does the Tana say about where the ox gores him?\n(b) If it bites him, it is a sign that he will suffer.   What if ...\n1. ... it kicks him?\n2. ... he rides on it?\n(c) To reconcile this with another Beraisa, which states 'Rachbo, Meis', how do we establish the latter?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the Pasuk in Zecharyah (in connection with Mashi'ach) \"Hinei Malkech Yavo lach, Tzadik ve'Nosha hu, Ani ve'Rochev al ha'Chamor\", what can a person who sees a donkey in his dream expect?\n(b) And if he sees a cat, what does this signify in a place where they call a cat ...\n1. ... 'Shunra'?\n2. ... 'Shinra'?\n(c) If he sees grapes, the Tana draws a distinction between 'white' grapes and 'black' ones.   What do white grapes always signify?\n(d) When do black also signify good news?\n(e) What about black grapes out of season?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q26",
        "label": "26)",
        "text": "(a) Similarly, the Tana differentiates between seeing a white horse and a red/brown one.   What does a white horse signify, regardless as to whether it is walking or running?\n(b) The same applies to a red one that is walking.   What if it is running?\n(c) What does the Tana say about someone who sees Yishmael in a dream? Which 'Yishmael; is he referring to?\n(d) What must a person have seen in a dream to know that he was spared from death?\n(e) If Rebbi Chama b'Rebbi Chanina learns this from acronym of the words \"Gam Aloh\" (in the Pasuk in Vayigash \"Anochi Eired im'cha Mitzraymah va'Anochi A'alcha Gam Aloh\"), how does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak learn it from the Pasuk in Shmuel (where Nasan ha'Navi was instructed to tell David) \"Gam Hash-m He'evir Chatascha Lo Tamus\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q27",
        "label": "27)",
        "text": "(a) Why does seeing Pinchas in a dream indicate that one will experience a miracle?\n(b) What if he sees ...\n1. ... an elephant?\n2. ... more than one elephant?\n(c) What does another Beraisa say about dreaming about any Chayah except for two in a dream, one of which is an elephant?\n(d) What is the other one?\n(e) How do we reconcile the two Beraisos?"
      }
    ]
  },
