      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) According to the Beraisa that the Beraisa expert cited to Rebbi Yochanan, which is the only beverage that is not always a good sign?\n(b) What do we learn from the Pasuk ...\n1. ... in Tehilim \"ve'Yayin Yesamach L'vav Enosh\"?\n2. ... in Mishlei \"T'nu Sheichar le'Oveid, ve'Yayin le'Marei Nefesh\"?\n(c) What did Rebbi Yochanan tell the Beraisa expert, based on the Pasuk \"L'chu Lachmu be'Lachmi, u'Shesu be'Yein Mesechti\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Yochanan say about someone who gets up in the morning and for no specific reason, thinks of a certain Pasuk?\n(b) What did David, Sh'lomoh and Ach'av have in common?\n(c) What can someone expect if he dreams about ...\n1. ... David?\n2. ... Sh'lomoh?\n3. ... Achav?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) What do the following three have in common ...\n1. ... Yechezkel, Yeshayah and Yirmiyah?\n2. ... Tehilim, Mishlei and Iyov?\n(b) If someone sees in a dream Seifer Melachim, he should expect greatness, Yechezkel (who saw Ma'aseh ha'Mekavah), wisdom and Yeshayah, consolation.   What can he expect if he sees Yirmiyah?\n(c) Likewise, if one sees in a dream Seifer Tehilim, he can expect Chasidus (piety) and Seifer Mishlei, wisdom.   What can he expect if he sees Seifer Iyov?\n(d) And what do Seifer Shir ha'Shirim, Seifer Koheles and Seifer Kinos (Eichah) have in common?\n(e) The Mishnah says that if one sees in a dream Shir ha'Shirim, one can expect Chasidus and Koheles, Chochmah.   What can one expect if one sees ...\n1. ... Kinos?\n2. ... Megilas Esther?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) How does the Tana describe Rebbi, Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah and Rebbi Yishmael ben Elisha?\n(b) What can one expect if one sees in a dream ...\n1. ... Rebbi?\n2. ... Rebbi Elazar ben Azaryah?\n3. ... Rebbi Yishmael ben Elisha?\n(c) Two of the three Talmidei-Chachamim listed by the Tana are ben Azai and ben Zoma.   Who is the third?\n(d) If one sees ben Zoma, he says, one can expect Chochmah.   What can one expect if one sees in a dream ...\n1. ... ben Azai?\n2. ... Acher?\n(e) Why can one expect punishment if one sees ...\n1. ... Rebbi Yishmael ben Elisha?\n2. ... Acher?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) Seeing Chayos in a dream is a good sign with three exceptions, a monkey an elephant and a Kipod.   What is a Kipod?\n(b) Why are they not a good sign?\n(c) How do we reconcile this with the statement of Mar that if one sees an elephant in a dream, he will experience a miracle ('Pele Na'aseh lo')?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Beraisa say about seeing any metal objects in a dream, with only three exceptions. Two of these are a hoe and an adze.   What is the third?\n(b) Why is this rule confined to where one sees them with their handles?\n(c) What is the sole exception to the rule that all ...\n1. ... fruit that one sees in a dream is good?\n2. ... vegetables are good?\n(d) How do we reconcile this with Rav, who claimed that he only became after he dreamt that he saw the heads of turnips?\n(e) Why is T'cheiles (dark blue) the only color that one dreams about that is not a good sign?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) In similar vein, what does the Tana say about 'Karya (a tawny-owl) Kifufa (an owl) and Kurpera'i (a mole)?\n(b) And what does he say ...\n1. ... about Gudganiyos (cherries), Kafniyos (an inferior species of date) and Pagei Temarah (dates that are not fully ripe)?\n2. ... in contrast, about bathing, anointing oneself and Tashmish?\n(c) In his list of three things that are akin to Olam ha'Ba, Shabbos, a shining sun and Tashmish, why can Tashmish not mean Tashmish ha'Mitah (as it did in the previous question?\n(d) Then what does it mean?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) Two of the three things that ...\n1. ... revive a person's spirits are someone singing a nice song and a beautiful sight.   What is the third?\n2. ... make him feel relaxed are a nice wife and a nice home.   What is the third?\n(b) What do the following five things have in common: fire, honey, Shabbos, sleep and a dream?\n(c) If ...\n1. ... fire is a sixtieth of Gehinom, what is honey a sixtieth of?\n2. ... Shabbos is a sixtieth of Olam ha'Ba, what is sleep a sixtieth of?\n(d) And of what is a dream a sixtieth?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) What do the following five things have in common: sneezing, perspiring, diarrhea, an emission and sleep?\n(b) What do we learn from the Pasuk in ...\n1. ... Iyov \"Atishosav Tahel Or\"?\n2. ... Bereishis \"be'Ze'as Aprcha Tochal Lechem\"?\n3. ... Yeshayah \"Maher Tzo'ah le'Hipase'ach ve'Lo Yamus la'Shachas\"?\n4. ... Yeshayah \"Yir'eh Zera, Ya'arich Yamim\"?\n5. ... Iyov \"Yashanti Az Yanu'ach li\"?\n(c) And what do we learn from the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"va'Tachlimeni ve'Hachyeini\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) Besides the fact that they all serve as a cure, what does the Beraisa say about the following six things: cabbage, beets, a dry Poli'ol (pennyroyal) plant and the stomach, womb and lobe of the liver of an animal?\n(b) What do others say about small fish, besides adding fish (even large ones) on to the previous list?\n(c) The first four items on the following list of ten things cited by the Tana are meat of an ox, fat (juicy) meat, roasted meat and meat of a bird.    What does he say about them?\n(d) Four out of the next five are a roasted egg, a shave, cress and milk.   What is the fifth?\n(e) What is the last item that harms a sick person?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q26",
        "label": "26)",
        "text": "(a) Some add nuts to the previous list.   What do others add?\n(b) What did Rebbi Yishmael say in a Beraisa about the word 'Kishu'in' that bears this out?\n(c) We query this from a statement of Rav Yehudah Amar Rav, to explain the Pasuk in Toldos \"Vayomer Hash-m lah (to Rivkah) 'Sh'nei Goyim be'Vitnech ... ' \".   How did he interpret \"Sh'nei Goyim\"? At whom does it hint?\n(d) How did he explain it in a way that clashes with Rebbi Yishmael?\n(e) How do we reconcile the two statements?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q27",
        "label": "27)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa discusses a dream that concerns a Meis.   What does it signify to dream that ...\n1. ... there is a Meis in the house?\n2. ... the Meis eats or drinks?\n(b) If the Meis takes 'vessels' from the house, it is a bad sign.   Which vessels is the Tana referring to according to Rav Papa?\n(c) What if the Meis takes anything else from the house?\n(d) The reason for the former is because - it is a sign that somebody else will be leave the house (in a coffin).\n(e) The two exceptions to the rule that whatever the Meis places in the house is a good sign are earth and mustard.   What does placing earth in the house indicate?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q28",
        "label": "28)",
        "text": "(a) In connection with the B'rachah that one recites over seeing the location where an idol was destroyed from our land (cited in our Mishnah), what does the Beraisa say about someone who sees ...\n1. ... the idol Markulis?\n2. ... the location from which Avodah-Zarah has been destroyed?\n(b) What does one say after adding ''and just as it has been destroyed from this location, so too, may it be destroyed from all other locations!'\n(c) Why, according to the Tana Kama, does one omit the final request in Chutz la'Aretz?\n(d) What does Rebbi Shimon ben Elazar say?\n(e) What has that to do with the Pasuk in Tzefanyah \"Az Ahafoch el Amim Safah Berurah\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q29",
        "label": "29)",
        "text": "(a) How many B'rachos does Rav Hamnuna require someone who sees the wicked (town of) Bavel to recite?\n(b) At which point does one recite 'Baruch ... she'Hechriv Bavel ha'Rish'ah'?\n(c) Which B'rachah does one recite upon seeing Nevuchadnetzar's house?\n(d) Which of two locations must one see before reciting  'Baruch she'Asah Nisim la'Tzadikim ba'Makom ha'Zeh'?\n(e) What is the significance of the furnace?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q30",
        "label": "30)",
        "text": "(a) When does one say 'Baruch ...\n1. ... she'Nasan Erech Apayim le'Ovrei Retzono'?\n2. ... Omer ve'Oseh Gozer u'Mekayem'?\n(b) According to one explanation, no animal can leave that area unless one places earth from there on to its back (a curse in itself).   What do others say?\n(c) According to the second explanation, how is that a bad sign?\n(d) What did Rava used to say to the donkeys he saw taking earth from there as he gave them a slap on the back?\n(e) And, based on the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"ve'Tei'teisiha be'Mat'atei Hashmed\", what did Mar b'rei de'Ravina used to do when he arrived in Bavel?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q31",
        "label": "31)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Ashi used to do even though he had not heard the ruling of Rav Hamnuna?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 58,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yirmiyah ben Elazar say about the curse of Bavel?\n(b) How does he learn it from the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"ve'Samtihah le'Morash Kipod ve'Agmei Mayim ... \"?\n(c) On which principle is it based?\n(d) What does the same Chacham say in contrast, about the curse of Shomron (as expressed in the Pasuk in Michah)?\n(e) What is the significance of Shomron?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Hamnuna rules that someone who sees Uchlusei Yisrael recites the B'rachah 'Baruch ... Chacham ha'Razim'.   How many people does 'Uchlusei Yisrael' incorporate?\n(b) What does the B'rachah mean?\n(c) When does one recite 'Bushah Im'chem ... '?\n(d) What dual reason does a supportive Beraisa give for Rav Hamnuna's first ruling?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Where was ben Zoma standing when he recited the B'rachah 'Baruch ... Chacham ha'Razim'?\n(b) What B'rachah did he add to that?\n(c) What advantage did he have over Adam ha'Rishon (after the curse) when it came to eating and obtaining clothes to wear?\n(d) After ...\n1. ... plowing, sowing, reaping, gathering into a pile, threshing and winnowing, what five things did Adam ha'Rishon still have to do himself before having bread to eat?\n2. ... shearing the wool, bleaching and combing it, which two things did he still have to perform himself before having clothes to wear?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) How did ben Zama obtain all his needs?\n(b) On what basis did they all come to him and not vice-versa?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) According to ben Zoma, what does ...\n1. ... a good guest say?\n2. ... a bad guest say?\n(b) About whom does the Pasuk in Iyov say ...\n1. ... \"Z'chor, ki Sasgi Pa'alo asher Shor'ru Anashim\"?\n2. ... \"Lachein Y'rei'uhu Anashim Lo Yir'eh Kol Chachmei Leiv\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) About whom is the Pasuk in Shmuel speaking when it writes \"ve'ha'Ish bi'Yemei Shaul Zakein Ba ba'Anashim\"?\n(b) According to the Beraisa, what is the minimum number of people that qualify as an Uchlusa?\n(c) At the head of how many followers did Yishai therefore go out, come in and Darshen?\n(d) What does the Beraisa also say about 'Uchlusa in Bavel'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What B'rachah should one recite upon seeing ...\n1. ... Chachmei Yisrael?\n2. ... Chachmei Akum?\n(b) And what B'rachah should a person recite upon seeing ...\n1. ... a Jewish king?\n2. ... a gentile king?\n(c) What did Rebbi Yochanan say one should do in order to see ...\n1. ... a Jewish king?\n2. ... a gentile king?\n(d) What is the reason for the latter?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Sheishes, who was blind, do, when everybody went to greet the king?\n(b) What did that Tzedoki remark to Rav Sheishes about whole and broken barrels going down to the river?\n(c) What did he mean by that?\n(d) What did Rav Sheishes reply?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rav Sheishes say when, as the first group of the king's men arrived amidst a fanfare, the Tzedoki remarked that the king had arrived?\n(b) How many times did this happen?\n(c) What did Rav Sheishes remark when the third group arrived amidst silence?\n(d) What did he initially reply to the Tzedoki's query how he knew?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Pasuk in Melachim (that Rav Sheishes quoted in reply to the Tzedoki) say about the storm-wind, the noise and the fire that passed before the Navi as he stood on the mountain?\n(b) When did Hash-m pass?\n(c) What was the name of the Navi?\n(d) What did the Tzedoki ask when Rav Sheishes recited the appropriate B'rachah?\n(e) Some say that the Tzedoki's friends poked out his eyes.   What do others say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Shilo do to the man who had relations with an Egyptian woman?\n(b) How did the latter react to that?\n(c) What did Rebbi Shilo reply when the group of king's men came to fetch him asked him why he gave the man Malkos?\n(d) What happened when he told the men that he had a witness who would testify to that effect?\n(e) And what did he reply when they asked him why he did not then sentence him to death?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) Which Pasuk in Divrei ha'Yamim did he recite whilst they were looking into the matter?\n(b) And what did he reply when they asked him what he was saying?\n(c) What did the king's men do when they heard how appreciative Rebbi Shilo was of their judicial system?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) How did he explain his actions to the man who asked him why Hash-m would perform miracles with someone who tells lies?\n(b) What did that Rasha intend to do?\n(c) Based on what principle did Rebbi Shilo therefore feel justified in killing him?\n(d) How did he do just that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) Why did Rebbi Shiloh then begin to Darshen the Pasuk \"L'cha Hash-m ha'Gedulah\"?\n(b) According to his explanation, based on ...\n1. ... the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Oseh Gedolos ad Ein Cheiker\", to which event does \"Gedulah\" refer?\n2. ... the words \"ha'Yad ha'Gedolah\" (in the Pasuk in Beshalach \"va'Yar Yisrael es ha'Yad he'Gedolah\"), to which event does ''Gevurah\" refer?\n3. ... the Pasuk in Yehoshua \"va'Yidom ha'Shemesh\", to which event does \"Tiferes\" refer?\n(c) Based on the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"ve'Yeiz Nitzcham al Begadai\", \"Netzach\" refers to the downfall of Rome.   Based on the Pasuk ...\n1. ... in Chukas \"Al kein Ye'amer be'Seifer Milchamos Hash-m es Vahev be'Sufah\", to which event does \"Hod' refer?\n2. ... in Shoftim \"Min Shamayim Nilchamu ha'Kochevim mi'Mesilosam ... \", to which battle does \"Ki Chol ba'Shamayim u'va'Aretz\" refer?\n(d) And based on the Pasuk ...\n1. ... in Ki Seitzei \"Ki Yad al Keis Kah ... \", to which event does \"L'cha Hash-m ha'Mamlachah\" refer?\n2. ... in Yechezkel \"Hin'ni eilecha Gog ... \", to which battle does \"ve'ha'Misnasei\" pertain?\n(e) What do all the above cases have in common?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) How did Rav Chanan bar Rava amar Rebbi Yochanan (or Rav) explain the words \"le'Chol le'Rosh\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) A Beraisa, citing Rebbi Akiva explains \"Gedulah\" with reference to K'ri'as Yam-Suf, and \"Gevurah\" with reference to Makas Bechoros.   In connection with which event does he explain \"Tif'eres\"?\n(b) If, according to him, \"Netzach\" refers to Yerushalayim, to which location does \"Hod\" refer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa now discusses the B'rachah that one had to recite over houses in Eretz Yisrael.   To which period is the Tana referring?\n(b) Over which houses did one recite 'Baruch Matziv G'vul Almanah'?\n(c) What did one say if one saw them in their state of destruction?\n(d) Over which houses did one recite the Pasuk ...\n1. ... in Mishlei \"Beis Ge'im Yisach Hash-m\"?\n2. ... in Tehilim \"Keil Nekamos Hash-m ... \"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) Ula queried Rav Chisda, who sighed upon seeing the house of Rav Chana bar Chanila'i, based on a statement of Rav.   What did Rav say, based on the Pasuk in Yechezkel \"ve'Atah ben-Adam, He'anach be'Shivron Masnayim\"?\n(b) What did Rebbi Yochanan say, based on another Pasuk there?\n(c) Which outstanding Midah of Rav Chana caused Rav Chisda to involuntarily sigh at the sight of his house?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) How many bakers were busy in Rav Chana bar Chanila'i's house both by day and by night to bake for the needy?\n(b) And why was his hand always on his purse?\n(c) How many entrances did his house have?\n(d) And what did Rav Chisda say about anybody who entered Rav Chana's house hungry?\n(e) Why did he used to throw wheat and barley into the street?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) How did Ula quoting the Pasuk in Yeshayah cited by Rebbi Yochanan, explain the strange phenomenon of such a Tzadik's house having become a ruin?\n(b) What did Rebbi Yochanan also say, based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Shir ha'Ma'alos le'David, ha'Botchim ba'Hashem ke'Har Tziyon\"?\n(c) How did Rav Chisda react to Ula's attempt to raise his spirits?\n(d) What did Ula mean when he concluded 'Dayo le'Eved Lih'yos ke'Rabo'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) Regarding which occasion does the Beraisa cite the B'rachah 'Baruch ... asher Yatzar eschem ba'Din ... '?\n(b) The B'rachah continues ve'Zan eschem ba'Din ve'Kilkel eschem ba'Din ve'Asaf eschem ba'Din\".   How does the first half of the B'rachah end?\n(c) Mar b'rei de'Ravina in the name of Rav Nachman adds \"ve'Yode'a Mispar Kulchem ve'Hu Asid le'Hachayoschem u'Lekayem eschem\".   How does the B'rachah end?\n(d) And in connection with which occasion does the Tana cite the Pasuk in Yirmiyah \"Bushah Imchem Me'od ... \"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi say one should recite upon seeing one's friend after a break of ...\n1. ... thirty days?\n2. ... twelve months?\n(b) What does Rav prove from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Nishkachti ke'Meis mi'Leiv Hayisi ki'Cheli Oveid\"?\n(c) What is the proof from there?\n(d) How can we also learn it from the Halachah regarding a lost article?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) Which two B'rachos did Rav Papa and Rav Huna b'rei de'Rav Yehoshua tell Rav Chanina b'rei de'Rav Ika they recited when they saw him?\n(b) Which third B'rachah did he tell them that he recited when he saw them?\n(c) Why did he do that?\n(d) What did they then say to him?\n(e) What happened next?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) Which B'rachah does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi require one to recite when one sees an albino?\n(b) We query this from a Beraisa however.   What does the Tana say one recites upon seeing someone who ...\n1. ... is black, red or very white-skinned?\n2. ... appears squashed on account of his fatness (or who is extremely tall and his face protrudes from his head), a dwarf or someone who is covered with warts (or who has a twisted mouth)?\n(c) And which B'rachah does he prescribe upon seeing someone ...\n1. ... whose hands have been cut off, who is blind or whose hair is completely matted?\n2. ... who is lame, who is a leper, or someone who is covered with freckles?\n(d) How do we reconcile Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi with the Beraisa?\n(e) From which case in the same list do we prove the answer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) Which B'rachah does the Beraisa require someone who sees an elephant or a monkey to recite?\n(b) Included in the list is a Kifof.   What is a 'Kifof'?\n(c) And what does the Tana say one should recite upon seeing beautiful creatures and nice-looking trees?\n(d) Shmuel describes the 'Zikin' in our Mishnah over which one recites 'Baruch ... she'Kocho u'Gevuraso Malei Olam' as shooting-stars.   What did he comment about the paths of Heaven and shooting-stars?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q26",
        "label": "26)",
        "text": "(a) How do we reconcile the fact that shooting-stars seem to pass Mazal K'sil with the tradition that it never does such a thing?\n(b) What would happen if they did pass K'sil?\n(c) How does Rav Huna b'rei de'Rav Yehoshua explain shooting-stars?\n(d) And how does Rav Ashi reconcile the Kashya from the tradition on the fact that the shooting-stars seemingly pass Mazal K'sil?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q27",
        "label": "27)",
        "text": "(a) What problem did Shmuel have with the two Pesukim \"Oseh Ash u'Kesil ve'Kimah\" (Amos) and \"Oseh Kimah u'Kesil\" (Iyov)?\n(b) What was his basic answer?\n(c) When does ...\n1. ... K'sil govern?\n2. ... Kimah govern?\n(d) What would happen to the world were it not for ...\n1. ... the heat of K'sil?\n2. ... the cold of Kimah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q28",
        "label": "28)",
        "text": "(a) What is another name for 'Kimah' (which is part of Mazal T'leh)?\n(b) What is 'Nahar di'Yenur'?\n(c) How does it weaken the power of Kimah/Akrav?\n(d) What would happen if that was not the case?\n(e) What was Hash-m referring to when He said to Iyov \"Did you tie up the bonds of Kimah, or did you unbind the cords of K'sil\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q29",
        "label": "29)",
        "text": "(a) According to Shmuel, what is 'Kimah' the acronym of?\n(b) Some say that this is referring to stars that are bunched together closely.   What do others say?\n(c) How does Rav Yehudah connect \"Ash\" (mentioned in the Pasuk that we cited earlier) with 'Yuta'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q30",
        "label": "30)",
        "text": "(a) Bearing in mind that the first two Mazalos are T'leh and Eglah, some say that 'Yuta' is the tail of Mazal T'leh, others say - that it is the head of\n(b) What is the significance of 'the tail of T'leh'?\n(c) What do we prove from the Pasuk there \"ve'Ayash al Banehah Tanchem\"?\n(d) What do we mean when we say that it resembles a 'Tarfa de'Mitrif'?\n(e) Why does Ayash therefore follow Kimah?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 59,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) When/Why did Hash-m take two stars from Mazal Kimah?\n(b) From where did He take two stars to fill in the gap?\n(c) One of the reasons that He did not simply replace what He took is based on the mantra that 'A Pit cannot be filled up with the earth that one took from it'.   What is the other reason?\n(d) Why did He not then simply create two new stars?\n(e) What did Rav Nachman learn from the Pasuk in Iyov \"ve'Ayish al Banehah Tanchem\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Ketina defines 'Zeva'os' in our Mishnah as Gohah.   What does 'Gohah' mean?\n(b) What happened as Rebbi Ketina on his travels was once passing the entrance of Uva Tamya's house?\n(c) What does 'Uva Tamya' mean?\n(d) How did Uva Tamya ...\n1. ... initially react, when Rebbi Ketina asked him whether he knew the cause of earthquakes?\n2. ... then explain it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) On what grounds did Rebbi Ketina object to Uva Tamya's explanation?\n(b) What did he say about Uva Tamya and his statements?\n(c) Why was his objection unjustified?\n(d) Then why did he raise it?\n(e) How did he himself explain an earthquake, based on the Pasuk in Yechezkel \"ve'Gam Ani Akeh Kapi el Kapi ... \"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) To what does ...\n1. ... Rebbi Nasan ascribe earthquakes, based on the Pasuk there \"ve'Hanichosi Chamasi bam ve'Hinechamti\"?\n2. ... the Rabbanan ascribe them, based on the Pasuk in Yirmiyah \"Heydad ke'Dorchim Ya'aneh el Kol Yoshvei ha'Aretz\"?\n3. ... Rav Acha bar Ya'akov ascribe them, based on the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"Koh Amar Hash-m 'ha'Shamayim Kis'i ve'ha'Aretz Hadom Raglai\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) The Gemara now discusses the source of thunder.   Based on the Pasuk in ...\n1. ... Tehilim \"Kol Ra'amcha ba'Galgal; He'iru Berakim Teivel ... \", what does Shmuel say?\n2. ... Yirmiyah \"le'Kol Tito Hamon Mayim ba'Shamayim\"?\n(b) Rav Acha bar Ya'akov attributes it to the lightning breaking off pieces of ice that has formed in the clouds.   To what does Rav Ashi attribute it?\n(c) On what grounds do we support the opinion of Rav Acha bar Ya'akov?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) Abaye defines 'Ruchos' in our Mishnah as Za'afa.   What does 'Za'afa' mean?\n(b) How do we query Abaye, who says that Za'afa never occurs at nighttime?\n(c) How do we resolve the problem?\n(d) What did Abaye also say that conforms with the Pasuk in Nachum \"Lo Sakum Pa'amayim Tzarah\"?\n(e) How do we reconcile this with the fact that storm-winds sometimes do last longer than two hours?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) Rava defines B'rakim in our Mishnah as Barka.   What is 'Barka'?\n(b) And what does he say about ...\n1. ... a single flash of lightning and about white and green lightning?\n2. ... clouds that come from the west but that appear to come from the south and two clouds that approach each other?\n(c) Why does Rava consider it important to tell us this?\n(d) When does this apply? On what condition should one not worry about them?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Shmuel bar Yitzchak, based on the Pasuk in Hoshe'a (said ruefully) \"ve'Chasd'chem ka'Anan Boker\" say about morning clouds?\n(b) Rav Papa queried this from a well-known saying about someone who opens his front door in the morning and is greeted by rain.   Who is the mantra addressing?\n(c) What does it advise him to do?\n(d) How did Abaye answer Rav Papa?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"ve'ha'Elokim Asah she'Yir'u mi'Lefanav\", what did Rebbi Alexandri quoting Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi give as the main objective of thunder?\n(b) What did he also say someone who sees a rainbow should do, based on what the Navi Yechezkel did when he saw one?\n(c) Why is that?\n(d) Then why did they react to that in Eretz Yisrael by cursing the statement?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) They agreed however, that one recites the B'rachah 'Baruch ... Zocher ha'Beris' upon seeing a rainbow.   What did the Beraisa add to that?\n(b) What did Rav Papa therefore conclude?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) How do we query the Mishnah, which requires the B'rachah of 'Baruch ... Oseh Ma'aseh Berishis\" over mountains and hilltops, based on the Pasuk in Tehilim, \"Berakim la'Matar Asah\"?\n(b) What does Abaye mean when he answers 'K'roch ve'Tani'?\n(c) How does Rava modify Abaye's answer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi say one should recite upon seeing a clear sky?\n(b) Why is that?\n(c) To what occasion does Abaye restrict this ruling?\n(d) Rafram bar Papa Amar Rav Chisda disagrees with Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi however.   What does he say, based on the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"Albish Shamayim Kidros, ve'Sak Asim Kesusah\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa now discusses the B'rachah that one recites upon seeing the sun in its Tekufah, the moon in its strength, the stars in their paths and the Mazalos in their correct formation.    What does 'the sun in its Tekufah' mean?\n(b) How often does this take place, according to Abaye?\n(c) On what date and time does it take place?\n(d) Which B'rachah do we recite then?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) What is the significance of 'Shab'sa'i' in this connection?\n(b) The order in which the seven Mazalaos appear during the first hour of each night of the week, starting with Motza'ei Shabbos is 'Katznash Chalam'.   What does 'Katznash Chalam' stand for?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) The Mishnah required a B'rachah over the sea on occasions.   How does Rami bar Aba Amar Rebbi Yitzchak interpret 'on occasions'?\n(b) And what did Rami bar Aba Amar Rebbi Yitzchak say about someone who sees the River P'ras from the bridge of Bavel?\n(c) Why not beyond that point?\n(d) What do we comment about bei Shavur and beyond, and Rav Yosef about Ihi de'Kira and beyond?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) Rami bar Aba also said that someone who sees the River Diglas from the bridge of Shevist'na should recite 'Baruch ... she'Oseh Ma'aseh Bereishis'.   What does the Torah call the River Diglas?\n(b) What, according to Rav Ashi, is 'Chidekel' the acronym of?\n(c) And o0f what is 'P'ras' the acronym?\n(d) To what did Rava attribute the fact that the residents of Mechuza ...\n1. ... who lived on the banks of the Chidekel, were smart?\n2. ... had a red tint?\n(e) And why did their eyes tend to dart around?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) We query the ruling in our Mishnah to recite 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv' over rain, from statements starting with that of Rebbi Avahu (or of a Beraisa).  What did he mean when he said that one recites a B'rachah over the first rain when 'the Chasan goes to meet the Kalah'?\n(b) What did Rav Yehudah say that one must recite?\n(c) Rebbi Yochanan adds 'Ilu Finu Malei Shirah ka'Yam ...Ein Anu Maspikin Lehodos l'Cha ... ' (as we say in Nishmas).  What are the last words that one should say before the final B'rachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) What problem do we have with the wording of the final B'rachah 'Rov ha'Hoda'os'?\n(b) How do we therefore amend it?\n(c) What does Rav Papa therefore conclude?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) In any event, we see that over rain one recites 'Modim Anachnu Lach\".   How do we reconcile this with our Mishnah which prescribes the B'rachah of 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv'?\n(b) We query this from the B'rachah over good news.   Which B'rachah does the Mishnah prescribe for good news?\n(c) What is now the problem?\n(d) We therefore conclude that both are speaking where one saw the rain, and it depends on the size of the rainfall.   What exactly is the answer?\n(e) Alternatively, both speak where a lot of rain fell.   On what condition will one nevertheless recite 'Modim Anachnu Lach ... ', and not 'Baruch ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) We query the above answer from a Beraisa however.   What B'rachah does the Tana require one to recite over a new house?\n(b) How do we establish the case on order to reconcile that with the previous answer?\n(c) The Beraisa that we cite in support of this answer begins with words 'Katzro shel Davar'.   What does this mean?\n(d) And what does the Tana mean when he draws a distinction between 'al she'Lo' and 'al she'lo ve'al shel Chavero'?\n(e) And how do we reconcile this with the Beraisa, which obligates someone who hears that his wife has given birth to a boy and who is obligated to recite 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv' even though nobody else is involved?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) We also query the previous answer from the Beraisa which discusses someone whose father dies.   Which two B'rachos must he then recite?\n(b) What is the significance of 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv'?\n(c) According to the above answer, why does he recite 'ha'Tov ve'ha'Meitiv' and not 'Shehechiyanu'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) We query the above answer once more from a statement of Rav Yosef bar Aba in connection with the Beraisa which discusses someone who drinks a bottle of fresh superior wine or who continues to drink in a different location.    What does the Tana say about ...\n1. ... the former?\n2. ... the latter?\n(b) What did Rav Yosef bar Aba Amar Rebbi Yochanan comment in connection with the former?\n(c) How do we establish the case in order to reconcile it with the earlier ruling?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rav Huna restrict the ruling of our Mishnah that over a new house or new clothes one recites 'Shehechiyanu'?\n(b) What does Rebbi Yochanan say?\n(c) What can we extrapolate from both opinions regarding someone who purchases a similar house or vessels to the house or vessels that he already purchased?\n(d) Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) According to the second Lashon, Rav Huna restricts the Mishnah's ruling to where one did not purchase a similar house or vessels to the first one/s.   What does Rebbi Yochanan say?\n(b) What can we extrapolate with regard to someone who purchases a house or vessels that are similar to those that he already owns?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 60,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Querying the second Lashon, we cite a Beraisa, which discusses a Machlokes between Rebbi Meir and Rebbi Yehudah regarding the current issue.   What distinction does Rebbi Meir draw between someone who purchases a house or clothes when they are not similar to the one/s that he already owns and when they are?\n(b) What does Rebbi Yehudah say?\n(c) How does the first Lashon conform completely with the Beraisa?\n(d) Like which Tana does Rav Huna in the second Lashon hold?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) What is then the problem with Rebbi Yochanan in the second Lashon?\n(b) To answer the Kashya, how do we explain Rebbi Yehudah ('Kanah ve'Yesh lo Nami Tzarich Levarech')?\n(c) Then why do they argue by 'Yesh lo ve'Kanah' and not by 'Kanah ve'Chazar ve'Kanah'?\n(d) Based on which principle do they rather argue there than over a case where he purchased twice in order to teach us that even there, Rebbi Yehudah requires a B'rachah?\n(e) Which Heter is this referring to?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Our Mishnah requires a B'rachah over 'bad that resembles good' and over 'good that resembles bad'.    What is an example of ...\n1. ... 'bad that resembles good'?\n2. ... 'good that resembles bad'?\n(b) Rav Yosef queries our Mishnah, which declares a Tefilah that one's wife gives birth to a boy futile from the Pasuk \"va'Achar Yaldah Bas, Vatikra es Sh'mah Dinah\".\n(c) About whom is the Pasuk speaking?\n(d) What results did Le'ah's Tefilah produce?\n(e) What is now the problem?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) One answer is that one cannot ask from miracles.   What is the other?\n(b) This latter answer is based on a Beraisa, which advises one to Daven five different Tefilos during the course of the pregnancy.   What should one Daven for during ...\n1. ... the first three days?\n2. ... from three days till forty?\n(c) If between forty days and three months one Davens that the baby should not become a 'Sandal' (flattened), what should one Daven between ...\n1. ... three and six months?\n2. ... six and nine months?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) We query the Tana's advice to Daven from three days till forty that the baby should be a boy from a statement of Rebbi Yitzchak b'rei de'Rav Ami.   Based on the Pasuk in Tazri'a \"Ishah ki Sazri'a ve'Yaldah Zachar\" what will be the gender of the baby assuming that it is ...\n1. ... the man who is 'Mazri'a' first?\n2. ... the woman who is 'Mazri'a' first?\n(b) What is now the problem?\n(c) To solve the problem, how do we establish the Beraisa?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa cites Hillel ha'Zakein, who once heard a scream as he re-entered his hometown after a journey out of town.   What did he declare, based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"mi'Shemu'ah Ra'ah Lo Yiyra\"?\n(b) How does the Pasuk end?\n(c) Rava states that one can Darshen the Pasuk whichever way one wishes.   How can one Darshen it from the ..\n1. ... Seifa to the Reisha?\n2. ... Reisha to the Seifa?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) Where was Rebbi Yishmael b'Rebbi Yossi walking when he noticed that a certain Talmid who was accompanying him was afraid?\n(b) What did he comment, based on the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"Pachdu be'Tziyon Chata'im ... \"?\n(c) What did he reply when the Talmid cited him the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Ashrei Adam Mefached Tamid\"?\n(d) What did Rav Hamnuna say to Rav Yehudah bar Nasan (based on the Pasuk in Iyov \"Ki Pachad Pachadti ve'Ye'esayeini, va'asher Yagorti Yavo li\") who was walking behind him, when the latter sighed?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Based on ben Azai in our Mishnah (who requires two Tefilos upon entering a city and two upon leaving), if a person who is about to ...\n1. ... enter the city says 'Y'hi Ratzon mi'Lefanecha Hash-m Elokai she'Tachniseini li'K'erach Zeh le'Shalom', what does he say once he has entered it safely?\n2. ... leave the city says 'Y'hi Ratzon mi'Lefanecha Hash-m Elokai v'Elokei Avosai she'Totzi'eni mi'Kerach zeh le'Shalom', what does he say once he has left it safely?\n(b) According to Rav Masna, the above is confined to a city where they kill a person without judging him fairly.  Why, if they do, are the above Tefilos not necessary?\n(c) According to the second Lashon, either way, one must recite the Tefilos.   Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa presents a somewhat similar Tefilah that one recites upon entering a bathhouse and upon leaving it safely.   What objection does Abaye raise to the addition 've'Im Ye'era bi Takalah ve'Avon T'hei Misasi Kaparah le'Chol Avonosai!'?\n(b) This is based on a statement of Resh Lakish and the Tana quoting Rebbi Yossi.   How did Rav Yosef learn it from Pesukim in Yeshayah? What does the Pasuk in Yeshayah say?\n(c) According to Rav Acha, what does one say upon leaving the bathhouse without mishap?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What happened once to Rebbi Avahu whilst he was bathing in the bathhouse?\n(b) How was he miraculously saved?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) How many people did Rebbi Avahu manage to save at the same time?\n(b) How did he do it?\n(c) What do we mean when we conclude 'Haynu de'Rav Acha'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) On what occasion does the Tana require a person to say 'Y'hi Ratzon ... she'Yehei Eisek Zeh li li'Refu'ah'?\n(b) How does the Tefilah end (See Hagahos ha'G'ra)?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) If one 'ought not to indulge in cures', then why do we?\n(b) What does Abaye comment on the previous statement, based on a statement of Tana de'Bei Rebbi Yishmael?\n(c) What does Tana de'Bei Rebbi Yishmael learn from the Pasuk in Mishpatim \"ve'Rapo Yerapei\"?\n(d) What should one say when one gets up from a session of Hakazas ha'Dam?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) On what occasion does the Beraisa require one to say 'Hiskabdu Mechubadim, Mesharsei T'nu Kavod l'Elokei Yisrael ... '?\n(b) To whom does one say it?\n(c) How does his statement continue?\n(d) On what grounds does Abaye object to that text?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) According to Abaye, one's opening words are  'Shamruni, Azruni, Samchuni, Hamtinu li ... '.   How many times does one repeat each of these words?\n(b) How does one conclude?\n(c) And what does one say upon leaving the bathroom?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) According to the G'ra, the text ends 'I Efshar La'amod Afilu Sha'ah Echas'.  On what grounds does Shmuel object to Rav's version of the conclusion 'Baruch ... Rofei Cholim'?\n(b) With what does he replace the two final words?\n(c) What does Rav Sheishes add to that?\n(d) How does Rav Papa therefore present the final B'rachah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) In the current B'rachah, to what do the following words refer ...\n1. ... 'she'Im Yipase'ach Echad meihem'?\n2. ... 'O Im Yisasem Echad meihem'?\n3. ... Rofei Chol Basar'?\n4. ... 'u'Mafli La'asos'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) Which Parshah does the Beraisa prescribe before going to sleep?\n(b) What are the opening words of the B'rachah that one then recites?\n(c) What is the meaning of the words 'u'Sehei Mitasi Sheleimah' that we say in the middle of the B'rachah??\n(d) How does the B'rachah end?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) What are the opening words of the B'rachah that one recites upon waking up in the morning?\n(b) How does the B'rachah end?\n(c) What B'rachah does one recite when one ...\n1. ... hears the cock crow? What is a 'Sechvi'?\n2. ... opens one's eyes?\n3. ... sits up?\n(d) Upon getting dressed, one recites the b'rachah ' ... Malbish Arumim, and upon sitting up straight, Zokef Kefufim.   What B'rachah does one recite when stepping on to the floor in the morning?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) If one recites ...\n1. ... ' ... asher Heichin Mitz'adei Gaver' when one begins to walk, what B'rachah does one recite when putting on one's shoes?\n2. ... 'Ozer Yisrael bi'Gevurah' when tying one's belt, what B'rachah does one recite when puts on one's Sudar (head-gear)?\n(b) The Tana also teaches us what B'rachah to recite when putting on one's Tallis and Tefilin and when washing one's hands.  What B'rachah does one recite when washing one's face in the morning?\n(c) How does the B'rachah end?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) How do we initially interpret the Mishnah's ruling that 'just as one recites a B'rachah over good new, so too, must one recite a B'rachah over bad news'?\n(b) What problem do we have with that?\n(c) How does Rava therefore re-interpret it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) How does ...\n1. ... Rav Acha in the name of Rebbi Levi learn the same thing from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Chesed u'Mishpat Ashirah, L'cha Hash-m Ashirah\"?\n2. ... Shmuel bar Nachmeni learn it from the Pasuk there \"ba'Hashem Ahalel Davar, b'Elokim Ahalel Davar\"?\n(b) Rebbi Tanchum learns it from the Pasuk there \"Kos Yeshu'os Esa u've'Shem Hash-m Ekra\".   Which is the second Pasuk denoting 'bad news' which ends in the same way?\n(c) Whereas the Rabbanan learn it from the Pasuk in Iyov \"Hash-m Nasan va'Hashem Lakach ... \".   How does the Pasuk end?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav Huna ... in the name of Rebbi Meir and a Beraisa in the name of Rebbi Akiva advise one to say constantly?\n(b) And the Tana illustrates this with the well-know story of Rebbi Akiva who was once traveling when he arrived at a town.   What response did he receive when he attempted to find lodgings for the night?\n(c) Where did he therefore spend the night?\n(d) Two of the three things that he had with him were a rooster and a donkey.   What was the third?\n(e) The first to go was the lamp, which was blown out by the wind.   What happened to his ...\n1. ... rooster?\n2. ... donkey?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Akiva declare following each of the four mishaps that he experienced?\n(b) What calamity happened overnight\n(c) What did Rebbi Akiva subsequently say to his Talmidim?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 61,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav Huna Amar Rav quoting Rebbi Meir learn from the Pasuk in Koheles \"Al Tevahel Al Picha ... \"?\n(b) And what reason does the Pasuk go on to give as to why one should be careful what one says before Hash-m?\n(c) What does Rav Nachman bar Rav Chisda initially learn from the two 'Yudin' in the word \"va'Yitzer\" (in the Pasuk in Bereishis \"va'Yitzer Hash-m Elokim es ha'Adam\"?\n(d) How does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak query this from the fact that the same does not appear in connection with the creation of animals?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) We therefore Darshen the two 'Yudin' in \"va'Yitzer\" like Rebbi Shimon ben Pazi, who Darshens 'Oy li mi'Yitzri, O li mi'Yotzri'.   What does this mean?\n(b) Alternatively, we Darshen it like Rebbi Yirmiyah ben Elazar.   What did Rebbi Yirmiyah ben Elazar Darshen, based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Achor va'Kedem Tzartani\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) Rav and Shmuel argue over the Pasuk \"And Hash-m Elokim built the Tzeila which he took from Adam into a woman.   One of them translates \"Tzeila\" as a body.   How does the other one translate it?\n(b) The second opinion explains the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Achor va'Kedem Tzartani\" like Rebbi Ami.   How does Rebbi Ami explain it?\n(c) 'Achor le'Ma'aseh Bereishis' fits nicely, with reference to the fact that Adam was created on Friday afternoon; but what does 'Kedem le'Pur'anus' refer to'?\n(d) It cannot refer to the punishment of Adam and Chavah's sin based on Rebbi in a Beraisa.   What does Rebbi learn from the Pasuk ...\n1. ... in Shemini \"Vayedaber Moshe el Aharon ve'el Elazar ve'el Isamar Banav ha'Nosarim 'K'chu es ha'Minchah ... ' \"?\n2. ... in Bereishis with reference to the punishment meted out to Adam, Chavah and the snake?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) How will the opinion that \"Tzela\" means 'a tail' explain the extra 'Yud' in \"va'Yitzer\"?\n(b) And he explains the Pasuk there \"Zachar u'Nekeivah Bera'am\" like Rebbi Avahu.  What problem does Rebbi Avahu have with this from the Pasuk (also in Bereishis) \" ...  ki be'Tzelem Elokim Asah es ha'Adam\"?\n(c) How does he resolve the discrepancy?\n(d) And how does Rebbi Yirmiyah (Rav Z'vid or Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak) explain the Pasuk \"va'Yiven Basar Tachtenah\", according to this opinion (seeing as Adam's body was fully structured?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What is the problem with the same Pasuk, according to the opinion that \"Tzela\" means a body?\n(b) How does Rebbi Shimon ben Menasyah resolve it?\n(c) What is the connection between 'Binyan' and plaiting?\n(d) Alternatively, we explain the Pasuk like Rav Chisda (or the Tana in a Beraisa), who explains 'building' to mean 'like a storehouse'.   What does he mean by that?\n(e) Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yirmiyah ben Elazar learn from the Pasuk there (in connection with Chavah) \"va'Yevi'ehah el ha'Adam\"?\n(b) What can we learn from this?\n(c) Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak proves that, according to the opinion that \"Tzeila\" means a body, Adam must have gone in front from a Beraisa.   What does the Tana there say?\n(d) What does the Beraisa say about ...\n1. ... walking behind a woman, even if it is his wife who is walking in front of him on a bridge?\n2. ... someone who crosses a river behind a woman?\n(e) Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) What does another Beraisa say about someone who counts money from his hand into the hand of a woman, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Yad le'Yad Lo Yinakeh Ra\"?\n(b) On what condition do they say this?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rav Nachman extrapolate from the Pasuk in Shoftim \"ve'Yeilech Mano'ach Acharei Ishto\"?\n(b) How does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak query this from Elkanah and and Elisha?\n(c) How does he therefore interpret all three Pesukim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav Nachman's initial criticism of Mano'ach, what does Rav Ashi comment about the extent of his ignorance?\n(b) What ought he to have learned from Rivkah?\n(c) What is then the definition of an Am ha'Aretz?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Yochanan say that one should walk behind rather than ...\n1. ... a woman?\n2. ... a Nochri?\n3. ... a Shul when the Tzibur are Davening?\n(b) On what condition may one walk behind a Shul ... even if ...\n1. ... one is not carrying a load?\n2. ... there is no other entrance?\n3. ... one is not riding a donkey?\n(c) Why is it permitted to pass by the entrance of the Shul in any one of these four cases?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav, based on a Pasuk in Mishlei (\"Zevuvei Maves Yav'ish ... \") the Yeitzer-ha'Ra is compared to a fly.   Where is it situated?\n(b) What is it compared to according to Shmuel?\n(c) How does he learn this from the Pasuk in Bereishis (in connection with Hash-m's message to Kayin) \"la'Pesach Chatas Roveitz\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What purpose do a person's two kidneys serve?\n(b) Which kidney is presumably the one that advises him to do good?\n(c) On which Pasuk in Mishlei is this based?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa defines the functions of most of a person's major limbs.   If the kidneys advise, what does the heart do?\n(b) If a person's mouth finalizes a person's speech, what function does his tongue serve?\n(c) The esophagus takes in the food that one eats and lets it out, what is the function of ...\n1. ... the wind-pipe?\n2. ... the lungs?\n3. ... the liver?\n(d) The Marah (the gall) throws a drop into the liver.  What does it achieve?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) What function does the spleen play?\n(b) If the Kurk'van (the equivalent of a bird's craw) grinds a person's food, and the Keivah (the stomach) brings on sleep, what does the nose do?\n(c) What happens if the latter two switch roles?\n(d) What does the Tosefta say about a case where both of them remain awake or both sleep?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yossi ha'Gelili in a Beraisa learn from the Pasuk in Tehilim ...\n1. ... (in connection with Tzadikim) \"ve'Libi Chalal be'Kirbi\"?\n2. ... \"Ne'um Pesha la'Rasha be'Kerev Libi Ein Pachad Elokim le'Neged Einai\"?\n(b) And what does he learn from the word \"mi'Shoftei\" (in the plural) in the Pasuk there \"Ki Ya'amod li'Yemin Evyon Lehoshi'a mi'Shoftei Nafsho\"?\n(c) What did Abaye comment when Rava (or Rabah) claimed that people like himself fall under the category of Benonim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rava say about the world? For whom was it created?\n(b) What did he mean by that?\n(c) And what did he say a person should know about himself?\n(d) As examples of Rava's statement, for whose benefit did Rav attribute the creation of ...\n1. ... the World to Come?\n2. ... this world?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) To decipher n the corollary between ... \"be'Chol Nafsh'cha\" and \"be'Chol Me'odecha\", how does Rebbi Eliezer, in a Beraisa, explain \"be'Chol ...\n1. ... Nafsh'cha\"?\n2. ... Me'odecha\"?\n(b) How does Rebbi Akiva explain \"be'Chol Nafsh'cha\"?\n(c) Alternatively (See Mesores ha'Shas), on what grounds does Rebbi Akiva decline to interpret \"be'Chol Nafsh'cha\" with regard to sacrificing one's money?\n(d) How does he therefore interpret it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) What did Papus ben Yehudah once find Rebbi Akiva doing, in spite of the Romana' decree prohibiting Torah-study?\n(b) What did he ask Rebbi Akiva?\n(c) With what famous Mashal did Rebbi Akiva answer him?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) What did the fish reply when the fox asked them why they were constantly darting from one place to another?\n(b) Despite the fox's renown for being the wisest of creatures, why did the fish consider him foolish?\n(c) Based on the Pasuk in Nitzavim \"ki Hi Chayecha ve'Orech Yamecha\", how did Rebbi Akiva conclude his message to Papus?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) What happened to Rebbi Akiva shortly after that?\n(b) Who subsequently joined him in jail?\n(c) What did Papus comment when Rabbi Akiva asked him what he was doing in jail?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) At what time of day did they take Rebbi Akiva out to be killed?\n(b) What was he doing even as they tore off his flesh with iron combs?\n(c) What did he answer when his Talmidim asked him how he could possibly do such a thing?\n(d) At which point did his soul leave his body?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) What did a Heavenly Voice announce at that moment?\n(b) What was the angels' basic question when they asked 'Zu Torah ve'Zu S'charah'?\n(c) What did Hash-m answer them?\n(d) What did a second Heavenly Voice proclaim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Yehudah Amar Rav qualifies the ruling in our Mishnah forbidding a person to behave in a lighthearted manner opposite the Eastern Gate.  From which point and onwards does he permit it?\n(b) Which other condition does he require for it to be forbidden?\n(c) In whose name does Rebbi Chiya bar Aba say the same thing?\n(d) Besides there being no wall between the Eastern Gate and the location where one is, what other condition does he require for the prohibition to take effect?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa requires someone who defecates in Yehudah to do so facing north to south, and not east to west.   What is the reason for this?\n(b) What if he defecates in the Galil?\n(c) On what condition may one not defecate facing north to south in Yehudah?\n(d) What does Rebbi Yossi say about this?\n(e) The Chachamim forbid it.   What is the difference between the Tana Kama and the Chachamim? In which point is the Tana Kama more stringent than the Chachamim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) In another Beraisa, Rebbi Yossi only requires 'Ro'eh.   Which of the above conditions does Rebbi Yehudah require?\n(b) What is the difference between the opinion of Rebbi Akiva, who says 'be'Chol Makom' and the Tana Kama? In which point is he more stringent than the Tana Kama?\n(c) How did Rabah arrange the bricks of his make-shift toilet in Bavel to enable himself to sit facing north to south?\n(d) On what basis did Abaye rearrange the direction of the bricks?\n(e) Why did this upset Rabah?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 62,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) Where did Rebbi Akiva once follow his Rebbe, Rebbi Eliezer?\n(b) The first thing he learned from him was that one may not face east to west when relieving oneself, only north to south.   Whereabouts in Eretz Yisrael did this episode take place?\n(c) The second thing he learned was that one may not relieve oneself standing, only sitting.   Which third thing did he learn from him concerning which hand to use when cleaning oneself?\n(d) What did Rebbi Akiva reply when ben Azai accused him of Chutzpah?\n(e) ben Azai seems to have accepted Rebbi Akiva's reply, since he did the same to him (Rebbi Akiva) as he did to Rebbi Eliezer.   What did ben Azai ...\n1. ... learn from Rebbi Akiva?\n2. ... reply when Rebbi Yehudah accused him of Chutzpah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) In similar fashion, where did Rav Kahana once go to lie down?\n(b) Which two things did Rav do before being intimate with his wife?\n(c) What did Rav Kahana comment?\n(d) How did Rav ...\n1. ... react to this?\n2. ... Kahana react to Rav's orders?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What reason does Rava give to explain why, after relieving oneself, one cleans oneself with one's left hand, and not with the right one, based on the Pasuk in ve'Zos ha'Berachah \"mi'Yemino Eish Das lamo\"?\n(b) According to Rabah bar bar Chanah, it is because one often places it in the mouth (e.g. whilst eating) eats with the right hand.   What does Resh Lakish say, based on the Mitzvah of Tefilin?\n(c) The last reason, connected with Leining, is that of Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak.   What does he say?\n(d) A similar Machlokes exists among the Tana'im ion a Beraisa, where Rebbi Eliezer explains that one eats with the right hand and Rebbi Yehoshua, because one writes Torah with it.   What does Rebbi Akiva say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rebbi Tanchum bar Chanila'i, two of the dangers that anyone who is discreet in the bathroom is saved from are snakes and scorpions.   What is the third?\n(b) From what other unpleasant thing do others say he is he spared?\n(c) What used to happen even when two people would enter a certain bathroom in Teverya?\n(d) To which two things did Rebbi Ami and Rebbi Asi attribute the fact that nothing happened to them even when they went in alone?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) From where did Rebbi Ami and Rebbi Asi learn the previous 'Segulah'?\n(b) What tradition did they also have as regards suffering? What are the best two antidotes against to alleviate it?\n(c) What did Abaye's nanny do to prevent the Mazikin from attacking him in the bathroom?\n(d) Why a lamb and not a goat?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) Whenever Rava went to the bathroom, Rav Chisda's daughter used to place a nut in a copper jar.   Who was Rav Chisda's daughter?\n(b) What did she ...\n1. ... do with it?\n2. ... achieve by doing it?\n(c) This is what she used to do before he became Rosh Yeshivah.   What did she do after he became Rosh Yeshivah?\n(d) Why did he need more protection afterwards?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) According to Ula, someone who defecates behind a wall does not need to distance himself any further.   What if he needs to do so in an open field?\n(b) Isi bar Nasan is more stringent.  What does he say?\n(c) We query Isi from the Mishnah in Taharos which discusses a guard in an olive-press.   What are the ramifications of the ruling that permits the guard to defecate immediately behind a wall that is in front of the olive-press?\n(d) How do we reconcile Isi's former ruling with the Mishnah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Similarly, we query Isi from the same Mishnah, which discusses a guard who leaves the olive-press to defecate.   How far away may he be from the olive-press for the oil to remain Tahor?\n(b) How do we reconcile Isi's latter ruling with the Mishnah?\n(c) How does Rav Ashi explain Isi's ruling ('so that he doesn't see him') to answer the latter Kashya simply?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) How did Rav Nachman, based on a Beraisa, react when a Safdan (eulogizer) praised a deceased person in that he was a Tzanu'a (discreet) in his behavior?\n(b) How does the Tana there define a 'Tzanu'a'?\n(c) Why, based on another Beraisa, did the words of that Safdan bother Rav Nachman? What did the Tana there say?\n(d) Who, besides the Safdan, is punished for a eulogy that is undeserved?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) How does another Tana define a Tzanu'a (in connection with someone who defecates)?\n(b) We query this from a statement of Rav Yehudah.   What does Rav Yehudah Amar Rav say about relieving oneself early in the morning and late at night?\n(c) We also query the Beraisa from Rebbi Zeira and from Rava, who used to travel a Mil out of town to relieve himself by day.   What did ...\n1. ... Rava instruct his servant to do at night?\n2. ... Rebbi Zeira instruct his servant to do at night?\n(d) How do we therefore amend the words 'in the same location' in the Beraisa?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) We already cited Rav Yehudah Amar Rav who says that one should relieve oneself early in the morning and at night, in order not to need to travel for (during the day).   What does ben Azai in a Beraisa say about that?\n(b) Why does he also say that one should open one's bowels ('Meshamesh' [with a clod of earth or with a small twig]) and then sit down, and not vice-versa?\n(c) Why can 'Meshamesh' not mean 'clean the seat'?\n(d) On what condition does the Tana advise one to say 'Lo li Lo li, Lo Tachim ve'Lo Tachtim, Lo Hani ve;Lo me'Hani, Lo Charshi de'Charsha ve'Lo Charshi de'Charsh'sa'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) ben Azai in a Beraisa says that one should not lie on the ground (because of the cold).   Why does he say that one should not sit on a (high) beam?\n(b) How does Shmuel describe sleep at dawn-break?\n(c) What else does he describe in the same way?\n(d) For how much did bar Kapara sell his pieces of advice?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) Why should one eat whilst one is still hungry?\n(b) What similar piece of advice did bar Kapar add to that?\n(c) What did he mean when he said 'Pour whilst the pot is hot!'\n(d) What does the sound of a horn blowing in Rome signify?\n(e) What should the son of a fig-salesman then do if his father is not at home?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) What did Abaye instruct the Rabbanan not to do, when they traversed the alleyways of Mechuza on their way to the fields?\n(b) Why was that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) How did Rav Safra respond, when Rebbi Aba came and coughed outside the bathroom (which had no door) where he was relieving himself?\n(b) Afterwards, Rebbi Aba, taking Rav Safra to task, based on the Mishnah in Tamid, compared him to the residents of Se'ir.   Which Midah of the b'nei Se'ir was he referring to?\n(c) Which Mishnah in Tamid was he referring to?\n(d) What did he extrapolate from there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) Based on a Beraisa, what did Rav Safra think, when he told Rebbi Aba to come in?\n(b) Raban Shimon ben Gamliel there states that not urinating when necessary leads to Hidrokon, and not defecating ... to Yerakon.   What is ...\n1. ... 'Hidrakon'?\n2. ... 'Yerakon'?\n(c) How did Rebbi Elazar react when a Persian once knocked at the door of the bathroom that he was using?\n(d) What happened to the Persian?\n(e) Rebbi Elazar applied to himself the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"va'Etein Adam Tachtecha\"? How did he interpret the Pasuk?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) About whom does the Pasuk in Shmuel write \"ve'Amar Lehorg'cha va'Techas alecha\"?\n(b) What are the two problems with the Pasuk? What ought the Navi to have written?\n(c) To whom does 've'Amar' then refer? Why was Shaul ha'Melech Chayav Misah?\n(d) And to whom does \"va'Techas\" refer? What merit did Shaul have that saved him from being killed?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) How does the Beraisa now explain the Pasuk there \"Vayavo el Gidros ha'Tzon ... ve'Sham Me'arah\"?\n(b) And how does Rebbi Elazar explain the phrase (in the same Pasuk) \"le'Hasech es Raglav\"?\n(c) What does Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina say about someone who treats clothes with disrespect?\n(d) How does this explain the fact that, in David's later years, his clothes did not keep him warm?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) What was wrong with David's statement to Shaul \"If Hash-m incited you against me, may He accept my prayers and remove your anger\"?\n(b) How did Hash-m respond to that?\n(c) What did David subsequently do wrong?\n(d) The Pasuk in Shmuel relates how the ensuing plague of pestilence began in the morning, and ended at \"Eis Mo'ed\", which according to the elder Shmuel in the name of his father-in-law Rebb Chanina, means from the time that they Shechted the Korban Tamid until they sprinkled its blood.   How does Rebbi Yochanan interpret \"ad Eis Mo'ed\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) According to Rav citing Rebbi Elazar, why did Hash-m instruct the Angel of Death to take their greatest sage.   Whom did the Angel of death choose?\n(b) To whom was Avishai ben Tzeruyah compared?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) Initially, four Amora'im argue over what the Pasuk is referring to when it writes that \"Hash-m retracted (from the decree) because He saw ... \". According to Rav, based on the Pasuk \"Vayomer Ya'akov ka'asher Ra'am\"(Vayeitzei), He saw Ya'akov.   Whom did He see, according to Shmuel, based on the Pasuk \"Hash-m Yir'eh Lo ha'Seh\" (Vayeira)?\n(b) If according to Rebbi Yitzchak Nafcha, based on the Pasuk \"ve'Lakachta es Kesef ha'Kipurim\" (Ki Sissa), Hash-m saw the money that Yisrael donated towards the construction of the Mishkan, what did He see according to Rebbi Yochanan, based on the Pasuk \"be'Har Hash-m Yera'eh\" (Vayeira)?\n(c) Rebbi Ya'akov bar Idi and Rebbi Shmuel bar Nachmeni argue over the last two reasons presented by the earlier Amora'im.   Which is the preferred reason?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) Rava interprets 'Kapendarya' (a shortcut) in our Mishnah literally.   What does the word mean (See Hagahos Mahari Landa)?\n(b) According to Rav Chana bar Ada in the name of Rav Sama b'rei de'Rav Mari interprets is as an acronym.   What is it the acronym of?\n(c) On what condition does ...\n1. ... Rav Nachman Amar Rabah bar Avuhah permit making a Shul a shortcut?\n2. ... Rebbi Avahu permit it anyway?\n(d) Rav Chelbo Amar Rav Huna is the most lenient of all.   What does he say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Yehoshua ben Levi say about someone who spits in the Har ha'Bayis area nowadays?\n(b) On what grounds does Rava permit spitting in Shul nowadays? What does he compare it to?\n(c) How does Rav Papa, Ravina or Rav Ada bar Masna query Rava? What else might we compare it too le'Chumra?\n(d) How does Rava attempt to refute their Kashya?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) In the Beraisa cited by Rava, the Tana forbids a person to enter the Har ha'Bayis holding his staff, wearing his shoes, with his money wrapped in a cloth or with his money-belt slung behind him.   What does he say about ...\n1. ... making it a shortcut?\n2. ... spitting there?\n(b) From where does the Tana Kama learn the prohibition of wearing shoes in a holy place?\n(c) Why is spitting worse?\n(d) From which Pasuk in Megilas Esther does Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Yehudah learn the Kal va'Chomer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) How does Rav Ada bar Masna explain his Kashya on Rava?\n(b) How does Rava therefore re-learn his source for spitting in Shul (from one's home)?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 63,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) To explain why they answer \"Baruch Shem ... \" after each B'rachah in the Beis-ha'Mikdash and not 'Amen', we cite the Pasuk in Nechemyah \"Kumu Barchu es Hash-m Elokeichem min ha'Olam ad ha'Olam vi'Yevarchu Shem K'vodecha ... \".   What do we learn from there?\n(b) And what do we learn from the continuation of the Pasuk \"u'Meromam al Kol B'rachah u'Tehilah\"?\n(c) How does the Mevarech therefore conclude each B'rachah?\n(d) Why did they add 'min ha'Olam ve'ad ha'Olam' to the B'rachah?\n(e) What does this have to do with B'rachos?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) The Mishnah proves that one may greet using the Name of Hash-m from the Pasuk in Rus, where Bo'az said to Rus \"Hash-m Imachem\".   Why does the Tana see fit to add the Pasuk ...\n1. ... in Shoftim (where the angel said to Gid'on) \"Hash-m Im'cha Gibor ha'Chayil\"?\n2. ... in Mishlei \"Al Tavoz ki Zaknah Imecha\"?\n(b) What is this Pasuk coming to teach us?\n(c) And what do we learn from the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Eis La'asos la'Hashem, Heifeiru Torasecha\"?\n(d) One of the two ways of explaining the latter Pasuk is \"Eis La'asos la'Hashem\"(Hash-m sometimes needs to punish the people) because \"Heifeiru Torasecha\" (they have nullified the Torah).   What is the other?\n(e) What is an example of the latter?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What did Hillel ha'Zakein mean when he said ...\n1. ... 'be'Sha'as ha'Machnisin Pazer'?\n2. ... 'be'Sha'as ha'Mefazrim Kaneis'?\n(b) What is the reason for the latter statement?\n(c) What has this to do with the previous Pasuk \"Eis La'asos la'Hashem\")?\n(d) Similarly, what did Hillel say about a generation that ...\n1. ... loves the Torah, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Yesh Mefazer ve'Nosaf Od\"?\n2. ... does not love Torah?\n(e) On which Pasuk is the latter ruling base?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) What did bar Kapara say about ...\n1. ... goods that are cheap?\n2. ... a town where there is not a man (to teach Torah)?\n(b) What did Abaye extrapolate from there?\n(c) How do we answer the Kashya 'P'shita' (that one should not Pasken in front of one's Rebbe)?\n(d) Why should one then refrain from teaching?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What does the Pasuk in Mishlei mean when it says...\n1. ... \"be'Chol Derachecha D'eihu\"?\n2. ... \"ve'Hu Yeyasher Orchosecha\"?\n(b) What did bar Kapara comment on this Pasuk?\n(c) What did Rava comment on that (presumably based on the word \"be'Chol\")?\n(d) What is an example of 'Afilu li'Devar Aveirah\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) bar Kapara also maintains that a person should pick a profession that contains two specifications, one of them is that it should be clean.   What does 'clean' mean?\n(b) What is the other specification?\n(c) An example of this is 'Machta de'Talmiyusa'.   What profession is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) bar Kapara further advises a person not to invite too many friends to one's house, based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Ish Re'im Lehisro'ei'a\".   What does \"Lehisro'ei' mean?\n(b) What does Rebbi in a Beraisa, say about appointing a manager who lives in the house to look after one's affairs?\n(c) What was his source for this?\n(d) And how does he explain the juxtaposition of the Parshah of Nazir to that of Sotah in Parshas Naso?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) How does Chizkiyah b'rei de'Rebbi Parnach quoting Rebbi Yochanan explain the juxtaposition of the Pasuk \"ve'Ish es Kodashav lo Yih'yu' (in connection with T'rumos and Ma'asros to that of \"Ve'heivi ha'Ish es Ishto\" (in connection with Sotah [in Parshas Naso])?\n(b) What does he add to the D'rashah, based on the earlier Pasuk concerning the earlier Pasuk?\n(c) And what does Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak Darshen from the continuation of the Pasuk \"Ish asher Yiten la'Kohen lo Yih'yeh\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) When Rebbi Huna bar B'rechyah in the name of Rebbi Elazar ha'Kapar talks about someone who is 'Meshatef Hash-m be'Tza'aro', he might be referring to someone who recites a B'rachah \"Baruch dayan ha'Emes' over 'bad' things.   What else might he mean?\n(b) Based on the Pasuk in Iyov \"ve'Hayah Shakai be'Tzarecha ve'Chesef To'afos (doubled) lach\", what does he say will happen to someone who does this?\n(c) On what basis does Rebbi Shmuel bar Nachmeni learn from the same Pasuk that his Parnasah will fly in like a bird?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q10",
        "label": "10)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the Pasuk in Mishlei \"Hisrapisa be'Yom Tzarah, Tzarah Tzar ke'Chakeh\", what does Rebbi Tavi quoting Rebbi Yashiyah say about someone who is lax in 'words of Torah'?\n(b) And what does Rebbi Ami bar Masna quoting Shmuel add, bearing in mind that the Pasuk simply says \"Hisrapisa\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q11",
        "label": "11)",
        "text": "(a) Rav Safra quoted Rebbi Avahu, in connection with something that Rebbi Chananyah did.   Who was Rebbi Chananyah?\n(b) Which two things did he do after he went to the Golah?\n(c) What was wrong with that, based on the Pasuk in Re'ei \"le'Shichno Sidr'shu u'Va'sa Shamah\"?\n(d) What do Rebbi Yossi ben Kipar and the grandson of Zecharyah ben Kevutal have to do with the story?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q12",
        "label": "12)",
        "text": "(a) What did the two above Talmidei-Chachamim reply when Rebbi Chananyah asked them why they had come?\n(b) What title did he confer upon them, and what did he say their ancestors used to do?\n(c) What did Zecharyah ben Kevutal testify about himself, in connection with the Kohen Gadol on the night of Yom Kipur?\n(d) What happened in the ensuing Torah discussion?\n(e) What did they comment when he then accused of being men of no consequence?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q13",
        "label": "13)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Yossi ben Kipar and the grandson of Zecharyah ben Kevutal answer when Chananyah asked them why they were declaring Tahor whatever he declare Tamei, and permitting whatever he forbade.\n(b) What did he reply when they ...\n1. ... accused him of declaring leap-years and fixing Roshei Chodashim in Chutz la'Aretz?\n2. ... pointed out that when Rebbi Akiva went to Chutz la'Aretz, he left behind nobody who could compare with him?\n(c) And what did they mean when they countered 'Gedayim Na'aseh Teyashim'?\n(d) Why did they add the words 'Ba'alei Karnayim'?\n(e) What in fact did these 'goats with horns' instruct them to warn Chananyah?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q14",
        "label": "14)",
        "text": "(a) What did the two Talmidei Chachamim mean when, following instructions, they said to 'their brother in the Golah' 've'Im Lo, Ya'alu la'Har; Achiyah Yivneh Mizbe'ach, Chananya Yenagen be'Chinor'?\n(b) Why would specifically Chananya play the harp?\n(c) And what would all the people of the Golah proclaim?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q15",
        "label": "15)",
        "text": "(a) How did the people of the Golah react when they heard the stern warning of the two Talmidei-Chachamim?\n(b) What is the source of the Din that the leap-years and the months must be fixed in Eretz Yisrael (i.e. Yerushalayim')?\n(c) What does the Beraisa say about a Chacham declaring Tahor what his colleague has declared Tamei, or Mutar what he has declared Asur?\n(d) On what grounds did the two Talmidei-Chachamim do precisely that to Chananya?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q16",
        "label": "16)",
        "text": "(a) The Beraisa relates what happened when Rebbi Yehudah, Rebbi Yossi, Rebbi Nechemyah and Rebbi Eliezer b'Rebbi Yossi entered Kerem be'Yavneh. What is 'Kerem be'Yavneh'?\n(b) Why is it called a 'Kerem'?\n(c) Each one made a D'rashah.  What did all the D'rashos have in common?\n(d) What is 'Achsanyah' referring to?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q17",
        "label": "17)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yehudah was the first to Darshen.   Who conferred upon him the title 'Rosh ha'Medabrim be'Chol Makom'?\n(b) What did he do to earn it?\n(c) In whose honor did he now Darshen?\n(d) He learned a Kal va'Chomer from the Pasuk in Ki Sissa \"u'Moshe Yikach es ha'Ohel ve'Natah lo mi'Chutz la'Machaneh\".   How far outside the camp did he place the Ohel Mo'ed?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q18",
        "label": "18)",
        "text": "(a) He Darshened a Kal va'Chomer from the people who traveled the three Parsah to the Ohel Mo'ed.   What does the Pasuk refer to them as?\n(b) What is the Kal va'Chomer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q19",
        "label": "19)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yitzchak explains the Pasuk there \"ve'Diber Hash-m El Moshe Panim El Panim\" to mean that Hash-m said to Moshe 'Come, let us learn Halachah together'.   What is his alternative explanation?\n(b) In connection with the Pasuk there \"ve'Shav el ha'Machaneh\", how did Rebbi Avahu explain Hash-m's concern that Moshe should return to the camp?\n(c) What threat did Hash-m issue Moshe with should he decline to conform with Hash-m's request to return the Ohel Mo'ed to the camp?\n(d) What did Rava extrapolate from the conclusion of the Pasuk \"u'Meshorso Yehoshua ben Nun Na'ar Lo Yamush mi'Toch ha'Ohel\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q20",
        "label": "20)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yehudah now Darshens the Pasuk in Ki Savo \"Haskes u'Shema Yisrael, ha'Yom ha'Zeh Niheyesa le'Am\", again in honor of the Torah and those who study it. How does he explain the Pasuk, bearing in mind that the Torah had been given forty years earlier?\n(b) How does Rebbi Tanchum bar Chiya Ish K'far Acco support Rebbi Yehudah from someone who recites the Sh'ma twice a day and who forgets to it one night?\n(c) What is \"Haskeis\" the acronym of?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q21",
        "label": "21)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Yehudah's latter statement conforms with a statement of Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina.   What does Rebbi Yossi b'Rebbi Chanina say, based on the Pasuk in Yirmiyahu \"Cherev el ha'Badim ... \"?\n(b) How does he explain the next word in the Pasuk \"ve'Noalu\"?\n(c) And he bases this in turn, on the Pasuk in Beha'aloscha (in connection with the Lashon ha'Ra that Aharon and Miriam spoke about Moshe) \"asher No'alnu ... \" or from the Pasuk in Yeshayah \"No'alu Sarei Tzo'an\".   What does he learn from the next two words in the Pasuk in Beha'aloshca?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q22",
        "label": "22)",
        "text": "(a) Alternatively, Rebbi Yehudah explains the Pasuk in Ki Savo (\"Haskeis u'Shema\") as 'Katsu Atzmechem al Divrei Torah'.   What does he mean by that?\n(b) And we supprt this with a statement of Resh Lakish.   What did Resh Lakish say based on the Pasuk in Chukas \"Zos ha'Torah, Adam ki Yamus be'Ohel\"?\n(c) Another interpretation of \"Haskeis\" is that it is the acronym of 'Has (ve'achar-kach) Kateis', in keeping with a statement of Rava.   What did Rava say?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q23",
        "label": "23)",
        "text": "(a) Bei Rebbi Yanai Darshens the Pasuk in Mishlei \"For the juice of milk will produce butter, the juice of anger (Af), blood, and the juice of great anger (Apayim), arguments (in words of Torah)\".   How does he explain ...\n1. ... \" ... the juice of milk will produce butter\"?\n2. ... \"the juice of anger (Af), blood\"?\n3. ... \"the juice of great anger (Apayim), arguments \"?\n(b) We connect the latter explanation with a statement of Rebbi Yishmael in a Mishnah in Bava Basra.   What did he say there about someone who wishes to become wise?\n(c) Why is that?\n(d) To what does the Tana compare them?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q24",
        "label": "24)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Shmuel bar Nachmeni, still in honor of Torah and its Talmidim, explains the Pasuk there \"Im Navalta, be'Hisnasei\" to mean that a Talmid who causes himself embarrassment will eventually be elevated.   What does he mean by 'causes himself embarrassment'?\n(b) And how does he explain the continuation of the Pasuk \"ve'Im Zamosa, Yad le'Peh\"?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q25",
        "label": "25)",
        "text": "(a) The next Tana to begin his D'rashah 'in honor of the host' Rebbi Nechemyah, cited a Pasuk in Shmuel (in connection with King Shaul's instructions to the Keini).   Who were the 'Keini'?\n(b) What did Shaul instruct them to do and why?\n(c) On what grounds did he tell them to do so?\n(d) What Kal va'Chomer did Rebbi Nechemyah learn from there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q26",
        "label": "26)",
        "text": "(a) The third Tana, Rebbi Yossi, Darshened from a Pasuk in Ki Seitzei.   Why does the Pasuk command us not to reject ...\n1. ... an Edumite?\n2. ... an Egyptian?\n(b) Rebbi Yossi Darshened from the Pasuk in Vayigash that the Egyptians accepted our fathers in Egypt for their own benefit.   Which Pasuk in Vayigash?\n(c) What Kal va'Chomer did Rebbi Yossi learn from there?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q27",
        "label": "27)",
        "text": "(a) Rebbi Eliezer, son of Rebbi Yossi ha'Gelili, the last of the four Tana'im to begin in honor of the host, Darshened from a Pasuk in Shmuel, which discusses Hash-m's blessing of Oveid Edom ha'Giti, who housed the Aron (which neither eats nor drinks) for a few months.   What did he do for the Aron?\n(b) Based on Pesukim in Divrei ha'Yamim, what reward did Oveid Edom receive?\n(c) How does the Pasuk arrive at the number sixty-two?\n(d) What Kal va'Chomer did Rebbi Eliezer, son of Rebbi Yossi ha'Gelili make?"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "daf": 64,
    "questions": [
      {
        "id": "q1",
        "label": "1)",
        "text": "(a) What did Rebbi Avin ha'Levi mean when he said 'Kol ha'Dochek es ha'Sha'ah, ha'Sha'ah Dochkaso'?\n(b) Who is a prime example of the principle\n(c) And what did he mean when he added 'Kol ha'Nidcheh Mipnei ha'Sha'ah, Sha'ah Nidchis mi'Panav'?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q2",
        "label": "2)",
        "text": "(a) A prime example of the latter statement is Rav Yosef.   Why did they refer to Rav Yosef as 'Sinai' and Rabah as 'Oker Harim'?\n(b) When the question was put to the Chachamim of Eretz Yisrael which takes precedence, 'Sinai' or 'Oker Harim', what did they reply?\n(c) What reason did they give for their answer?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q3",
        "label": "3)",
        "text": "(a) What did the astrologers tell Rav Yosef?\n(b) Why did he therefore decline to become Rosh Yeshivah before Rabah (despite the Chachamim's answer to the above-mentioned She'eilah)?\n(c) For how long was ...\n1. ... Rabah Rosh Yeshivah?\n2. ... Rav Yosef Rosh Yeshivah?\n(d) What did Rav Yosef not do throughout the twenty-two years of Rabah's 'reign'?\n(e) Why is that?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q4",
        "label": "4)",
        "text": "(a) What is initially strange about the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Ya'ancha Hash-m be'Yom Tzarah, Yesagevcha Sheim Elokei Ya'akov\"?\n(b) Rebbi Avin ha'Levi explains it with the mantra (that is based on this Pasuk) 'The owner of the beam is the one who should bear the brunt of carrying it'.   What does he mean by that?\n(c) How does this explain the Pasuk?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q5",
        "label": "5)",
        "text": "(a) What does Rebbi Avin ha'Levi then say about someone who participates in a Se'udah at which a Talmid-Chacham is sitting?\n(b) From whereabouts in Parshas Yisro did he learn it?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q6",
        "label": "6)",
        "text": "(a) What distinction does Rebbi Avin ha'Levi furthermore draw between someone who parts from his friend with the words 'Lech be'Shalom' and 'Lech le'Shalom'?\n(b) If 'Lech le'Shalom' is what Yisro said to Moshe and he lived, to whom did David ha'Melech say \"Lech be'Shalom\"?\n(c) What subsequently happened to Avshalom?\n(d) Where was ...\n1. ... he going after taking leave of his father?\n2. ... Moshe go after taking leave of his father-in-law?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q7",
        "label": "7)",
        "text": "(a) The same Amora cites the Pasuk in Lech-L'cha \"ve'Atah Tavo el Avosecha be'Shalom\".   Who said it to whom?\n(b) What does he learn from there?\n(c) How does the Pasuk end?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q8",
        "label": "8)",
        "text": "(a) Based on the Pasuk in Tehilim \"Yeilchu me'Chayil el Chayil, Yera'eh el Elokim be'Tzi'on\", what did Rebbi Levi bar Cita say about someone who leaves the Beis-ha'Keneses and goes to the Beis-ha'Medrash to study Torah?\n(b) And, based on the same Pasuk, what did Rebbi Chiya bar Ashi quoting Rav say about Talmidei-Chachamim in general?"
      },
      {
        "id": "q9",
        "label": "9)",
        "text": "(a) What is the first Pasuk in the well-known saying of Rebbi Elazar quoting Rebbi Chanina with which Berachos, Nidah, Yevamos and Kerisus ends?\n(b) What kind of blessing do Talmidei-Chachamim bring upon the world?\n(c) In the source Pasuk of this statement \" ... ve'Chol Banayich Limudei Hash-m ... \", how does he interpret \"Banayich\"?\n(d) Which two B'rachos will Hash-m bestow upon all those who love His Torah?\n(e) Which two assets will He ultimately bestow upon His people?"
      }
